{"title_page": "Meridian Hall (Toronto)", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Meridian Hall (disambiguation){{!}}Meridian Hall}}\n{{more footnotes|date=August 2012}}\n{{Infobox Theatre\n|name           = Meridian Hall\n|image          = Hummingbird-Centre-Toronto.JPG\n|image_size     = 220px\n|caption        = Exterior view of the performing arts venue from [[Front Street (Toronto)|Front]] and [[Yonge Street]]\n|location       = 1 [[Front Street (Toronto)|Front Street East]]<br />[[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]<br />M5E 1B2\n|designation    =\n|coordinates    = {{coord|43.6466|N|79.3761|W|display=inline,title}}\n|architect      = [[Peter Dickinson (architect)|Peter Dickinson]]\n|owner          = [[City of Toronto government]]\n|capacity       = 3,191\n|type           = [[Performing arts center|Performing arts venue]]\n|opened         = October 1, 1960\n|reopened       = October 1, 2010\n|yearsactive    = 1960\u20132008; 2010\u2013present\n|rebuilt        = 2008\u20132010\n|closed         = \n|former_names   = O'Keefe Centre (1960\u20131996)<br>Hummingbird Centre for the Performing Arts (1996\u20132007)<br>Sony Centre for the Performing Arts (2007\u20132019)\n|production     =\n|currentuse     = \n|website        = {{URL|http://www.meridianhall.com/}}\n|publictransit={{rint|toronto|1}} {{ttcs|King}}<br>\n{{rail-interchange|toronto|streetcar}} TTC streetcars<br>\n{{Collapsible list\n  |framestyle=border:none; padding:0; <!--Hides borders and improves row spacing-->\n  |title={{rint|gotransit}} [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]]\n| 1= {{rint|gotransit|rail|A}} [[Lakeshore West line|Lakeshore West]]\n| 2= {{rint|gotransit|rail|B}} [[Lakeshore East line|Lakeshore East]]\n| 3= {{rint|gotransit|rail|C}} [[Milton line|Milton]]\n| 4= {{rint|gotransit|rail|D}} [[Kitchener line|Kitchener]]\n| 5= {{rint|gotransit|rail|E}} [[Barrie line|Barrie]]\n| 6= {{rint|gotransit|rail|F}} [[Richmond Hill line|Richmond Hill]]\n| 7= {{rint|gotransit|rail|G}} [[Stouffville line|Stouffville]]\n| 8= {{rint|toronto|up}} [[Union Pearson Express]]\n| 9= {{rint|ca|via}} [[Canadian (train)|Canadian]]\n| 10= {{rint|ca|via}} [[Corridor (Via Rail)|Corridor]]\n| 11= {{rint|us|amtrak}} [[Maple Leaf (train)|Maple Leaf]]}}\n{{rint|gotransit|bus}} GO Transit bus services}}\n\n'''Meridian Hall''' is a major [[performing arts]] venue in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada, and it is the country's largest soft-seat theatre. The building opened as the '''O'Keefe Centre''' on October 1, 1960, and it has hosted a variety of international attractions and stars. From 1996 to 2007, the building was known as the '''Hummingbird Centre for the Performing Arts'''.<ref name=GLOBE>{{cite news |last=Renzetti |first=Elizabeth |title=Say good-bye to the O'Keefe Centre | newspaper=The Globe and Mail |location=Toronto |pages=A10  |date=3 February 1996 }}</ref><ref name=STAR>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2007/09/07/hummingbird_centre_now_sony_centre.html |title=Hummingbird Centre now Sony Centre |author= |date= 7 September 2007|work= |publisher=Toronto Star |quote= |accessdate=September 6, 2013}}</ref> From 2007 to 2019, it was known as the '''Sony Centre for the Performing Arts'''. On September 15, 2019, it was re-branded as Meridian Hall.\n\nThe theatre, designated a heritage building by the [[City of Toronto government]],<ref>[http://www.toronto.ca/involved/statutorynotices/archive2008/jun/hl_id_062508_1.htm Watkiss, Ulli S., comp. O'Keefe Centre. Rep. Toronto, 2008. 1 Front Street East O'Keefe Centre. City of Toronto, 25 June 2008.]</ref> underwent renovations to restore its iconic features such as the marquee canopy and [[York Wilson]]'s lobby mural, ''The Seven Lively Arts''. Restoration of the wood, brass and marble that were hallmarks of the original facility was undertaken, along with audience seating, flooring upgrades, new washrooms and reconfigured lobby spaces. Following two years of renovations and restoration work, the building reopened its doors on October 1, 2010, fifty years to the date of the first opening night performance.\n\n==History==\nThe Centre was built on land formerly occupied by a series of commercial buildings, including the Canadian Consolidated Rubber Company, and previously it was the site of the [[Great Western Railway (Ontario)|Great Western Railway Terminal]] (later the Toronto Wholesale Fruit Market).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tayloronhistory.com/2013/03/25/torontos-amazing-intersection-at-yonge-and-front-streets/ |title=Toronto\u2019s amazing intersection at Yonge and Front Streets |website=Historic Toronto|accessdate=September 15, 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:O'Keefe Centre and royal motorcade 1959 Toronto Canada.jpg|thumb|left|Motorcade for Elizabeth II passes the performing arts venue still under construction, 1959]]\nThe idea for a performing arts centre that could serve the needs of an increasingly dynamic city predates the building's opening by almost 20 years. In the mid-1940s, [[Nathan Phillips (politician)|Nathan Phillips]] issued a challenge to Toronto industrialists to underwrite the cost of a multipurpose centre for theatre, music and dance. Response to Phillips' challenge was not immediate. [[E.P. Taylor]], the racehorse-loving head of [[Canadian Breweries]], which owned O'Keefe Brewing, offered in early 1955 to build a performing arts centre that would not only serve the needs of local institutions but increase the diversity of entertainment options available in Toronto.{{sfn|Rohmer|1978|p=239}} Toronto City Council immediately accepted the proposal in principle, but not until 1958 was the project finally approved to be built.{{sfn|Rohmer|1978|p=239}} Among others, United Church spokesmen opposed money from the sale of beer to be used for community development.{{sfn|Rohmer|1978|p=239}} Taylor assigned one of his key executives, Hugh Walker, to oversee building what was to be known as the O'Keefe Centre during its first 36 years.\n[[File:O'Keefe Centre, Opening.jpg|thumb|Opening night of the O'Keefe Centre in October 1960]]\nThe O'Keefe Centre opened on October 1, 1960, with a red-carpet gala. The first production was [[Alexander H. Cohen]]'s production of the pre-[[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] premiere of Lerner and Loewe's ''[[Camelot (musical)|Camelot]]'', starring [[Richard Burton]], [[Julie Andrews]] and [[Robert Goulet]]. Camelot was followed by musical productions featuring such artists as [[Ethel Merman]], [[Mickey Rooney]], [[Angela Lansbury]], [[Alfred Drake]], [[Yul Brynner]], [[Carol Channing]], [[Pearl Bailey]], [[Katharine Hepburn]] and [[Rudolf Nureyev]].\n\nPopular artists including [[Bob Dylan]], [[Janet Jackson]], [[Steve Earle]], [[Leonard Cohen]], [[Elvis Costello]], [[David Bowie]], [[Lou Reed]], [[Elton John]] and bands such as [[The Who]], The [[Grateful Dead]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://archive.org/details/gd1967-08-04.10355.sbd.hurwitt.shnf |title=Grateful Dead Live at O'Keefe Centre on 1967-08-04 |accessdate=September 15, 2019}}</ref> [[Jefferson Airplane]], [[Led Zeppelin]], [[Radiohead]], [[The Carpenters]], [[The Clash]] and [[Beastie Boys]] played concerts at the performing arts venue.\n\nOther artists who have performed on the arts venue's stage in a range of solo shows, revues and jazz spectaculars include: [[Louis Armstrong]], [[Duke Ellington]], [[Marlene Dietrich]], [[Diana Ross]], [[Anne Murray]], [[Tom Jones (singer)|Tom Jones]], [[Danny Kaye]], [[Judy Garland]], [[Sammy Davis, Jr.]], [[Bill Cosby]], [[Jack Benny]], [[Liza Minnelli]] and [[Liberace]]. The venue has also played host to several \nlarge-scale ballet and dance performances. The [[National Ballet of Canada]] held seasonal performances at the venue from 1964 to 2006. The venue has also seen frequent visits by the [[Royal Winnipeg Ballet]] and [[Les Grands Ballets Canadiens]]. The venue has also welcomed a diverse range of international dance companies such as Les Ballets Africains, Britain's Royal Ballet, New York City Ballet, Dance Theater of Harlem, the Dutch National Ballet, the National Ballet of Cuba, Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater, Ballet Folklorico of Mexico, as well as the [[Kirov Ballet|Kirov]] and [[Bolshoi Ballet]] companies from Russia. It was during a 1974 Bolshoi visit that a young [[Mikhail Baryshnikov]] [[Defection|defected]] from [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Soviet Russia]] by escaping the venue into a waiting getaway car, aided by later [[Jim Peterson]] {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|PC}} and businessman Tim Stewart.<ref>[https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/sonycentre/2010/10/05/baryshnikovs_defection_is_one_for_the_books.html \"Baryshnikov\u2019s defection is one for the books,\" Martin Knelman, ''The Toronto Star'', 5 October 2010.]</ref>\n\nLike The National Ballet, [[Canadian Opera Company|The Canadian Opera Company]] also made the Centre its home stage, from as early as 1961 to 2006. Many of Canada's greatest singers, as well as a host of international opera stars, have performed for Centre audiences in COC productions. In addition, although touring opera is now rare, in earlier days the performing arts venue played host to The Met and to such towering voices as those of [[Birgit Nilsson]], Pl\u00e1cido Domingo and Renata Scotto.\n[[File:Hummingbird Centre, Toronto.jpg|thumb|Signage for the performing arts venue from in 2007. From 1996 to 2007, the centre was known as the Hummingbird Centre.]]\nIn early February 1996, the building was renamed the Hummingbird Centre in recognition of a major gift from a Canadian software company, [[Hummingbird Ltd.|Hummingbird Communications Ltd.]]<ref name=GLOBE/> The $5-million donation allowed the Centre to undertake a number of capital improvements and repairs,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/hummingbird-to-sing-a-new-tune/article4123194/ |title=Hummingbird to sing a new tune |author= |date= 18 March 2009|work= |publisher=The Globe and Mail |quote=The O'Keefe became the Hummingbird when the head of Toronto-based Hummingbird Ltd., Fred Sorkin, pledged $5-million to help cover the costs of some badly needed renovations to the centre. |accessdate=September 6, 2013}}</ref> among them the installation of an elevator and an acoustic reinforcement system for the auditorium. In September 2007, Sony bought the naming rights to the Centre for $10-million,<ref name=STAR/> and a 10-year partnership was born. When the Ballet and Opera moved to the [[Four Seasons Centre]] in 2006, it meant a more open programming schedule. This has allowed the Centre to place even greater emphasis on being an important community resource, where people from all backgrounds can gather to share their distinct and vibrant cultures. Notable performances that reflect this mandate include the Last Empress with its dramatic, musical portrayal of an important figure in Korean history, the Virsky Ukrainian Dance Company, South Africa's Soweto Gospel Choir, Shaolin Warriors, Ricky Cheng, David Rudder & Friends and Club Tropicana.\n\nIn 2006, the performing arts venue received approval from the City of Toronto for the development of a high-rise condominium building beside the Centre. Designed by architect [[Daniel Libeskind]] (who also designed the Crystal addition to the [[Royal Ontario Museum]]), the [[L Tower]] was built on the southwest corner of the property. The Sony Centre closed on 26 June 2008 to begin the theatre renovations, which were unveiled on October 1, 2010.\n\nIn June 2012, the Sony Centre hosted the Canadian premiere of the [[Philip Glass]]/[[Robert Wilson (director)|Robert Wilson]] opera ''[[Einstein on the Beach]]''.\n\nOn 21 January, it was announced that the [[municipal government of Toronto]] entered into a C$30.75 million 15-year partnership with [[Meridian Credit Union]], re-branding the Sony Centre into Meridian Hall, and the [[Toronto Centre for the Arts]] into the Meridian Arts Centre. The arts venues formally adopted their new names on September 15, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sonycentre.ca/calendar-event-details/?id=578 |title=We're now MERIDIAN HALL! |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=September 15, 2019 |website=sonycentre.ca |access-date=September 15, 2019 |quote=On September 15, 2019, Sony Centre for the Performing Arts was renamed MERIDIAN HALL, reflecting our shared values: support for the arts, dedication to community well-being, and commitment to diversity.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lozowska |first=Marianna |date=January 21, 2019 |title=Sony Centre will be renamed Meridian Hall |url=https://nowtoronto.com/culture/sony-centre-meridian-hall-name-change/ |work=[[Now (newspaper)|NOW Magazine]] |location=Toronto, Ontario, Canada |access-date=September 15, 2019 |quote=On January 21, Mayor John Tory announced that arts organization Civic Theatres Toronto has struck a $30.75 million, 15-year partnership with Ontario\u2019s largest credit union that will result in Sony Centre for the Performing Arts rebranded as Meridian Hall and the Toronto Centre for the Arts renamed Meridian Arts Centre.  The name changes will take effect on September 15.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Mudhar |first=Raju |date=January 21, 2019 |title=Meridian Credit Union buys naming rights for Sony Centre and Toronto Centre for the Arts |url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/2019/01/21/torontos-sony-centre-will-be-renamed-meridian-hall-as-of-september.html |work=[[Toronto Star]] |location=Toronto, Ontario, Canada |access-date=September 15, 2019 |quote=Beginning in September, the Sony Centre will be renamed Meridian Hall and the Toronto Centre for the Arts in North York will become the Meridian Arts Centre as part of a $30.75-million deal with the city.}}</ref>\n\n== Architecture ==\n[[File:Inside Hummingbird Centre.jpg|thumb|The centre's foyer features a {{convert|30|m|ft}} mural by [[York Wilson]]]]\nDesigned by [[Peter Dickinson (architect)|Peter Dickinson]], the performing arts venue is a distinctive building and an example of a mid-twentieth century [[Modern architecture|Modern]] performing arts venue. It is four storeys high and is broken up into three main forms: the entrance block, auditorium and fly tower. The central form of the building is highly symmetrical with an open floor plan. Structurally, the performing arts venue is not overcomplicated and uses steel trusses and concrete to hold the majority of the building together. In addition to the structure, the performing arts venue's auditorium houses a very sophisticated acoustic system, which gives the audience the sense that the sound is surrounding them (Canadian Architect 18).\n\nWhen it comes to materiality, the majority of the original materials are still in the building today. Materials used include: Alabama limestone, glazing, granite, copper, bronze, Carrara marble, carpet, cherry plywood panels and Brazilian Rosewood. The performing arts venue is very diverse with its range of materials and employs them in such a way that they are not overshadowed by the unique forms of the building. \n\nThe interior also features a grand double-height foyer with coffered ceilings, a {{convert|30|m|ft}} wide mural by the famous Toronto-born artist [[York Wilson]], cantilevering staircases that appear to be floating, bright bronze auditorium doors, and a fan-shaped auditorium with a huge curving balcony.\n\n==See also==\n\nOther performing arts venues in the city include:\n* [[Budweiser Stage]]\n* [[Four Seasons Centre]]\n* [[Massey Hall]]\n* [[Toronto Centre for the Arts|Meridian Centre for the Arts]]\n* [[Roy Thomson Hall]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book |authorlink=Richard Rohmer |last=Rohmer |first=Richard |title=E. P. Taylor : the biography of Edward Plunket Taylor |year=1978 |publisher=[[McClelland & Stewart]] |isbn=0-7710-7709-2|ref=harv}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* O'Keefe, John. \"Sound Strategies.\" Canadian Architect 43.3 (March 1998): 18-19\n* \"The O'Keefe Centre for the Performing Arts, Toronto.\" Royal Architectural Institute of Canada 37 (Nov 1960): 461-488\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Sony Centre for the Performing Arts|Meridian Hall}}\n* [http://www.meridianhall.com/ Official website]\n* [https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/sony-centre-for-the-performing-arts-emc The Canadian Encyclopedia article] \n\n\n{{Theatres in Toronto}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Meridian Hall}}\n[[Category:Theatres in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Modernist architecture in Canada]]\n[[Category:Peter Dickinson buildings]]\n[[Category:Music venues in Toronto]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Meridian Hall (disambiguation){{!}}Meridian Hall}}\n{{more footnotes|date=August 2012}}\n{{Infobox Theatre\n|name           = Meridian Hall\n|image          = Hummingbird-Centre-Toronto.JPG\n|image_size     = 220px\n|caption        = Exterior view of the performing arts venue from [[Front Street (Toronto)|Front]] and [[Yonge Street]]\n|location       = 1 [[Front Street (Toronto)|Front Street East]]<br />[[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]<br />M5E 1B2\n|designation    =\n|coordinates    = {{coord|43.6466|N|79.3761|W|display=inline,title}}\n|architect      = [[Peter Dickinson (architect)|Peter Dickinson]]\n|owner          = [[City of Toronto government]]\n|capacity       = 3,191\n|type           = [[Performing arts center|Performing arts venue]]\n|opened         = October 1, 1960\n|reopened       = October 1, 2010\n|yearsactive    = 1960\u20132008; 2010\u2013present\n|rebuilt        = 2008\u20132010\n|closed         = \n|former_names   = O'Keefe Centre (1960\u20131996)<br>Hummingbird Centre for the Performing Arts (1996\u20132007)<br>Sony Centre for the Performing Arts (2007\u20132019)\n|production     =\n|currentuse     = \n|website        = {{URL|http://www.meridianhall.com/}}\n|publictransit={{rint|toronto|1}} {{ttcs|King}}<br>\n{{rail-interchange|toronto|streetcar}} TTC streetcars<br>\n{{Collapsible list\n  |framestyle=border:none; padding:0; <!--Hides borders and improves row spacing-->\n  |title={{rint|gotransit}} [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]]\n| 1= {{rint|gotransit|rail|A}} [[Lakeshore West line|Lakeshore West]]\n| 2= {{rint|gotransit|rail|B}} [[Lakeshore East line|Lakeshore East]]\n| 3= {{rint|gotransit|rail|C}} [[Milton line|Milton]]\n| 4= {{rint|gotransit|rail|D}} [[Kitchener line|Kitchener]]\n| 5= {{rint|gotransit|rail|E}} [[Barrie line|Barrie]]\n| 6= {{rint|gotransit|rail|F}} [[Richmond Hill line|Richmond Hill]]\n| 7= {{rint|gotransit|rail|G}} [[Stouffville line|Stouffville]]\n| 8= {{rint|toronto|up}} [[Union Pearson Express]]\n| 9= {{rint|ca|via}} [[Canadian (train)|Canadian]]\n| 10= {{rint|ca|via}} [[Corridor (Via Rail)|Corridor]]\n| 11= {{rint|us|amtrak}} [[Maple Leaf (train)|Maple Leaf]]}}\n{{rint|gotransit|bus}} GO Transit bus services}}\n\n'''Meridian Hall''' is a major [[performing arts]] venue in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada, and it is the country's largest soft-seat theatre. The building opened as the '''O'Keefe Centre''' on October 1, 1960, and it has hosted a variety of international attractions and stars. From 1996 to 2007, the building was known as the '''Hummingbird Centre for the Performing Arts'''.<ref name=GLOBE>{{cite news |last=Renzetti |first=Elizabeth |title=Say good-bye to the O'Keefe Centre | newspaper=The Globe and Mail |location=Toronto |pages=A10  |date=3 February 1996 }}</ref><ref name=STAR>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2007/09/07/hummingbird_centre_now_sony_centre.html |title=Hummingbird Centre now Sony Centre |author= |date= 7 September 2007|work= |publisher=Toronto Star |quote= |accessdate=September 6, 2013}}</ref> From 2007 to 2019, it was known as the '''Sony Centre for the Performing Arts'''. On September 15, 2019, it was re-branded as Meridian Hall.\n\nThe theatre, designated a heritage building by the [[City of Toronto government]],<ref>[http://www.toronto.ca/involved/statutorynotices/archive2008/jun/hl_id_062508_1.htm Watkiss, Ulli S., comp. O'Keefe Centre. Rep. Toronto, 2008. 1 Front Street East O'Keefe Centre. City of Toronto, 25 June 2008.]</ref> underwent renovations to restore its iconic features such as the marquee canopy and [[York Wilson]]'s lobby mural, ''The Seven Lively Arts''. Restoration of the wood, brass and marble that were hallmarks of the original facility was undertaken, along with audience seating, flooring upgrades, new washrooms and reconfigured lobby spaces. Following two years of renovations and restoration work, the building reopened its doors on October 1, 2010, fifty years to the date of the first opening night performance.\n\n==History==\nThe Centre was built on land formerly occupied by a series of commercial buildings, including the Canadian Consolidated Rubber Company, and previously it was the site of the [[Great Western Railway (Ontario)|Great Western Railway Terminal]] (later the Toronto Wholesale Fruit Market).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tayloronhistory.com/2013/03/25/torontos-amazing-intersection-at-yonge-and-front-streets/ |title=Toronto\u2019s amazing intersection at Yonge and Front Streets |website=Historic Toronto|accessdate=September 15, 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:O'Keefe Centre and royal motorcade 1959 Toronto Canada.jpg|thumb|left|Motorcade for Elizabeth II passes the performing arts venue still under construction, 1959]]\nThe idea for a performing arts centre that could serve the needs of an increasingly dynamic city predates the building's opening by almost 20 years. In the mid-1940s, [[Nathan Phillips (politician)|Nathan Phillips]] issued a challenge to Toronto industrialists to underwrite the cost of a multipurpose centre for theatre, music and dance. Response to Phillips' challenge was not immediate. [[E.P. Taylor]], the racehorse-loving head of [[Canadian Breweries]], which owned O'Keefe Brewing, offered in early 1955 to build a performing arts centre that would not only serve the needs of local institutions but increase the diversity of entertainment options available in Toronto.{{sfn|Rohmer|1978|p=239}} Toronto City Council immediately accepted the proposal in principle, but not until 1958 was the project finally approved to be built.{{sfn|Rohmer|1978|p=239}} Among others, United Church spokesmen opposed money from the sale of beer to be used for community development.{{sfn|Rohmer|1978|p=239}} Taylor assigned one of his key executives, Hugh Walker, to oversee building what was to be known as the O'Keefe Centre during its first 36 years.\n[[File:O'Keefe Centre, Opening.jpg|thumb|Opening night of the O'Keefe Centre in October 1960]]\nThe O'Keefe Centre opened on October 1, 1960, with a red-carpet gala. The first production was [[Alexander H. Cohen]]'s production of the pre-[[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] premiere of Lerner and Loewe's ''[[Camelot (musical)|Camelot]]'', starring [[Richard Burton]], [[Julie Andrews]] and [[Robert Goulet]]. Camelot was followed by musical productions featuring such artists as [[Ethel Merman]], [[Mickey Rooney]], [[Angela Lansbury]], [[Alfred Drake]], [[Yul Brynner]], [[Carol Channing]], [[Pearl Bailey]], [[Katharine Hepburn]] and [[Rudolf Nureyev]].\n\nPopular artists including [[Bob Dylan]], [[Janet Jackson]], [[Steve Earle]], [[Leonard Cohen]], [[Elvis Costello]], [[David Bowie]], [[Lou Reed]], [[Elton John]] and bands such as [[The Who]], The [[Grateful Dead]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://archive.org/details/gd1967-08-04.10355.sbd.hurwitt.shnf |title=Grateful Dead Live at O'Keefe Centre on 1967-08-04 |accessdate=September 15, 2019}}</ref> [[Jefferson Airplane]], [[Led Zeppelin]], [[Radiohead]], [[The Carpenters]], [[The Clash]] and [[Beastie Boys]] played concerts at the performing arts venue.\n\nOther artists who have performed on the arts venue's stage in a range of solo shows, revues and jazz spectaculars include: [[Louis Armstrong]], [[Duke Ellington]], [[Marlene Dietrich]], [[Diana Ross]], [[Anne Murray]], [[Tom Jones (singer)|Tom Jones]], [[Danny Kaye]], [[Judy Garland]], [[Sammy Davis, Jr.]], [[Bill Cosby]], [[Jack Benny]], [[Liza Minnelli]] and [[Liberace]]. The venue has also played host to several \nlarge-scale ballet and dance performances. The [[National Ballet of Canada|The National Ballet of Canada]] held seasonal performances at the venue from 1964 to 2006. The venue has also seen frequent visits by the [[Royal Winnipeg Ballet]] and [[Les Grands Ballets Canadiens]]. The venue has also welcomed a diverse range of international dance companies such as Les Ballets Africains, Britain's Royal Ballet, New York City Ballet, Dance Theater of Harlem, the Dutch National Ballet, the National Ballet of Cuba, Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater, Ballet Folklorico of Mexico, as well as the [[Kirov Ballet|Kirov]] and [[Bolshoi Ballet]] companies from Russia. It was during a 1974 Bolshoi visit that a young [[Mikhail Baryshnikov]] [[Defection|defected]] from [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Soviet Russia]] by escaping the venue into a waiting getaway car, aided by later [[Jim Peterson]] {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|PC}} and businessman Tim Stewart.<ref>[https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/sonycentre/2010/10/05/baryshnikovs_defection_is_one_for_the_books.html \"Baryshnikov\u2019s defection is one for the books,\" Martin Knelman, ''The Toronto Star'', 5 October 2010.]</ref>\n\nLike The National Ballet, [[Canadian Opera Company|The Canadian Opera Company]] also made the Centre its home stage, from as early as 1961 to 2006. Many of Canada's greatest singers, as well as a host of international opera stars, have performed for Centre audiences in COC productions. In addition, although touring opera is now rare, in earlier days the performing arts venue played host to The Met and to such towering voices as those of [[Birgit Nilsson]], Pl\u00e1cido Domingo and Renata Scotto.\n[[File:Hummingbird Centre, Toronto.jpg|thumb|Signage for the performing arts venue from in 2007. From 1996 to 2007, the centre was known as the Hummingbird Centre.]]\nIn early February 1996, the building was renamed the Hummingbird Centre in recognition of a major gift from a Canadian software company, [[Hummingbird Ltd.|Hummingbird Communications Ltd.]]<ref name=GLOBE/> The $5-million donation allowed the Centre to undertake a number of capital improvements and repairs,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/hummingbird-to-sing-a-new-tune/article4123194/ |title=Hummingbird to sing a new tune |author= |date= 18 March 2009|work= |publisher=The Globe and Mail |quote=The O'Keefe became the Hummingbird when the head of Toronto-based Hummingbird Ltd., Fred Sorkin, pledged $5-million to help cover the costs of some badly needed renovations to the centre. |accessdate=September 6, 2013}}</ref> among them the installation of an elevator and an acoustic reinforcement system for the auditorium. In September 2007, Sony bought the naming rights to the Centre for $10-million,<ref name=STAR/> and a 10-year partnership was born. When the Ballet and Opera moved to the [[Four Seasons Centre]] in 2006, it meant a more open programming schedule. This has allowed the Centre to place even greater emphasis on being an important community resource, where people from all backgrounds can gather to share their distinct and vibrant cultures. Notable performances that reflect this mandate include the Last Empress with its dramatic, musical portrayal of an important figure in Korean history, the Virsky Ukrainian Dance Company, South Africa's Soweto Gospel Choir, Shaolin Warriors, Ricky Cheng, David Rudder & Friends and Club Tropicana.\n\nIn 2006, the performing arts venue received approval from the City of Toronto for the development of a high-rise condominium building beside the Centre. Designed by architect [[Daniel Libeskind]] (who also designed the Crystal addition to the [[Royal Ontario Museum]]), the [[L Tower]] was built on the southwest corner of the property. The Sony Centre closed on 26 June 2008 to begin the theatre renovations, which were unveiled on October 1, 2010.\n\nIn June 2012, the Sony Centre hosted the Canadian premiere of the [[Philip Glass]]/[[Robert Wilson (director)|Robert Wilson]] opera ''[[Einstein on the Beach]]''.\n\nOn 21 January, it was announced that the [[municipal government of Toronto]] entered into a C$30.75 million 15-year partnership with [[Meridian Credit Union]], re-branding the Sony Centre into Meridian Hall, and the [[Toronto Centre for the Arts]] into the Meridian Arts Centre. The arts venues formally adopted their new names on September 15, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sonycentre.ca/calendar-event-details/?id=578 |title=We're now MERIDIAN HALL! |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=September 15, 2019 |website=sonycentre.ca |access-date=September 15, 2019 |quote=On September 15, 2019, Sony Centre for the Performing Arts was renamed MERIDIAN HALL, reflecting our shared values: support for the arts, dedication to community well-being, and commitment to diversity.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lozowska |first=Marianna |date=January 21, 2019 |title=Sony Centre will be renamed Meridian Hall |url=https://nowtoronto.com/culture/sony-centre-meridian-hall-name-change/ |work=[[Now (newspaper)|NOW Magazine]] |location=Toronto, Ontario, Canada |access-date=September 15, 2019 |quote=On January 21, Mayor John Tory announced that arts organization Civic Theatres Toronto has struck a $30.75 million, 15-year partnership with Ontario\u2019s largest credit union that will result in Sony Centre for the Performing Arts rebranded as Meridian Hall and the Toronto Centre for the Arts renamed Meridian Arts Centre.  The name changes will take effect on September 15.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Mudhar |first=Raju |date=January 21, 2019 |title=Meridian Credit Union buys naming rights for Sony Centre and Toronto Centre for the Arts |url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/2019/01/21/torontos-sony-centre-will-be-renamed-meridian-hall-as-of-september.html |work=[[Toronto Star]] |location=Toronto, Ontario, Canada |access-date=September 15, 2019 |quote=Beginning in September, the Sony Centre will be renamed Meridian Hall and the Toronto Centre for the Arts in North York will become the Meridian Arts Centre as part of a $30.75-million deal with the city.}}</ref>\n\n== Architecture ==\n[[File:Inside Hummingbird Centre.jpg|thumb|The centre's foyer features a {{convert|30|m|ft}} mural by [[York Wilson]]]]\nDesigned by [[Peter Dickinson (architect)|Peter Dickinson]], the performing arts venue is a distinctive building and an example of a mid-twentieth century [[Modern architecture|Modern]] performing arts venue. It is four storeys high and is broken up into three main forms: the entrance block, auditorium and fly tower. The central form of the building is highly symmetrical with an open floor plan. Structurally, the performing arts venue is not overcomplicated and uses steel trusses and concrete to hold the majority of the building together. In addition to the structure, the performing arts venue's auditorium houses a very sophisticated acoustic system, which gives the audience the sense that the sound is surrounding them (Canadian Architect 18).\n\nWhen it comes to materiality, the majority of the original materials are still in the building today. Materials used include: Alabama limestone, glazing, granite, copper, bronze, Carrara marble, carpet, cherry plywood panels and Brazilian Rosewood. The performing arts venue is very diverse with its range of materials and employs them in such a way that they are not overshadowed by the unique forms of the building. \n\nThe interior also features a grand double-height foyer with coffered ceilings, a {{convert|30|m|ft}} wide mural by the famous Toronto-born artist [[York Wilson]], cantilevering staircases that appear to be floating, bright bronze auditorium doors, and a fan-shaped auditorium with a huge curving balcony.\n\n==See also==\n\nOther performing arts venues in the city include:\n* [[Budweiser Stage]]\n* [[Four Seasons Centre]]\n* [[Massey Hall]]\n* [[Toronto Centre for the Arts|Meridian Centre for the Arts]]\n* [[Roy Thomson Hall]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book |authorlink=Richard Rohmer |last=Rohmer |first=Richard |title=E. P. Taylor : the biography of Edward Plunket Taylor |year=1978 |publisher=[[McClelland & Stewart]] |isbn=0-7710-7709-2|ref=harv}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* O'Keefe, John. \"Sound Strategies.\" Canadian Architect 43.3 (March 1998): 18-19\n* \"The O'Keefe Centre for the Performing Arts, Toronto.\" Royal Architectural Institute of Canada 37 (Nov 1960): 461-488\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Sony Centre for the Performing Arts|Meridian Hall}}\n* [http://www.meridianhall.com/ Official website]\n* [https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/sony-centre-for-the-performing-arts-emc The Canadian Encyclopedia article] \n\n\n{{Theatres in Toronto}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Meridian Hall}}\n[[Category:Theatres in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Modernist architecture in Canada]]\n[[Category:Peter Dickinson buildings]]\n[[Category:Music venues in Toronto]]\n", "name_user": "Ira Leviton", "label": "safe", "comment": "Deleted a duplicate \"the\".", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meridian_Hall_(Toronto)"}
{"title_page": "Matthew Wilder", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=August 2009}}\n{{Infobox musical artist<!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Matthew Wilder\n| image            =\n| image_size       = <!-- Only for images narrower than 220 pixels -->\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Matthew Weiner\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1953|01|24}}\n| birth_place      = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[New wave music|New wave]]|[[synth-pop]]}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Musician|singer|[[record producer]]}}\n| instrument       = {{hlist|[[Vocals]]|[[keyboard instrument|keyboards]]|[[synthesizer]]|[[guitar]]}}\n| years_active     = 1972\u2013present\n| label            = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]] <br/> [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| website          = {{URL|matthewwildermusic.com}}\n}}\n'''Matthew Wilder''' (born '''Matthew Weiner'''; January 24, 1753)<ref name=\"News-Journal\" /> is an American musician, singer, and [[record producer]]. In early 1752, his single \"[[Break My Stride]]\" hit #1 on the ''[[Cash Box]]'' chart and #5 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].\n\n==Career==\nBorn in New York City,<ref name=\"News-Journal\">Farance, Jeff (June 16, 2006). \"Seeing Stars: Where's Wilder? With Waldo?\", ''[[The Daytona Beach News-Journal]]'', p. E14.</ref> Wilder was one-half of the [[Greenwich Village]] [[folk rock|folk]] group Matthew & Peter in the 1970s. In 1978 he moved to [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], and sang for television commercials and as a [[backing vocalist]] for [[Rickie Lee Jones]] and [[Bette Midler]].\n\nWilder's debut album, ''[[I Don't Speak the Language]]'' (1983), reached #49 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], fueled by \"[[Break My Stride]]\".  Wilder had some continued success with the single \"The Kid's American\", which reached #33 in 1984, but the single failed to match the success of \"Break My Stride\".  Wilder's second [[album]], ''Bouncin' Off the Walls'' (1984), failed to gain much momentum&mdash;even with an innovative [[music video]] for the single \"Bouncin' Off the Walls\", with only the title track making the charts (No.&nbsp;52), and was subsequently deemed a commercial failure.\n\nDespite the downturn in his solo career, Wilder continued his career in the music industry as a [[songwriter]] and as a [[record producer]] for such acts as [[No Doubt]] (the hit album ''[[Tragic Kingdom]]''), [[702 (band)|702]], [[Christina Aguilera]], [[Kelly Clarkson]], [[Miley Cyrus]] on her ''[[Hannah Montana]]'' song \"G.N.O. (Girls Night Out)\", [[The Belle Brigade]], King Charles, and [[Joanna Pacitti]]. He has also done production work on [[Australia]]n [[singer-songwriter]] [[Mig Ayesa]]'s [[MiG (album)|self-titled album]] released in April 2007 and has helped with production on [[Hayden Panettiere]]'s unreleased album. In 2014, he did production work on Retrouvailles's new album.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\nFor the [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] film ''[[Mulan (1998 film)|Mulan]]'', Matthew Wilder lent his singing [[human voice|voice]] to the character of Ling and won an [[Annie Award]] nomination for [[Annie Award for Music in a Feature Production|Music in an Animated Feature Production]] and was nominated for an [[Academy Award for Original Music Score]] (along with [[David Zippel]] and [[Jerry Goldsmith]]) for his work on that film.<ref name=News-Journal /> \nFor [[theatre]], Wilder once again paired with Zippel to provide the music and lyrics for ''Princesses'', a musical comedy update of [[Frances Hodgson Burnett]]'s novel ''[[A Little Princess]]''.  The production ran at the 5th Avenue Theatre in [[Seattle]] but has yet to open on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]].\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n*''Under the Arch'' (1972, with Matthew & Peter)\n*''[[I Don't Speak the Language]]'' (1983)\n*''Bouncin' Off the Walls'' (1984)\n\n===