014\n| \u2014\n| \n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1983\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Break My Stride]]\"\n| 5\n| 4\n| 17\n| 76\n| 4\n| align=\"left\"| \n* [[ARIA Charts|ARIA]]: Gold<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupagesSinglesAccreds2020.htm|title=ARIA Accreditations 2020|publisher=ARIA|date= January 2020|accessdate=18 February 2020}}</ref>\n* [[British Phonographic Industry|UK]]: Silver<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx |title=BPI Search Results |publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]] |accessdate=May 14, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115055129/http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx |archivedate=January 15, 2013 }}</ref>\n| align=\"left\" rowspan=\"5\"| ''I Don't Speak the Language''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"I Don't Speak the Language\"\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1984\n! scope=\"row\"| \"World of the Rich and Famous\"\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"The Kid's American\"\n| 33\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| 93\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1985\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Ladder of Lovers\"\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Bouncin' Off the Walls\"\n| 52\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \n| align=\"left\"| ''Bouncin' Off the Walls''\n|-\n| colspan=\"10\" style=\"font-size:8pt\"| \"\u2014\" denotes releases that did not chart\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.matthewwildermusic.com/}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0928607}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wilder, Matthew}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Record producers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Annie Award winners]]\n[[Category:Singers from New York City]]\n[[Category:People from Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records artists]]\n[[Category:Epic Records artists]]\n[[Category:American new wave musicians]]\n[[Category:Synth-pop new wave musicians]]\n[[Category:Male new wave singers]]\n[[Category:American pop singers]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=August 2009}}\n{{Infobox musical artist<!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Matthew Wilder\n| image            =\n| image_size       = <!-- Only for images narrower than 220 pixels -->\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Matthew Weiner\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1953|01|24}}\n| birth_place      = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[New wave music|New wave]]|[[synth-pop]]}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Musician|singer|[[record producer]]}}\n| instrument       = {{hlist|[[Vocals]]|[[keyboard instrument|keyboards]]|[[synthesizer]]|[[guitar]]}}\n| years_active     = 1972\u2013present\n| label            = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]] <br/> [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| website          = {{URL|matthewwildermusic.com}}\n}}\n'''Matthew Wilder''' (born '''Matthew Weiner'''; January 24, 1953)<ref name=\"News-Journal\" /> is an American musician, singer, and [[record producer]]. In early 1984, his single \"[[Break My Stride]]\" hit #2 on the ''[[Cash Box]]'' chart and #5 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].\n\n==Career==\nBorn in New York City,<ref name=\"News-Journal\">Farance, Jeff (June 16, 2006). \"Seeing Stars: Where's Wilder? With Waldo?\", ''[[The Daytona Beach News-Journal]]'', p. E14.</ref> Wilder was one-half of the [[Greenwich Village]] [[folk rock|folk]] group Matthew & Peter in the 1970s. In 1978 he moved to [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], and sang for television commercials and as a [[backing vocalist]] for [[Rickie Lee Jones]] and [[Bette Midler]].\n\nWilder's debut album, ''[[I Don't Speak the Language]]'' (1983), reached #49 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], fueled by \"[[Break My Stride]]\".  Wilder had some continued success with the single \"The Kid's American\", which reached #33 in 1984, but the single failed to match the success of \"Break My Stride\".  Wilder's second [[album]], ''Bouncin' Off the Walls'' (1984), failed to gain much momentum&mdash;even with an innovative [[music video]] for the single \"Bouncin' Off the Walls\", with only the title track making the charts (No.&nbsp;52), and was subsequently deemed a commercial failure.\n\nDespite the downturn in his solo career, Wilder continued his career in the music industry as a [[songwriter]] and as a [[record producer]] for such acts as [[No Doubt]] (the hit album ''[[Tragic Kingdom]]''), [[702 (band)|702]], [[Christina Aguilera]], [[Kelly Clarkson]], [[Miley Cyrus]] on her ''[[Hannah Montana]]'' song \"G.N.O. (Girls Night Out)\", [[The Belle Brigade]], King Charles, and [[Joanna Pacitti]]. He has also done production work on [[Australia]]n [[singer-songwriter]] [[Mig Ayesa]]'s [[MiG (album)|self-titled album]] released in April 2007 and has helped with production on [[Hayden Panettiere]]'s unreleased album. In 2014, he did production work on Retrouvailles's new album.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\nFor the [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] film ''[[Mulan (1998 film)|Mulan]]'', Matthew Wilder lent his singing [[human voice|voice]] to the character of Ling and won an [[Annie Award]] nomination for [[Annie Award for Music in a Feature Production|Music in an Animated Feature Production]] and was nominated for an [[Academy Award for Original Music Score]] (along with [[David Zippel]] and [[Jerry Goldsmith]]) for his work on that film.<ref name=News-Journal /> \nFor [[theatre]], Wilder once again paired with Zippel to provide the music and lyrics for ''Princesses'', a musical comedy update of [[Frances Hodgson Burnett]]'s novel ''[[A Little Princess]]''.  The production ran at the 5th Avenue Theatre in [[Seattle]] but has yet to open on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]].\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n*''Under the Arch'' (1972, with Matthew & Peter)\n*''[[I Don't Speak the Language]]'' (1983)\n*''Bouncin' Off the Walls'' (1984)\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Single\n! colspan=\"5\"| Peak chart positions\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:8em;\"| [[Music recording sales certification|Certifications]]<br><small>([[List of best selling music artists|sales threshold]])</small>\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|- style=\"font-size:smaller;\"\n! width=\"35\"| [[Billboard Hot 100|US]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=matthew wilder|chart=all}}|title=Matthew Wilder Album & Song Chart History - Hot 100|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=May 14, 2011}}</ref>\n! width=\"35\"| [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|US AC]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=matthew wilder|chart=Adult Contemporary}}|title=Matthew Wilder Album & Song Chart History - Adult Contemporary|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=May 14, 2011}}</ref>\n! width=\"35\"| [[Hot Dance Club Songs|US Dance]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=matthew wilder|chart=Dance/Club Play Songs}}|title=Matthew Wilder Album & Song Chart History - Dance/Club Play Songs|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=May 14, 2011}}</ref>\n! width=\"35\"| [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|US<br>R&B]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=matthew wilder|chart=R&B/Hip-Hop Songs}}|title=Matthew Wilder Album & Song Chart History - R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=May 14, 2011}}</ref>\n! width=\"35\"| [[UK Singles Chart|UK]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artists/ |title=The Official Charts Company - Matthew Wilder |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |accessdate=May 14, 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n|-\n| | 1982\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Work So Hard\"\n| \u2014\n| 32\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1983\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Break My Stride]]\"\n| 5\n| 4\n| 17\n| 76\n| 4\n| align=\"left\"| \n* [[ARIA Charts|ARIA]]: Gold<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupagesSinglesAccreds2020.htm|title=ARIA Accreditations 2020|publisher=ARIA|date= January 2020|accessdate=18 February 2020}}</ref>\n* [[British Phonographic Industry|UK]]: Silver<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx |title=BPI Search Results |publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]] |accessdate=May 14, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115055129/http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx |archivedate=January 15, 2013 }}</ref>\n| align=\"left\" rowspan=\"5\"| ''I Don't Speak the Language''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"I Don't Speak the Language\"\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1984\n! scope=\"row\"| \"World of the Rich and Famous\"\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"The Kid's American\"\n| 33\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| 93\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1985\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Ladder of Lovers\"\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Bouncin' Off the Walls\"\n| 52\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \n| align=\"left\"| ''Bouncin' Off the Walls''\n|-\n| colspan=\"10\" style=\"font-size:8pt\"| \"\u2014\" denotes releases that did not chart\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.matthewwildermusic.com/}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0928607}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wilder, Matthew}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Record producers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Annie Award winners]]\n[[Category:Singers from New York City]]\n[[Category:People from Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records artists]]\n[[Category:Epic Records artists]]\n[[Category:American new wave musicians]]\n[[Category:Synth-pop new wave musicians]]\n[[Category:Male new wave singers]]\n[[Category:American pop singers]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "2600:8800:3804:6600:b0d0:8b40:b56f:119a", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matthew_Wilder"}
{"title_page": "Podoserpula", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Taxobox\n| image = Podoserpula pusio.jpg\n| image_width = 240px\n| image_caption = ''Podoserpula pusio'' var. ''pusio'',<br> [[Tasmania]], Australia\n| regnum = [[Fungi]]\n| divisio = [[Basidiomycota]]\n| classis = [[Agaricomycetes]]\n| ordo = [[Amylocorticiales]]\n| familia = [[Amylocorticiaceae]]\n| genus = '''''Podoserpula'''''\n| genus_authority = [[Derek Reid|D.A.Reid]] (1963)\n| type_species = ''Podoserpula pusio''\n| type_species_authority = ([[Miles Joseph Berkeley|Berk.]]) D.A.Reid (1963)\n| subdivision_ranks = Species\n| subdivision = ''[[Podoserpula miranda|P.&nbsp;miranda]]''<br>\n''[[Podoserpula pusio|P.&nbsp;pusio]]''\n}}\n\n'''''Podoserpula''''' is a [[genus]] of [[fungi]] in the family [[Amylocorticiaceae]]. The genus contains two species: the [[type species|type]], ''[[Podoserpula pusio|P.&nbsp;pusio]]'', commonly known as the pagoda fungus, and the \"Barbie pagoda\", ''[[Podoserpula miranda|P.&nbsp;miranda]]'', officially published in 2013. ''Podoserpula'' species produce [[sporocarp (fungus)|fruit bodies]] consisting of up to a dozen [[pileus (mycology)|caps]] arranged in overlapping shelves, attached to a central axis. Its unique shape is not known to exist in any other fungi. Four [[variety (botany)|varieties]] of ''P.&nbsp;pusio'' are known, which differ in their sizes, spore [[morphology (biology)|morphology]], and [[species distribution|distribution]]. The genus is known to occur in Australia and New Zealand, Venezuela, Madagascar, and [[New Caledonia]].\n\n==Taxonomy and phylogeny==\n''Craterellus pusio'' was first [[species description|described]] by [[Miles Joseph Berkeley]] in an 1859 publication by [[James Hooker]].<ref name=\"Hooker 1859\"/> [[Otto Kuntze]] transferred it to the genus ''[[Merulius]]'' in 1891.<ref name=\"Kuntze 1891\"/> Until the 1960s, however, it was known as ''Craterellus multiplex'', a species described by [[Mordecai Cubitt Cooke]] and [[George Edward Massee]] in 1889,<ref name=\"Cooke 1889\"/> and moved to ''Cantharellus'' by [[Curtis Gates Lloyd]] in 1920.<ref name=\"Lloyd 1920\"/> In 1958, British mycologist [[R.W.G. Dennis]] collected the species in Venezuela during an expedition financed by the [[Percy Sladen Memorial Trust]]. [[Derek Reid]], attempting to identify the species, rediscovered Berkeley's name, which had priority, and described the new genus ''Podoserpula'' for it in 1963 while simultaneously describing four [[variety (botany)|varieties]] of it.<ref name=\"Reid 1963\"/><ref name=\"urlMycoBank: Podoserpula pusio\"/>\n\nReid considered the genus allied to ''[[Leucogyrophana]]'', then thought to belong to the family [[Coniophoraceae]].<ref name=\"Reid 1963\"/> [[Marinus Anton Donk]], in a monograph published the next year,<ref name=\"Donk1964\">{{cite journal | author=Donk MA. |year=1964 |title=A conspectus of the families of Aphyllophorales | journal=Persoonia |volume=3 |pages=199\u2013324 }}</ref> agreed and placed it close to ''[[Serpula]]'' and ''[[Coniophora]]''; these genera are now known to represent early-diverging lineages in the order [[Boletales]].<ref name=\"Binder 2002\"/> However, the white [[spore print]] and small, smooth, and [[hyaline]] spores are not characteristic of species in the Coniophoraceae.<ref name=\"Watling 2009\"/> In a large-scale [[phylogenetic]] analysis published in 2006, ''Podoserpula'' nested far from them in the ''Plicaturopsis'' [[clade]], an evolutionarily related group of early-diverging members of the order [[Agaricales]]. Other [[taxon|taxa]] in this clade include ''[[Plicaturopsis]]'' and ''[[Sclerotium rolfsii]]''.<ref name=\"Matheny 2006\"/> The entire clade was later separated into three smaller orders, ''Podoserpula'' becoming a member of the [[Amylocorticiales]] along with mostly [[corticioid]] genera such as ''[[Amylocorticium]]'' and ''[[Serpulomyces]]''.<ref name=\"Binder 2010\"/>\n\nA new species, ''Podoserpula miranda'', was proposed in 2009 by a group of [[New Caledonia]]n mycologists for a species of that [[Oceania|South Pacific]] archipelago.<ref name=\"Ducousso 2009\"/> The name was provisional (not validly published), however, as the description was in French (the [[International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants|code of nomenclature]] mandates Latin<ref name=\"urlIAPT\"/>) and lacked a required designation of a [[holotype|type specimen]].<ref name=\"urlIAPT\"/> It was validly published in 2013.<ref name=\"Buyck 2013\"/>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Podoserpula pusio var tristis 233816.jpg|thumb|left|''Podoserpula pusio'' var. ''tristis'', from New Zealand]]\nThe [[sporocarp (fungus)|fruit bodies]] of ''Podoserpula'' species have an unusual form unknown in other fungi.<ref name=\"Roberts 2011\"/> The fruit bodies, which grow to a height of {{convert|1|\u2013|18|cm|in|1|abbr=on}}, consist of up to a dozen cup-shaped (spathulate) to kidney-shaped (reniform) caps arranged in multiple tiers and attached to a central stem. Caps are joined to the main axis by short, flattened, stem-like attachments. The variety ''tristis'', in contrast, has  caps that are more circular and appear to be pierced either centrally or off to the side. The surface of the caps is smooth and often brightly colored. The [[hymenium]] (spore-bearing surface) on the underside of the caps is pink and has a folded and corrugated surface. Close to the area of attachment between the cap and the stem-like connection to the main axis are swellings resembling warts or blisters.<ref name=\"Reid 1963\"/> Individual caps resemble somewhat those of the European species ''[[Plicaturopsis crispa]]''.<ref name=\"Watling 2009\"/>\n\n''Podoserpula'' has a monomitic [[hypha]]l structure, meaning that it only contains generative hyphae, which are  relatively undifferentiated and can develop reproductive structures. These hyphae are thin-walled, [[hyaline]] (translucent), branched, and up to 10&nbsp;[[micrometre|\u03bcm]] thick. They have distinct, often swollen, [[clamp connection]]s at the [[septum|septa]]. The [[spore]]s are small, typically 2.75\u20136 by 2\u20133.5&nbsp;\u03bcm, smooth, hyaline, and vary in shape from roughly elliptical to somewhat spherical. The [[basidia]] (spore-bearing cells) can be either two- or four-spored, and are club shaped, with a clamp connection at the base. ''Podoserpula'' has neither [[cystidia]] nor gloeocystidia.<ref name=\"Reid 1963\"/>\n\n''Podoserpula pusio'' var. ''pusio'' is the [[Nominate subspecies#Nominotypical subspecies and subspecies autonyms|nominate]] variety. Its fruit bodies are rarely greater than {{convert|7.5|cm|in|abbr=on}} tall. Variety ''austro-americana'' is the largest of the varieties, reaching heights up to {{convert|18|cm|in|abbr=on}}. Other than its size and geographical distribution, it is roughly similar to var. ''pusio''. Variety ''ellipsospora'' has elongated elliptical spores typically measuring 4\u20135 by 2.75\u20133.5&nbsp;\u03bcm. Variety ''tristis'' has caps whose upper surfaces are colored pale [[fawn (colour)|fawn]], and the main axis of the fruit bodies pierces through the cap.<ref name=\"Reid 1963\"/>\n\n''Podoserpula miranda'' grows to a height of {{convert|10|cm|in|abbr=on}}. It differs from ''P.&nbsp;pusio'' var. ''pusio'' in having thinner flesh, up to six funnel-shaped caps whose size diminishes approaching the top, and a bright pink coloration in the folds of the hymenium.<ref name=\"Ducousso 2009\"/>\n\n==Habitat and distribution==\nThe fruit bodies of ''Podoserpula pusio'' grow on the ground, on well-rotted stumps,<ref name=\"Reid 1963\"/> or among decaying [[tussock (grass)|tussock]] grass.<ref name=\"Watling 2009\"/> They are presumed to be [[Saprotrophic nutrition|saprobic]], and obtain nutrients by breaking down larger organic molecules found in the soil or in decaying wood.<ref name=\"Reid 1963\"/> ''P.&nbsp;miranda'' in contrast, is thought to be [[Mycorrhiza|ectomycorrhizal]], as it appears to associate with ''[[arillastrum|Arillastrum gummiferum]]'', the predominant [[canopy (biology)|canopy]] tree in the forests where it is found.<ref name=\"Ducousso 2009\"/>\n\nThe nominate variety is found in Australasia, but in 1997 it was reported in a [[protected area]] near [[Antananarivo]] in [[Madagascar]],<ref name=\"Buyck 2008\"/> and in 2009 on the [[Falkland Islands]].<ref name=\"Watling 2009\"/> Variety ''ellipsospora'' occurs in Australia, var. ''tristis'' in New Zealand, and var. ''austro-americana'' is known from Venezuela.<ref name=\"Reid 1963\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Binder 2002\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Binder M, Bresinsky A |year=2002 |title=Derivation of a polymorphic lineage of Gasteromycetes from boletoid ancestors |journal=Mycologia |volume=94 |issue=1 |pages=85\u201398 |url=http://www.mycologia.org/content/94/1/85.full.pdf |doi= 10.2307/3761848|pmid=21156480}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Binder 2010\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Binder M, Larsson KH, Matheny PB, Hibbett DS |title=Amylocorticiales ord. nov. and Jaapiales ord. nov.: Early diverging clades of Agaricomycetidae dominated by corticioid forms |journal=Mycologia |year=2010 |volume=102 |issue=4 |pages=865\u201380 |doi=10.3852/09-288 |pmid=20648753}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Buyck 2008\">{{cite journal |author=Buyck B. |title=The edible mushrooms of Madagascar: An evolving enigma |journal=Economic Botany |year=2008 |volume=62 |issue=3 |pages=509\u201320 |doi=10.1007/s12231-008-9029-4}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Buyck 2013\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Buyck B, Duhem B, Eyssartier G, Ducousso M |title=''Podoserpula miranda'' sp. nov. (Amylocorticiales, Basidiomycota) from New Caledonia |journal=Cryptogamie, Mycologie |year=2012 |volume=33 |issue=4 |pages=453\u201351 |doi=10.7872/crym.v33.iss4.2012.453}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Cooke 1889\">{{cite journal |title=New Australian fungi |journal=Grevillea |year=1889 |author=Cooke MC. |volume=18 |pages=25\u20136 |url=http://www.cybertruffle.org.uk/cyberliber/59649/0018/086/0025.htm}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Ducousso 2009\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Ducoussou M, Proust S, Vigier D, Eyssartier G |title=''Podoserpula miranda'' nom prov., une nouvelle esp\u00e8ce de champignon tr\u00e8s spectaculaire d\u00e9couverte en Nouvelle-Cal\u00e9donie |trans-title=''Podoserpula miranda'' prov. name, a spectacular new fungus species discovered in New-Caledonia |journal=Bois et For\u00eats des Tropiques |year=2009 |volume=302 |issue=4 |pages=74\u20135 |language=French |url=http://agritrop.cirad.fr/555107/1/BFT_302_73-75.pdf |format=PDF }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Hooker 1859\">{{cite book |author=Hooker JD. |year=1860 |title=The botany of the antarctic voyage of H.M. ships Erebus and Terror in the years 1839\u201343 under the command of Sir James Clark Ross. III Flora Tasmaniae |volume=2 |publisher= |edition=1860 |page=258}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Kuntze 1891\">{{cite book |author=Kuntze O. |title=Revisio Generum Plantarum |volume=2 |location=Leipzig, Germany |publisher=A. Felix |year=1891 |page=862 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/4284 |language=German}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Lloyd 1920\">{{cite journal |author=Lloyd CG. |title=Mycological Notes |journal=Mycological Writings |year=1920 |volume=6 |issue=62 |pages=904\u201344}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Matheny 2006\">{{cite journal  |vauthors=Matheny PB, Curtis JM, Hofstetter V, etal |title=Major clades of Agaricales: a multilocus phylogenetic overview |journal=Mycologia |volume=98 |issue=6 |pages=982\u201395 |year=2006 |pmid=17486974 |format=PDF |url=http://www.fs.fed.us/global/iitf/pubs/ja_iitf_2006_Matheny001.pdf |doi=10.3852/mycologia.98.6.982}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Reid 1963\">{{cite journal |author=Reid DA. |year=1963 |title=Fungi venezuelani: VI (New or interesting records of Australasian Basidiomycetes: IV). ''Podoserpula'' Reid: A new genus based on ''Craterellus pusio'' Berk. (''C. Multiplex'' Cooke & Massee) |journal=Kew Bulletin |volume=15 |issue=3 |pages=437\u201345 |jstor=4114687}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Roberts 2011\">{{cite book |vauthors=Roberts P, Evans S |title=The Book of Fungi |year=2011 |publisher=University of Chicago Press |location=Chicago, Illinois |page=432 |isbn=978-0226721170}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"urlIAPT\">{{cite web |title=Chapter IV. Effective and valid publication. Section 2. Conditions and dates of valid publication of names. Article 34 |url=http://ibot.sav.sk/icbn/frameset/0038Ch4Sec2a034.htm |publisher=International Association for Plant Taxonomy |work=International Code of Botanical Nomenclature (Vienna Code) |year=2006 |accessdate=2012-09-02}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"urlMycoBank: Podoserpula pusio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mycobank.org/MycoTaxo.aspx?Link=T&Rec=18321 |title=''Podoserpula pusio'' (Berk.) D.A. Reid 1963 |publisher=[[MycoBank]]. International Mycological Association |accessdate=2012-09-02}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Watling 2009\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Watling R, Eggeling T |title=Pagoda fungus, ''Podoserpula pusio'' found in the Falklands |journal=Field Mycology |year=2009 |volume=10 |issue=2 |pages=56\u20137 |doi=10.1016/S1468-1641(10)60501-4}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IndexFungorum|18321}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3071497}}\n\n[[Category:Amylocorticiales]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Taxobox\n| image = Podoserpula pusio.jpg\n| image_width = 240px\n| image_caption = ''Podoserpula pusio'' var. ''pusio'',<br> [[Tasmania]], Australia\n| regnum = [[Fungi]]\n| divisio = [[Basidiomycota]]\n| classis = [[Agaricomycetes]]\n| ordo = [[Amylocorticiales]]\n| familia = [[Amylocorticiaceae]]\n| genus = '''''Podoserpula'''''\n| genus_authority = [[Derek Reid|D.A.Reid]] (1963)\n| type_species = ''Podoserpula pusio''\n| type_species_authority = ([[Miles Joseph Berkeley|Berk.]]) D.A.Reid (1963)\n| subdivision_ranks = Species\n| subdivision = ''[[Podoserpula miranda|P.&nbsp;miranda]]''<br>\n''[[Podoserpula pusio|P.&nbsp;pusio]]''\n}}\n\n'''''Podoserpula''''' is a [[genus]] of [[fungi]] in the family [[Amylocorticiaceae]]. The genus contains two species: the [[type species|type]], ''[[Podoserpula pusio|P.&nbsp;pusio]]'', commonly known as the pagoda fungus, and the \"Barbie pagoda\", ''[[Podoserpula miranda|P.&nbsp;miranda]]'', officially published in 2013. ''Podoserpula'' species produce [[sporocarp (fungus)|fruit bodies]] consisting of up to a dozen [[pileus (mycology)|caps]] arranged in overlapping shelves, attached to a central axis. Its unique shape is not known to exist in any other fungi. Four [[variety (botany)|varieties]] of ''P.&nbsp;pusio'' are known, which differ in their sizes, spore [[morphology (biology)|morphology]], and [[species distribution|distribution]]. The genus is known to occur in Australia and New Zealand, Venezuela, Madagascar, and [[New Caledonia]].\n\n==Taxonomy and phylogeny==\n''Craterellus pusio'' was first [[species description|described]] by [[Miles Joseph Berkeley]] in an 1859 publication by [[James Hooker]].<ref name=\"Hooker 1859\"/> [[Otto Kuntze]] transferred it to the genus ''[[Merulius]]'' in 1891.<ref name=\"Kuntze 1891\"/> Until the 1960s, however, it was known as ''Craterellus multiplex'', a species described by [[Mordecai Cubitt Cooke]] and [[George Edward Massee]] in 1889,<ref name=\"Cooke 1889\"/> and moved to ''Cantharellus'' by [[Curtis Gates Lloyd]] in 1920.<ref name=\"Lloyd 1920\"/> In 1958, British mycologist [[R.W.G. Dennis]] collected the species in Venezuela during an expedition financed by the [[Percy Sladen Memorial Trust]]. [[Derek Reid]], attempting to identify the species, rediscovered Berkeley's name, which had priority, and described the new genus ''Podoserpula'' for it in 1963 while simultaneously describing four [[variety (botany)|varieties]] of it.<ref name=\"Reid 1963\"/><ref name=\"urlMycoBank: Podoserpula pusio\"/>\n\nReid considered the genus allied to ''[[Leucogyrophana]]'', then thought to belong to the family [[Coniophoraceae]].<ref name=\"Reid 1963\"/> [[Marinus Anton Donk]], in a monograph published the next year,<ref name=\"Donk1964\">{{cite journal | author=Donk MA. |year=1964 |title=A conspectus of the families of Aphyllophorales | journal=Persoonia |volume=3 |pages=199\u2013324 }}</ref> agreed and placed it close to ''[[Serpula]]'' and ''[[Coniophora]]''; these genera are now known to represent early-diverging lineages in the [[Boletales]] order.<ref name=\"Binder 2002\"/> However, the white [[spore print]] and small, smooth, and [[hyaline]] spores are not characteristic of species in the Coniophoraceae.<ref name=\"Watling 2009\"/> In a large-scale [[phylogenetic]] analysis published in 2006, ''Podoserpula'' nested far from them in the ''Plicaturopsis'' [[clade]], an evolutionarily related group of early-diverging members of the [[Agaricales]] order. Other [[taxon|taxa]] in this clade include ''[[Plicaturopsis]]'' and ''[[Sclerotium rolfsii]]''.<ref name=\"Matheny 2006\"/> The entire clade was later separated into three smaller orders, ''Podoserpula'' becoming a member of the [[Amylocorticiales]] along with mostly [[corticioid]] genera such as ''[[Amylocorticium]]'' and ''[[Serpulomyces]]''.<ref name=\"Binder 2010\"/>\n\nA new species, ''Podoserpula miranda'', was proposed in 2009 by a group of [[New Caledonia]]n mycologists for a species of that [[Oceania|South Pacific]] archipelago.<ref name=\"Ducousso 2009\"/> The name was provisional (not validly published), however, as the description was in French (the [[International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants|code of nomenclature]] mandates Latin<ref name=\"urlIAPT\"/>) and lacked a required designation of a [[holotype|type specimen]].<ref name=\"urlIAPT\"/> It was validly published in 2013.<ref name=\"Buyck 2013\"/>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Podoserpula pusio var tristis 233816.jpg|thumb|left|''Podoserpula pusio'' var. ''tristis'', from New Zealand]]\nThe [[sporocarp (fungus)|fruit bodies]] of ''Podoserpula'' species have an unusual form unknown in other fungi.<ref name=\"Roberts 2011\"/> The fruit bodies, which grow to a height of {{convert|1|\u2013|18|cm|in|1|abbr=on}}, consist of up to a dozen cup-shaped (spathulate) to kidney-shaped (reniform) caps arranged in multiple tiers and attached to a central stem. Caps are joined to the main axis by short, flattened, stem-like attachments. The variety ''tristis'', in contrast, has  caps that are more circular and appear to be pierced either centrally or off to the side. The surface of the caps is smooth and often brightly colored. The [[hymenium]] (spore-bearing surface) on the underside of the caps is pink and has a folded and corrugated surface. Close to the area of attachment between the cap and the stem-like connection to the main axis are swellings resembling warts or blisters.<ref name=\"Reid 1963\"/> Individual caps resemble somewhat those of the European species ''[[Plicaturopsis crispa]]''.<ref name=\"Watling 2009\"/>\n\n''Podoserpula'' has a monomitic [[hypha]]l structure, meaning that it only contains generative hyphae, which are  relatively undifferentiated and can develop reproductive structures. These hyphae are thin-walled, [[hyaline]] (translucent), branched, and up to 10&nbsp;[[micrometre|\u03bcm]] thick. They have distinct, often swollen, [[clamp connection]]s at the [[septum|septa]]. The [[spore]]s are small, typically 2.75\u20136 by 2\u20133.5&nbsp;\u03bcm, smooth, hyaline, and vary in shape from roughly elliptical to somewhat spherical. The [[basidia]] (spore-bearing cells) can be either two- or four-spored, and are club shaped, with a clamp connection at the base. ''Podoserpula'' has neither [[cystidia]] nor gloeocystidia.<ref name=\"Reid 1963\"/>\n\n''Podoserpula pusio'' var. ''pusio'' is the [[Nominate subspecies#Nominotypical subspecies and subspecies autonyms|nominate]] variety. Its fruit bodies are rarely greater than {{convert|7.5|cm|in|abbr=on}} tall. Variety ''austro-americana'' is the largest of the varieties, reaching heights up to {{convert|18|cm|in|abbr=on}}. Other than its size and geographical distribution, it is roughly similar to var. ''pusio''. Variety ''ellipsospora'' has elongated elliptical spores typically measuring 4\u20135 by 2.75\u20133.5&nbsp;\u03bcm. Variety ''tristis'' has caps whose upper surfaces are colored pale [[fawn (colour)|fawn]], and the main axis of the fruit bodies pierces through the cap.<ref name=\"Reid 1963\"/>\n\n''Podoserpula miranda'' grows to a height of {{convert|10|cm|in|abbr=on}}. It differs from ''P.&nbsp;pusio'' var. ''pusio'' in having thinner flesh, up to six funnel-shaped caps whose size diminishes approaching the top, and a bright pink coloration in the folds of the hymenium.<ref name=\"Ducousso 2009\"/>\n\n==Habitat and distribution==\nThe fruit bodies of ''Podoserpula pusio'' grow on the ground, on well-rotted stumps,<ref name=\"Reid 1963\"/> or among decaying [[tussock (grass)|tussock]] grass.<ref name=\"Watling 2009\"/> They are presumed to be [[Saprotrophic nutrition|saprobic]], and obtain nutrients by breaking down larger organic molecules found in the soil or in decaying wood.<ref name=\"Reid 1963\"/> ''P.&nbsp;miranda'' in contrast, is thought to be [[Mycorrhiza|ectomycorrhizal]], as it appears to associate with ''[[arillastrum|Arillastrum gummiferum]]'', the predominant [[canopy (biology)|canopy]] tree in the forests where it is found.<ref name=\"Ducousso 2009\"/>\n\nThe nominate variety is found in Australasia, but in 1997 it was reported in a [[protected area]] near [[Antananarivo]] in [[Madagascar]],<ref name=\"Buyck 2008\"/> and in 2009 on the [[Falkland Islands]].<ref name=\"Watling 2009\"/> Variety ''ellipsospora'' occurs in Australia, var. ''tristis'' in New Zealand, and var. ''austro-americana'' is known from Venezuela.<ref name=\"Reid 1963\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Binder 2002\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Binder M, Bresinsky A |year=2002 |title=Derivation of a polymorphic lineage of Gasteromycetes from boletoid ancestors |journal=Mycologia |volume=94 |issue=1 |pages=85\u201398 |url=http://www.mycologia.org/content/94/1/85.full.pdf |doi= 10.2307/3761848|pmid=21156480}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Binder 2010\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Binder M, Larsson KH, Matheny PB, Hibbett DS |title=Amylocorticiales ord. nov. and Jaapiales ord. nov.: Early diverging clades of Agaricomycetidae dominated by corticioid forms |journal=Mycologia |year=2010 |volume=102 |issue=4 |pages=865\u201380 |doi=10.3852/09-288 |pmid=20648753}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Buyck 2008\">{{cite journal |author=Buyck B. |title=The edible mushrooms of Madagascar: An evolving enigma |journal=Economic Botany |year=2008 |volume=62 |issue=3 |pages=509\u201320 |doi=10.1007/s12231-008-9029-4}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Buyck 2013\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Buyck B, Duhem B, Eyssartier G, Ducousso M |title=''Podoserpula miranda'' sp. nov. (Amylocorticiales, Basidiomycota) from New Caledonia |journal=Cryptogamie, Mycologie |year=2012 |volume=33 |issue=4 |pages=453\u201351 |doi=10.7872/crym.v33.iss4.2012.453}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Cooke 1889\">{{cite journal |title=New Australian fungi |journal=Grevillea |year=1889 |author=Cooke MC. |volume=18 |pages=25\u20136 |url=http://www.cybertruffle.org.uk/cyberliber/59649/0018/086/0025.htm}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Ducousso 2009\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Ducoussou M, Proust S, Vigier D, Eyssartier G |title=''Podoserpula miranda'' nom prov., une nouvelle esp\u00e8ce de champignon tr\u00e8s spectaculaire d\u00e9couverte en Nouvelle-Cal\u00e9donie |trans-title=''Podoserpula miranda'' prov. name, a spectacular new fungus species discovered in New-Caledonia |journal=Bois et For\u00eats des Tropiques |year=2009 |volume=302 |issue=4 |pages=74\u20135 |language=French |url=http://agritrop.cirad.fr/555107/1/BFT_302_73-75.pdf |format=PDF }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Hooker 1859\">{{cite book |author=Hooker JD. |year=1860 |title=The botany of the antarctic voyage of H.M. ships Erebus and Terror in the years 1839\u201343 under the command of Sir James Clark Ross. III Flora Tasmaniae |volume=2 |publisher= |edition=1860 |page=258}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Kuntze 1891\">{{cite book |author=Kuntze O. |title=Revisio Generum Plantarum |volume=2 |location=Leipzig, Germany |publisher=A. Felix |year=1891 |page=862 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/4284 |language=German}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Lloyd 1920\">{{cite journal |author=Lloyd CG. |title=Mycological Notes |journal=Mycological Writings |year=1920 |volume=6 |issue=62 |pages=904\u201344}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Matheny 2006\">{{cite journal  |vauthors=Matheny PB, Curtis JM, Hofstetter V, etal |title=Major clades of Agaricales: a multilocus phylogenetic overview |journal=Mycologia |volume=98 |issue=6 |pages=982\u201395 |year=2006 |pmid=17486974 |format=PDF |url=http://www.fs.fed.us/global/iitf/pubs/ja_iitf_2006_Matheny001.pdf |doi=10.3852/mycologia.98.6.982}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Reid 1963\">{{cite journal |author=Reid DA. |year=1963 |title=Fungi venezuelani: VI (New or interesting records of Australasian Basidiomycetes: IV). ''Podoserpula'' Reid: A new genus based on ''Craterellus pusio'' Berk. (''C. Multiplex'' Cooke & Massee) |journal=Kew Bulletin |volume=15 |issue=3 |pages=437\u201345 |jstor=4114687}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Roberts 2011\">{{cite book |vauthors=Roberts P, Evans S |title=The Book of Fungi |year=2011 |publisher=University of Chicago Press |location=Chicago, Illinois |page=432 |isbn=978-0226721170}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"urlIAPT\">{{cite web |title=Chapter IV. Effective and valid publication. Section 2. Conditions and dates of valid publication of names. Article 34 |url=http://ibot.sav.sk/icbn/frameset/0038Ch4Sec2a034.htm |publisher=International Association for Plant Taxonomy |work=International Code of Botanical Nomenclature (Vienna Code) |year=2006 |accessdate=2012-09-02}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"urlMycoBank: Podoserpula pusio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mycobank.org/MycoTaxo.aspx?Link=T&Rec=18321 |title=''Podoserpula pusio'' (Berk.) D.A. Reid 1963 |publisher=[[MycoBank]]. International Mycological Association |accessdate=2012-09-02}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Watling 2009\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Watling R, Eggeling T |title=Pagoda fungus, ''Podoserpula pusio'' found in the Falklands |journal=Field Mycology |year=2009 |volume=10 |issue=2 |pages=56\u20137 |doi=10.1016/S1468-1641(10)60501-4}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IndexFungorum|18321}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3071497}}\n\n[[Category:Amylocorticiales]]\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTaxonomy and phylogeny:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Podoserpula"}
{"title_page": "Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi", "text_new": "{{short description|Swedish activist and member of the Yellow vests}}\n{{Sources|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi\n| birth_place        = [[Gothenburg]], Sweden.\n| nationality        = Swedish\n| occupation         = activist, debater and orator.\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|2003|11|25}}\n}}\n\n'''Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi''' (born November 25, 2003)<ref>{{cite web |title=Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi {{!}} Ratsit.se |url=https://www.ratsit.se/20031125-Izabella_Zhila_Maria_Nilsson_Jarvandi_Angered/nukoj9Zj4Ba_oTT6_HYUQ8po1f1xaYVWPytzAzoclrg |website=www.ratsit.se | accessdate=13 December 2019 |language=sv-se}}</ref> is a Swedish activist and protester part of the [[Yellow vests movement|Yellow vests]] known for having held a protest speech at [[Mynttorget]] in [[Gothenburg]] against Sweden's signing of the UN contract of [[Global Compact for Migration]] on December 9, 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zackrisson |first1=Pelle |title=Janouch: 'Vi har ingen kvinnofrid l\u00e4ngre' (We have no safety for women any more) |url=https://nyheteridag.se/janouch-vi-har-ingen-kvinnofrid-langre/ |accessdate=23 June 2019 |agency=Publicism NITEK AB |issue=\"Isabella Nilsson Jarvandi is one of the girls engaged in this) |publisher=Jakob Bergman |date=16 December 2018 |language=sv-SE}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=SVENSSON |first1=TOBIAS |title=Intervju med Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi: \"Skulle inte f\u00f6rv\u00e5na mig om det blir inb\u00f6rdeskrig\" (Wouldn't surprise me if there is an outbreak of civil war) |url=https://www.nyatider.nu/intervju-med-izabella-nilsson-jarvandi-skulle-inte-forvana-mig-om-det-blir-inbordeskrig/ |accessdate=23 June 2019 |work=article |agency=Fria Tider |issue=Yellow vests |publisher=AlternaMedia AB, V\u00e1vra Suk. |date=1 May 2019 |language=sv-SE}}</ref> She has also held speeches in [[Helsingborg]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Skandinaviska F\u00f6rbundet |first1=Skandinaviska F\u00f6rbundet |title=Protester i Helsingborg kl 12.00 nu p\u00e5 l\u00f6rdag den 15/12 (Protest in Helsingborg now against the FN Migration contract) |url=http://skandinaviskfrihet.se/protester-i-helsingborg-kl-12-00-nu-pa-lordag-den-15-12/ |accessdate=23 June 2019 |agency=Skandinavisk frihet |issue=Event |publisher=Skandinaviska F\u00f6rbundet |date=13 December 2018 |language=sv-SE}}</ref> and [[Stockholm]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Skogssj\u00f6n |first1=Skogssj\u00f6n |title=Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi \u2013 Protest mot Globalismen i Stockholm (Protest against globalism in Stockholm) |url=https://idreporter.net/v/izabella-nilsson-jarvandi-protest-mot-globalismen-i-stockholm-P5CsnZejJzU.html |website=idreporter.net |publisher=idreporter.net}}</ref> Jarvandi is mentioned in the book \"''Tutto quello che c'\u00e8 da sapere sul clima''\" by Thomas Pedretti.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Pedretti |first1=Thomas |title=Tutto quello che c'\u00e8 da sapere sul clima |date=2019 |publisher= |isbn=9780244777067 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=miWUDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA22&dq=izabella+nilsson+jarvandi#v=onepage&q=izabella%20nilsson%20jarvandi&f=false |language=it}}</ref> She is also mentioned in Antonio Giangrande's \"''Italia allo specchio il DNA deli italiani anno 2019 quarta parte. La cultura ed i media''\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=GIANGRANDE |first1=ANTONIO |title=ITALIA ALLO SPECCHIO IL DNA DEGLI ITALIANI ANNO 2019 QUARTA PARTE. LA CULTURA ED I MEDIA |date=2019 |publisher=Antonio Giangrande |page=133 |edition=olym 168 av L\u2019Italia del Trucco, l\u2019Italia che siamo |url=https://books.google.com/?id=P1yHDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA133&dq=izabella+nilsson+jarvandi#v=onepage&q=izabella%20nilsson%20jarvandi&f=false |language=it}}</ref>\n\nDue to her age and politics, Jarvandi has been called the \"anti-[[Greta Thunberg]]\".\n\n== Background ==\nIzabella Nilsson Jarvandi has Iranian and Swedish heritage. Her father came from [[Iran]] and her mother is Swedish. Jarvandi grew up in a high-crime suburb in Gothenburg. She studied at a calm elementary school but she experienced the segregation through friends and family members who witnessed amongst segregated immigrants, and second generation immigrants, language deficients, [[maladaptation]], racism, crime, sexual harassments and drugs. In an interview with [[Mikael Willgert]], the host on [[Svensk Webbtelevision|Swebbtv]], Jarvandi explains that there have been incidents of rape on Swedish school property and that many teachers are afraid of opposing students.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Willger of Swebbtv |first1=Mikael |title=L\u00f6rdagsintervju 44 \u2013 Izabella 15 \u00e5r, om livet som ton\u00e5ring och nationalist. (Saturday interview with Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi and how it is like to be a 15 year old nationalist) |url=https://www.swebbtv.se/blogg/242-lordagsintervju-44-izabella-15-ar-om-livet-som-tonaring-och-nationalist |website=SwebbTV |publisher=Svensk Webbtelevision AB 2019 |accessdate=23 June 2019 |language=sv-se}}</ref>\n\n== Politics ==\nJarvandi has stated that she is \"''upset, angry and devastated''\" over the Swedish governments politics in multiculturalism and integration of immigrants.<ref>{{cite web |last1=ett SUVER\u00c4NT Sverige. |first1=Stockholmare f\u00f6r |title=G\u00e4stinl\u00e4gg: Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi \u2013 Mitt liv har pr\u00e4glats av systemfel \u2013 Stockholmare f\u00f6r ett suver\u00e4nt Sverige (Guest publication: Stockholmers for a great Sweden) |url=http://svenskt.bloggo.nu/Gastinlagg-Izabella-Nilsson-Jarvandi---Mitt-liv-har-praglats-av-systemfel/ |publisher=ett SUVER\u00c4NT Sverige. |accessdate=23 June 2019}}</ref> In an article by Katerina Magasin, published on December 2018, Jarvandi wrote an article saying \"''I am so angry at the politicians in the parliament \u2013 Sweden was a great country''!\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Janouch |first1=Katerina |title=Izabella, 15 \u00e5r: \"Jag \u00e4r s\u00e5 arg p\u00e5 politikerna i Riksdagen \u2013 Sverige har varit ett bra land\" (Translation: I am so angry at the politicians at the parliament \u2013 Sweden was a great country!) |url=http://katerinamagasin.se/izabella-15-ar-jag-ar-sa-arg-pa-politikerna-riksdagen-sverige-har-varit-ett-bra-land/ |accessdate=23 June 2019 |agency=Katerina Magasin |issue=Debate article |publisher=Katerina Janouch |date=18 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Maria |first1=Ingrid och |title=15-\u00e5riga Izabella leder FN-protesterna \u2013 \"det \u00e4r min framtid\" (15 year old Izabella leads protest against UN \u2013 \"Its my future\") |url=https://www.ingridochmaria.se/2018/12/20/blir-izabella-15-var-forsta-kvinnliga-statsminister/ |accessdate=23 June 2019 |agency=Ingrid och Maria |publisher=Ingrid och Maria |date=20 December 2018 |language=sv-SE}}</ref> According to an article by the Italian newspaper Lettera Donna, Jarvandi is \"''a young political activist who is against globalism and who seeks the truth and justice for my beloved Sweden''\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Donna |first1=Lettera |title=L'anti-Greta \u00e8 sovranista (e pro-famiglia tradizionale) (Translation: Who is Izabella Jarvandi, the 15-year-old Swedish against gender and migrants?) |url=https://www.letteradonna.it/it/articoli/ritratti/2019/04/23/izabella-nilsson-jarvandi-svezia-gender/28200/ |accessdate=23 June 2019 |work=LetteraDonna |agency=LetteraDonna |issue=Article |publisher=\u00a9 RIPRODUZIONE RISERVATA |date=23 April 2019 |language=it}}</ref> She has been called the Anti-[[Greta Thunberg|Greta]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bianchi |first1=Leonardo |last2=VICE |first2=Redazione |title=La vera storia dietro 'l'anti-Greta Thunberg' di cui parlano i media italiani (Translation: The real story behind 'the anti-Greta Thunberg spoken of by the Italian media. The 15 year old Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi is presented as Thunberg's perfect nemesis, but we only talk so stubbornly in Italy) |url=https://www.vice.com/it/article/bj9zdq/izabella-nilsson-jarvandi-greta-thunberg |accessdate=23 June 2019 |work=Article |agency=Vice |date=25 April 2019 |language=it}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Inrikes |first1=Fria Tider |title=Greta Thunberg: \"M\u00e4nsklighetens st\u00f6rsta kris n\u00e5gonsin\" (Greta Thunberg: Humanitys greatest threat) |url=https://www.friatider.se/greta-thunberg-m-nsklighetens-st-rsta-kris-n-gonsin |accessdate=23 June 2019 |work=Fria Tider |agency=Fria Tider |issue=Article \"Izabella Jarvandi, sometimes called Anti\u2013Greta\") |publisher=Fria Tider |language=sv}}</ref> Jarvandi has 7200 followers on Twitter. In an article by Fidelity News on March 2019, Jarvandi is described as opposing globalism, mass-migration, and gender ideology which she believes spread disinformation amongst Swedish youngsters.<ref>{{cite news |last1=BARBATO |first1=MARIO |title=Chi \u00e8 Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi, la 15enne svedese idolo dei sovranisti? (Translation: Who is Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi, the sovereign idol?) |url=https://news.fidelityhouse.eu/esteri/chi-e-izabella-nilsson-jarvandi-la-15enne-svedese-idolo-dei-sovranisti-411442.html |accessdate=23 June 2019 |work=Fidelity News |agency=Fidelity News |issue=Article |publisher=Horizon Group |date=6 May 2019 |language=it}}</ref> Jarvandi supports the Hungarian government led by [[Viktor Orb\u00e1n]].<ref>{{cite news |title=)Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi, (l'altra) ragazza (costruita) questa volta anti gender e anti migranti (Translation: Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi, (the other) girl (built) this time anti-gender and anti-migrants |url=http://www.ticinolive.ch/2019/04/24/jarvandi-nilsson-laltra-ragazza-costruita-questa-volta-anti-gender-e-anti-migranti/ |accessdate=23 June 2019 |work=Ticinolive |agency=Ticino Live |issue=Debate |publisher=Quotidiano della Svizzera italiana |date=24 April 2019 |language=it-IT}}</ref> In an article by the French newspaper Bvoltaire, Jarvandi is quoted saying \"''I will never be silenced and I will never forgive the politicians for all the harm they have done to my dear Sweden [...] I am convinced that the gods are watching and I know that traitors will one day be judged severely''\", Izabella fumed as she spoke in the streets of the Scandinavian cities.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bernadac |first1=J.-P. Fabre |title=En Su\u00e8de, Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi, ou l'anti-Greta Thunberg ? (Translation: And the Swedish girl, Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi, the Anti-Greta Thunberg? |url=https://www.bvoltaire.fr/en-suede-izabella-nilsson-jarvandi-ou-lanti-greta-thunberg/ |accessdate=23 June 2019 |work=Article |agency=Boulevard Voltaire |publisher=Boulevard Voltaire |date=28 April 2019 |language=fr-FR}}</ref> The French politician and Secretary General of Parti de la France Thomas Joly supported Jarvandi.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Joly |first1=Thomas |title=En Su\u00e8de, Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi, l'anti-Greta Thunberg (Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi, the anti-Greta Thunberg) |url=http://www.thomasjoly.fr/2019/04/en-suede-izabella-nilsson-jarvandi-l-anti-greta-thunberg.html |accessdate=23 June 2019 |work=Le blog politique de Thomas JOLY |agency=Le blog politique de Thomas Joly |publisher=Thomas Joly |date=2019 |language=fr}}</ref> In an article by Der Freie Welt published on March 2019, Jarvandi is described as \"''being in while Greta is out''\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dinnebin |first1=Micha |title=Greta ist \"out\", Izabella ist \"in\" |url=https://www.freiewelt.net/blog/greta-ist-out-izabella-ist-in-10077221/ |accessdate=23 June 2019 |work=FreieWelt.net |agency=Der Freie Welt (the free will) |date=2019 |language=de}}</ref> On March 17, 2019, Jarvandi tweeted saying \"You who have the audacity to harass me for my opinions are only proving me right. It is because of people like you and actions like yours I am fighting and I will not bow nor surrender. We were born free and I intend future generations to be as well\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jarvandi |first1=Izabella Nilsson |title=You who have the audacity to harass me for my opinions are only proving me right. It is because of people like you and actions like yours I am fighting and I will not bow nor surrender We were born free and I intend future generations to be as well |url=https://twitter.com/izabellamarianj/status/1107419421105102848 |website=Twitter |accessdate=23 June 2019 |language=en |date=17 March 2019}}</ref> In an article by the Italian newspaper Vietato Parlare, Izabella says: \"''In relation to the rest of the world, the EU, the government and other rulers are the extremists. Who else wants to exterminate their own people? The left is fun ... On the one hand, he wants variety - at the same time, there is no diversity, because he wants everyone to be the same''\".<ref>{{cite news |title=La svedese Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi come Greta Thunberg ma per lei l'oblio dei media (The Swedish Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi as Greta Thunberg) |url=https://www.vietatoparlare.it/la-svedese-izabella-nilsson-jarvandi-come-greta-gutenberg-ma-per-lei-oblio-dei-media/ |accessdate=23 June 2019 |agency=Vietato Parlare |issue=Article |publisher=Vietato Parlare |date=24 April 2019 |language=it-IT}}</ref> In an article by My Nation, Izabella said \"''The Swedes may not demonstrate in the same way as the French, but that one should be careful while angering the sons and daughters of the Vikings preparing for a rebellion''.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=My Nation |first1=Team |title='Children shouldn't work in fields, but on dreams' |url=https://www.mynation.com/world/children-should-not-work-in-fields-but-on-dreams-world-day-against-child-labour-today-psz01j |accessdate=23 June 2019 |work=Asianet News Network Pvt Ltd |agency=Asianet News Media & Entertainment |issue=Article}}</ref>\n\n== Public praise ==\nJarvandi was praised by a reporter for being brave and \"standing up for her values\" on April 24, 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Make The West Great Again |first1=Evan |title=The anti-Greta |url=https://makethewestgreatagain.wordpress.com/2019/04/24/the-anti-greta/ |accessdate=23 June 2019 |agency=Make The West Great Again |issue=Article |publisher=Make The West Great Again |date=24 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref> She has also received positive feedback from Swedens conservative and nationalist establishment. On January 2019, Jarvandi was praised for her bravery by reporter Matthias Feinbork of the German Die Weltwoche.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Feinbork |first1=Matthias |title=Wir basteln uns eine KlimatIkone (Translation: We make a climate icon of the WEF, the 16-year-old poster girl of climate protection, Greta Thunberg, is swarming around. Her Swedish colleague Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi, 15, is hardly heard. I wonder why?) |url=https://www.weltwoche.ch/ausgaben/2019-4/artikel/wir-basteln-uns-eine-klima-ikone-die-weltwoche-ausgabe-4-2019.html |accessdate=23 June 2019 |work=www.weltwoche.ch |agency=Die Weltwoche |issue=Article}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nilsson Jarvandi, Izabella}}\n[[Category:2003 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Swedish activists]]\n[[Category:Swedish nationalists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Sources|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi\n| birth_place        = [[Gothenburg]], Sweden.\n| nationality        = Swedish\n| occupation         = activist, debater and orator.\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|2003|11|25}}\n}}\n\n'''Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi''' (born November 25, 2003)<ref>{{cite web |title=Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi {{!}} Ratsit.se |url=https://www.ratsit.se/20031125-Izabella_Zhila_Maria_Nilsson_Jarvandi_Angered/nukoj9Zj4Ba_oTT6_HYUQ8po1f1xaYVWPytzAzoclrg |website=www.ratsit.se | accessdate=13 December 2019 |language=sv-se}}</ref> is a Swedish activist and protester part of the [[Yellow vests movement|Yellow vests]] known for having held a protest speech at [[Mynttorget]] in [[Gothenburg]] against Sweden's signing of the UN contract of [[Global Compact for Migration]] on December 9, 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zackrisson |first1=Pelle |title=Janouch: 'Vi har ingen kvinnofrid l\u00e4ngre' (We have no safety for women any more) |url=https://nyheteridag.se/janouch-vi-har-ingen-kvinnofrid-langre/ |accessdate=23 June 2019 |agency=Publicism NITEK AB |issue=\"Isabella Nilsson Jarvandi is one of the girls engaged in this) |publisher=Jakob Bergman |date=16 December 2018 |language=sv-SE}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=SVENSSON |first1=TOBIAS |title=Intervju med Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi: \"Skulle inte f\u00f6rv\u00e5na mig om det blir inb\u00f6rdeskrig\" (Wouldn't surprise me if there is an outbreak of civil war) |url=https://www.nyatider.nu/intervju-med-izabella-nilsson-jarvandi-skulle-inte-forvana-mig-om-det-blir-inbordeskrig/ |accessdate=23 June 2019 |work=article |agency=Fria Tider |issue=Yellow vests |publisher=AlternaMedia AB, V\u00e1vra Suk. |date=1 May 2019 |language=sv-SE}}</ref> She has also held speeches in [[Helsingborg]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Skandinaviska F\u00f6rbundet |first1=Skandinaviska F\u00f6rbundet |title=Protester i Helsingborg kl 12.00 nu p\u00e5 l\u00f6rdag den 15/12 (Protest in Helsingborg now against the FN Migration contract) |url=http://skandinaviskfrihet.se/protester-i-helsingborg-kl-12-00-nu-pa-lordag-den-15-12/ |accessdate=23 June 2019 |agency=Skandinavisk frihet |issue=Event |publisher=Skandinaviska F\u00f6rbundet |date=13 December 2018 |language=sv-SE}}</ref> and [[Stockholm]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Skogssj\u00f6n |first1=Skogssj\u00f6n |title=Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi \u2013 Protest mot Globalismen i Stockholm (Protest against globalism in Stockholm) |url=https://idreporter.net/v/izabella-nilsson-jarvandi-protest-mot-globalismen-i-stockholm-P5CsnZejJzU.html |website=idreporter.net |publisher=idreporter.net}}</ref> Jarvandi is mentioned in the book \"''Tutto quello che c'\u00e8 da sapere sul clima''\" by Thomas Pedretti.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Pedretti |first1=Thomas |title=Tutto quello che c'\u00e8 da sapere sul clima |date=2019 |publisher= |isbn=9780244777067 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=miWUDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA22&dq=izabella+nilsson+jarvandi#v=onepage&q=izabella%20nilsson%20jarvandi&f=false |language=it}}</ref> She is also mentioned in Antonio Giangrande's \"''Italia allo specchio il DNA deli italiani anno 2019 quarta parte. La cultura ed i media''\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=GIANGRANDE |first1=ANTONIO |title=ITALIA ALLO SPECCHIO IL DNA DEGLI ITALIANI ANNO 2019 QUARTA PARTE. LA CULTURA ED I MEDIA |date=2019 |publisher=Antonio Giangrande |page=133 |edition=olym 168 av L\u2019Italia del Trucco, l\u2019Italia che siamo |url=https://books.google.com/?id=P1yHDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA133&dq=izabella+nilsson+jarvandi#v=onepage&q=izabella%20nilsson%20jarvandi&f=false |language=it}}</ref>\n\nDue to her age and politics, Jarvandi has been called the \"anti-[[Greta Thunberg]]\".\n\n== Background ==\nIzabella Nilsson Jarvandi has Iranian and Swedish heritage. Her father came from [[Iran]] and her mother is Swedish. Jarvandi grew up in a high-crime suburb in Gothenburg. She studied at a calm elementary school but she experienced the segregation through friends and family members who witnessed amongst segregated immigrants, and second generation immigrants, language deficients, [[maladaptation]], racism, crime, sexual harassments and drugs. In an interview with [[Mikael Willgert]], the host on [[Svensk Webbtelevision|Swebbtv]], Jarvandi explains that there have been incidents of rape on Swedish school property and that many teachers are afraid of opposing students.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Willger of Swebbtv |first1=Mikael |title=L\u00f6rdagsintervju 44 \u2013 Izabella 15 \u00e5r, om livet som ton\u00e5ring och nationalist. (Saturday interview with Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi and how it is like to be a 15 year old nationalist) |url=https://www.swebbtv.se/blogg/242-lordagsintervju-44-izabella-15-ar-om-livet-som-tonaring-och-nationalist |website=SwebbTV |publisher=Svensk Webbtelevision AB 2019 |accessdate=23 June 2019 |language=sv-se}}</ref>\n\n== Politics ==\nJarvandi has stated that she is \"''upset, angry and devastated''\" over the Swedish governments politics in multiculturalism and integration of immigrants.<ref>{{cite web |last1=ett SUVER\u00c4NT Sverige. |first1=Stockholmare f\u00f6r |title=G\u00e4stinl\u00e4gg: Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi \u2013 Mitt liv har pr\u00e4glats av systemfel \u2013 Stockholmare f\u00f6r ett suver\u00e4nt Sverige (Guest publication: Stockholmers for a great Sweden) |url=http://svenskt.bloggo.nu/Gastinlagg-Izabella-Nilsson-Jarvandi---Mitt-liv-har-praglats-av-systemfel/ |publisher=ett SUVER\u00c4NT Sverige. |accessdate=23 June 2019}}</ref> In an article by Katerina Magasin, published on December 2018, Jarvandi wrote an article saying \"''I am so angry at the politicians in the parliament \u2013 Sweden was a great country''!\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Janouch |first1=Katerina |title=Izabella, 15 \u00e5r: \"Jag \u00e4r s\u00e5 arg p\u00e5 politikerna i Riksdagen \u2013 Sverige har varit ett bra land\" (Translation: I am so angry at the politicians at the parliament \u2013 Sweden was a great country!) |url=http://katerinamagasin.se/izabella-15-ar-jag-ar-sa-arg-pa-politikerna-riksdagen-sverige-har-varit-ett-bra-land/ |accessdate=23 June 2019 |agency=Katerina Magasin |issue=Debate article |publisher=Katerina Janouch |date=18 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Maria |first1=Ingrid och |title=15-\u00e5riga Izabella leder FN-protesterna \u2013 \"det \u00e4r min framtid\" (15 year old Izabella leads protest against UN \u2013 \"Its my future\") |url=https://www.ingridochmaria.se/2018/12/20/blir-izabella-15-var-forsta-kvinnliga-statsminister/ |accessdate=23 June 2019 |agency=Ingrid och Maria |publisher=Ingrid och Maria |date=20 December 2018 |language=sv-SE}}</ref> According to an article by the Italian newspaper Lettera Donna, Jarvandi is \"''a young political activist who is against globalism and who seeks the truth and justice for my beloved Sweden''\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Donna |first1=Lettera |title=L'anti-Greta \u00e8 sovranista (e pro-famiglia tradizionale) (Translation: Who is Izabella Jarvandi, the 15-year-old Swedish against gender and migrants?) |url=https://www.letteradonna.it/it/articoli/ritratti/2019/04/23/izabella-nilsson-jarvandi-svezia-gender/28200/ |accessdate=23 June 2019 |work=LetteraDonna |agency=LetteraDonna |issue=Article |publisher=\u00a9 RIPRODUZIONE RISERVATA |date=23 April 2019 |language=it}}</ref> She has been called the Anti-[[Greta Thunberg|Greta]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bianchi |first1=Leonardo |last2=VICE |first2=Redazione |title=La vera storia dietro 'l'anti-Greta Thunberg' di cui parlano i media italiani (Translation: The real story behind 'the anti-Greta Thunberg spoken of by the Italian media. The 15 year old Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi is presented as Thunberg's perfect nemesis, but we only talk so stubbornly in Italy) |url=https://www.vice.com/it/article/bj9zdq/izabella-nilsson-jarvandi-greta-thunberg |accessdate=23 June 2019 |work=Article |agency=Vice |date=25 April 2019 |language=it}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Inrikes |first1=Fria Tider |title=Greta Thunberg: \"M\u00e4nsklighetens st\u00f6rsta kris n\u00e5gonsin\" (Greta Thunberg: Humanitys greatest threat) |url=https://www.friatider.se/greta-thunberg-m-nsklighetens-st-rsta-kris-n-gonsin |accessdate=23 June 2019 |work=Fria Tider |agency=Fria Tider |issue=Article \"Izabella Jarvandi, sometimes called Anti\u2013Greta\") |publisher=Fria Tider |language=sv}}</ref> Jarvandi has 7200 followers on Twitter. In an article by Fidelity News on March 2019, Jarvandi is described as opposing globalism, mass-migration, and gender ideology which she believes spread disinformation amongst Swedish youngsters.<ref>{{cite news |last1=BARBATO |first1=MARIO |title=Chi \u00e8 Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi, la 15enne svedese idolo dei sovranisti? (Translation: Who is Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi, the sovereign idol?) |url=https://news.fidelityhouse.eu/esteri/chi-e-izabella-nilsson-jarvandi-la-15enne-svedese-idolo-dei-sovranisti-411442.html |accessdate=23 June 2019 |work=Fidelity News |agency=Fidelity News |issue=Article |publisher=Horizon Group |date=6 May 2019 |language=it}}</ref> Jarvandi supports the Hungarian government led by [[Viktor Orb\u00e1n]].<ref>{{cite news |title=)Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi, (l'altra) ragazza (costruita) questa volta anti gender e anti migranti (Translation: Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi, (the other) girl (built) this time anti-gender and anti-migrants |url=http://www.ticinolive.ch/2019/04/24/jarvandi-nilsson-laltra-ragazza-costruita-questa-volta-anti-gender-e-anti-migranti/ |accessdate=23 June 2019 |work=Ticinolive |agency=Ticino Live |issue=Debate |publisher=Quotidiano della Svizzera italiana |date=24 April 2019 |language=it-IT}}</ref> In an article by the French newspaper Bvoltaire, Jarvandi is quoted saying \"''I will never be silenced and I will never forgive the politicians for all the harm they have done to my dear Sweden [...] I am convinced that the gods are watching and I know that traitors will one day be judged severely''\", Izabella fumed as she spoke in the streets of the Scandinavian cities.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bernadac |first1=J.-P. Fabre |title=En Su\u00e8de, Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi, ou l'anti-Greta Thunberg ? (Translation: And the Swedish girl, Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi, the Anti-Greta Thunberg? |url=https://www.bvoltaire.fr/en-suede-izabella-nilsson-jarvandi-ou-lanti-greta-thunberg/ |accessdate=23 June 2019 |work=Article |agency=Boulevard Voltaire |publisher=Boulevard Voltaire |date=28 April 2019 |language=fr-FR}}</ref> The French politician and Secretary General of Parti de la France Thomas Joly supported Jarvandi.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Joly |first1=Thomas |title=En Su\u00e8de, Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi, l'anti-Greta Thunberg (Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi, the anti-Greta Thunberg) |url=http://www.thomasjoly.fr/2019/04/en-suede-izabella-nilsson-jarvandi-l-anti-greta-thunberg.html |accessdate=23 June 2019 |work=Le blog politique de Thomas JOLY |agency=Le blog politique de Thomas Joly |publisher=Thomas Joly |date=2019 |language=fr}}</ref> In an article by Der Freie Welt published on March 2019, Jarvandi is described as \"''being in while Greta is out''\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dinnebin |first1=Micha |title=Greta ist \"out\", Izabella ist \"in\" |url=https://www.freiewelt.net/blog/greta-ist-out-izabella-ist-in-10077221/ |accessdate=23 June 2019 |work=FreieWelt.net |agency=Der Freie Welt (the free will) |date=2019 |language=de}}</ref> On March 17, 2019, Jarvandi tweeted saying \"You who have the audacity to harass me for my opinions are only proving me right. It is because of people like you and actions like yours I am fighting and I will not bow nor surrender. We were born free and I intend future generations to be as well\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jarvandi |first1=Izabella Nilsson |title=You who have the audacity to harass me for my opinions are only proving me right. It is because of people like you and actions like yours I am fighting and I will not bow nor surrender We were born free and I intend future generations to be as well |url=https://twitter.com/izabellamarianj/status/1107419421105102848 |website=Twitter |accessdate=23 June 2019 |language=en |date=17 March 2019}}</ref> In an article by the Italian newspaper Vietato Parlare, Izabella says: \"''In relation to the rest of the world, the EU, the government and other rulers are the extremists. Who else wants to exterminate their own people? The left is fun ... On the one hand, he wants variety - at the same time, there is no diversity, because he wants everyone to be the same''\".<ref>{{cite news |title=La svedese Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi come Greta Thunberg ma per lei l'oblio dei media (The Swedish Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi as Greta Thunberg) |url=https://www.vietatoparlare.it/la-svedese-izabella-nilsson-jarvandi-come-greta-gutenberg-ma-per-lei-oblio-dei-media/ |accessdate=23 June 2019 |agency=Vietato Parlare |issue=Article |publisher=Vietato Parlare |date=24 April 2019 |language=it-IT}}</ref> In an article by My Nation, Izabella said \"''The Swedes may not demonstrate in the same way as the French, but that one should be careful while angering the sons and daughters of the Vikings preparing for a rebellion''.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=My Nation |first1=Team |title='Children shouldn't work in fields, but on dreams' |url=https://www.mynation.com/world/children-should-not-work-in-fields-but-on-dreams-world-day-against-child-labour-today-psz01j |accessdate=23 June 2019 |work=Asianet News Network Pvt Ltd |agency=Asianet News Media & Entertainment |issue=Article}}</ref>\n\n== Public praise ==\nJarvandi was praised by a reporter for being brave and \"standing up for her values\" on April 24, 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Make The West Great Again |first1=Evan |title=The anti-Greta |url=https://makethewestgreatagain.wordpress.com/2019/04/24/the-anti-greta/ |accessdate=23 June 2019 |agency=Make The West Great Again |issue=Article |publisher=Make The West Great Again |date=24 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref> She has also received positive feedback from Swedens conservative and nationalist establishment. On January 2019, Jarvandi was praised for her bravery by reporter Matthias Feinbork of the German Die Weltwoche.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Feinbork |first1=Matthias |title=Wir basteln uns eine KlimatIkone (Translation: We make a climate icon of the WEF, the 16-year-old poster girl of climate protection, Greta Thunberg, is swarming around. Her Swedish colleague Izabella Nilsson Jarvandi, 15, is hardly heard. I wonder why?) |url=https://www.weltwoche.ch/ausgaben/2019-4/artikel/wir-basteln-uns-eine-klima-ikone-die-weltwoche-ausgabe-4-2019.html |accessdate=23 June 2019 |work=www.weltwoche.ch |agency=Die Weltwoche |issue=Article}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nilsson Jarvandi, Izabella}}\n[[Category:2003 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Swedish activists]]\n[[Category:Swedish nationalists]]\n", "name_user": "NASCARfan0548", "label": "safe", "comment": "Importing Wikidatashort description: \"Swedish activist and member of the Yellow vests\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Izabella_Nilsson_Jarvandi"}
{"title_page": "Wolcott Curran Collective", "text_new": "<!-- EDIT BELOW THIS LINE -->\n{{short description|Heavy instrumental soul music}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Wolcott Curran Collective\n| image            = [[File:AnnieWolcott photo SeanWolcott CraigCurran1a.jpg|thumb|Photo by Annie Wolcott]]\n| caption          = Sean Wolcott and Craig Curran recording at Soundview Analog\n| image_size       = \n| background       = group_or_band\n| origin           = [[Seattle, Washington]], U.S.\n| genre            = Instrumental, Soul\n| years_active     = 2019\u2013present\n| label            = Clockwork\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = {{URL|wolcottcurrancollective.com/}}\n| current_members  = Craig Curran<br />Sean Wolcott\n| past_members     = \n}}\n'''Wolcott Curran Collective''' is an instrumental group from [[Seattle]], [[Washington]]. The duo is comprised of [[Fleet Foxes]] former bassist, [[Craig Curran]] and guitarist, [[Sean Wolcott]] <ref>{{cite web |title=Wolcott Curran Collective |url=https://www.wolcottcurrancollective.com/about |website=Wolcott Curran Collective |accessdate=16 March 2020 |pages=1}}</ref>. The band has released two singles so far in their career; \"[https://soundcloud.com/wolcottcurrancollective/wolcott-curran-collective-devil-in-the-details Devil in the Details]\" and \"[https://soundcloud.com/wolcottcurrancollective/good-luck-with-that Good Luck With That]\" both of which have been released by Clockwork <ref>{{cite web |title=Wolcott Curran Collective Apple Music |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/good-luck-with-that-single/1499183050 |website=Apple Music |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Wolcott Curran Collective Soundcloud |url=https://soundcloud.com/wolcottcurrancollective |website=Soundcloud |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>. The latter of which has been featured in [[Spotify]]\u2019s instrumental funk playlist, which has around 185,000 followers <ref>{{cite web |title=WCC Spotify Instagram Post |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B89ilPEpUQ3/ |website=Instagram |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>. The song has been streamed all around the world <ref>{{cite web |title=Analog audio artifacts fill this Everett recording studio |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/analog-audio-artifacts-fill-this-everett-recording-studio/ |website=Herald Net |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Style==\nThe duo's music is recorded in a way that is similar to how many great records were made before them. Joining up with talented local Seattle musicians and recording live, directly to tape through original 1940s-1960s equipment at Wolcott\u2019s studio, [[Soundview Analog Recorders]] <ref>{{cite web |title=Analog audio artifacts fill this Everett recording studio|url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/analog-audio-artifacts-fill-this-everett-recording-studio |website=Herald Net |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>, the result is \"an organic, raw, and timeless sound\" <ref>{{cite web |title=Wolcott Curran Collective - About |url=https://www.wolcottcurrancollective.com/about |website=Wolcottcurrancollective |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\n== Discography ==\n\n'''Singles'''\n*\"Devil in the Details\" (Clockwork, 2019)\n*\"Good Luck With That\" (Clockwork, 2020)\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|wolcottcurrancollective.com}}\n\n== References ==\n", "text_old": "<!-- EDIT BELOW THIS LINE -->\n{{short description|Heavy instrumental soul music}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Wolcott Curran Collective\n| image            = [[File:AnnieWolcott photo SeanWolcott CraigCurran1a.jpg|thumb|Photo shot by Annie Wolcott]]\n| caption          = Sean Wolcott and Craig Curran recording at Soundview Analog\n| image_size       = \n| background       = group_or_band\n| origin           = [[Seattle, Washington]], U.S.\n| genre            = Instrumental, Soul\n| years_active     = 2019\u2013present\n| label            = Clockwork\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = {{URL|wolcottcurrancollective.com/}}\n| current_members  = Craig Curran<br />Sean Wolcott\n| past_members     = \n}}\n'''Wolcott Curran Collective''' is an instrumental group from [[Seattle]], [[Washington]]. The duo is comprised of [[Fleet Foxes]] former bassist, [[Craig Curran]] and guitarist, [[Sean Wolcott]] <ref>{{cite web |title=Wolcott Curran Collective |url=https://www.wolcottcurrancollective.com/about |website=Wolcott Curran Collective |accessdate=16 March 2020 |pages=1}}</ref>. The band has released two singles so far in their career; \"[https://soundcloud.com/wolcottcurrancollective/wolcott-curran-collective-devil-in-the-details Devil in the Details]\" and \"[https://soundcloud.com/wolcottcurrancollective/good-luck-with-that Good Luck With That]\" both of which have been released by Clockwork <ref>{{cite web |title=Wolcott Curran Collective Apple Music |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/good-luck-with-that-single/1499183050 |website=Apple Music |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Wolcott Curran Collective Soundcloud |url=https://soundcloud.com/wolcottcurrancollective |website=Soundcloud |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>. The latter of which has been featured in [[Spotify]]\u2019s instrumental funk playlist, which has around 185,000 followers <ref>{{cite web |title=WCC Spotify Instagram Post |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B89ilPEpUQ3/ |website=Instagram |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>. The song has been streamed all around the world <ref>{{cite web |title=Analog audio artifacts fill this Everett recording studio |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/analog-audio-artifacts-fill-this-everett-recording-studio/ |website=Herald Net |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Style==\nThe duo's music is recorded in a way that is similar to how many great records were made before them. Joining up with talented local Seattle musicians and recording live, directly to tape through original 1940s-1960s equipment at Wolcott\u2019s studio, [[Soundview Analog Recorders]] <ref>{{cite web |title=Analog audio artifacts fill this Everett recording studio|url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/analog-audio-artifacts-fill-this-everett-recording-studio |website=Herald Net |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>, the result is \"an organic, raw, and timeless sound\" <ref>{{cite web |title=Wolcott Curran Collective - About |url=https://www.wolcottcurrancollective.com/about |website=Wolcottcurrancollective |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\n== Discography ==\n\n'''Singles'''\n*\"Devil in the Details\" (Clockwork, 2019)\n*\"Good Luck With That\" (Clockwork, 2020)\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|wolcottcurrancollective.com}}\n\n== References ==\n", "name_user": "Sullycide", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wolcott_Curran_Collective"}
{"title_page": "National Assembly of Tajikistan", "text_new": "{{Expand language|topic=|langcode=fr|otherarticle=\nAssembl\u00e9e nationale (Tadjikistan)|date=January 2020}}\nThe '''National Assembly''' (''Majlisi milli'') is the upper chamber of [[Tajikistan]]'s bicameral [[Supreme Assembly (Tajikistan)|parliament]]. It has 33 members : 25 elected for a five-year term by deputies of local majlisi and 8 appointed by the president. By right, former presidents are members for life.<ref>National Assembly (''Majlisi milli''): [http://www.majmilli.tj official website]</ref> [[Mahmadsaid Ubaydulloyev]] was Chairman of the Majlisi milli from April 17, 2000.<ref>RFE/RL Newsline, Vol. 4. No. 77. 00-04-18</ref>\n\nTwenty-five members were elected on March 27, 2020 and President Rahmon appointed one quarter of the members in April, bringing the total number of members to thirty-one.<ref name=\"speech\">{{cite web|url=http://moh.tj/president-emomali-rahmon-attends-first-session-of-sixth-convocation-of-national-assembly/?lang=en|title=PRESIDENT EMOMALI RAHMON ATTENDS FIRST SESSION OF SIXTH CONVOCATION OF NATIONAL ASSEMBLY|date=20 April 2020|accessdate=20 April 2020|website=[[Ministry of Health (Tajikistan)|Ministry of Health]]|quote=Twenty-five members of the National Assembly were elected on March 27 and in accordance of his constitutional competence President Rahmon appointed one quarter of the members of the National Assembly on Wednesday. The National Assembly consist is of 31 members.{...}I would also like to congratulate Rustami Emomali on his election as the Chairman of the Majlisi Milli of Majlisi Oli (National Assembly of the Parliament) of the Republic of Tajikistan, Ahmadzoda Rajabboy and Yodgor Fayzov as Principal Deputy Chairman and Deputy Chairman of the Senate and wish them successes as well.}}</ref>\n==Chairmen of Majlisi milli==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!President\n!Took office\n!Left office\n|-\n|[[Mahmadsaid Ubaydulloyev]]<ref>http://archive.ipu.org/parline-e/reports/2366_A.htm</ref>\n|17 April 2000\n|\n|-\n|[[Rustam Emomali|Rustami Emomali]]<ref name=\"speech\"/>\n|2020\n|Incumbent\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{National upper houses}}\n\n{{legislature-stub}}\n{{Tajikistan-gov-stub}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Government of Tajikistan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expand language|topic=|langcode=fr|otherarticle=\nAssembl\u00e9e nationale (Tadjikistan)|date=January 2020}}\nThe '''National Assembly''' (''Majlisi milli'') is the upper chamber of [[Tajikistan]]'s bicameral [[Supreme Assembly (Tajikistan)|parliament]]. It has 33 members : 25 elected for a five-year term by deputies of local majlisi and 8 appointed by the president. By right, former presidents are members for life<ref>National Assembly (''Majlisi milli''): [http://www.majmilli.tj official website]</ref> [[Mahmadsaid Ubaydulloyev]] was Chairman of the Majlisi milli from April 17, 2000.<ref>RFE/RL Newsline, Vol. 4. No. 77. 00-04-18</ref>\n\nTwenty-five members were elected on March 27, 2020 and President Rahmon appointed one quarter of the members in April, bringing the total number of members to thirty-one.<ref name=\"speech\">{{cite web|url=http://moh.tj/president-emomali-rahmon-attends-first-session-of-sixth-convocation-of-national-assembly/?lang=en|title=PRESIDENT EMOMALI RAHMON ATTENDS FIRST SESSION OF SIXTH CONVOCATION OF NATIONAL ASSEMBLY|date=20 April 2020|accessdate=20 April 2020|website=[[Ministry of Health (Tajikistan)|Ministry of Health]]|quote=Twenty-five members of the National Assembly were elected on March 27 and in accordance of his constitutional competence President Rahmon appointed one quarter of the members of the National Assembly on Wednesday. The National Assembly consist is of 31 members.{...}I would also like to congratulate Rustami Emomali on his election as the Chairman of the Majlisi Milli of Majlisi Oli (National Assembly of the Parliament) of the Republic of Tajikistan, Ahmadzoda Rajabboy and Yodgor Fayzov as Principal Deputy Chairman and Deputy Chairman of the Senate and wish them successes as well.}}</ref>\n==Chairmen of Majlisi milli==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!President\n!Took office\n!Left office\n|-\n|[[Mahmadsaid Ubaydulloyev]]<ref>http://archive.ipu.org/parline-e/reports/2366_A.htm</ref>\n|17 April 2000\n|\n|-\n|[[Rustam Emomali|Rustami Emomali]]<ref name=\"speech\"/>\n|2020\n|Incumbent\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{National upper houses}}\n\n{{legislature-stub}}\n{{Tajikistan-gov-stub}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Government of Tajikistan]]\n", "name_user": "Geographyinitiative", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Assembly_of_Tajikistan"}
{"title_page": "Hugh P. Boon", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name          = Hugh P. Boon\n|image         = \n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1831|07|28}}\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1908|01|14|1831|07|28}}\n|birth_place   = \n|death_place   = \n|placeofburial = \n|allegiance    ={{flag|United States of America|1861}}\n|branch        ={{army|USA}}\n|serviceyears  = August 1861 to 8 July 1865\n|rank          = Captain\n|unit          ={{Flagicon|West Virginia}} [[1st Regiment West Virginia Volunteer Cavalry]] - Company B\n|battles       = [[Battle of Sayler's Creek]]\n|awards        ={{Flagicon image|Medal of Honor ribbon.svg}} [[Medal of Honor]]\n}}\n\nCaptain '''Hugh P. Boon''' (July 28, 1831 \u2013 January 14, 1908) was an American soldier who fought in the [[American Civil War]]. Boon received the country's highest award for bravery during combat, the [[Medal of Honor]], for his action during the [[Battle of Sayler's Creek]] in [[Virginia]] on 6 April 1865. He was honored with the award on 3 May 1865.<ref name=\"History\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.history.army.mil/html/moh/civwaral.html |title=Civil War (A-L) Medal of Honor Recipients |accessdate=14 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"CMOHS\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cmohs.org/recipient-detail/126/boon-hugh-p.php |title=Moon, Hugh P. |accessdate=25 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:Hugh P Boon marker.JPG|thumb|325 px|Marker at Washington (PA) Cemetery showing Boon is buried there]]\nBoon was born on 28 July 1831 to James and Margaret Miller Boone in [[Washington, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"CMOHS\"/> Prior to the outbreak of the war, Boon was involved in the grocery business. He first joined the war efforts as a volunteer in the three-month service and later enlisted into the [[1st Regiment West Virginia Volunteer Cavalry]] in August 1861,<ref name=\"History\"/> where he was eventually promoted to captain.<ref name=\"Obit\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.lindapages.com/wvcw/1wvc/1wvc-hpboon.htm |title=OBITUARIES: WAS BRAVE SOLDIER AND AN EXCELLENT CITIZEN: After Weeks of Illness, Captain Hugh P. Boone Answers the Last Summons |publisher=The Washington Pennsylvania Daily Reporter |date=January 15, 1908}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April 1865 Boon mounted his horse and entered the enemy's camp during the [[Battle of Sayler's Creek]], capturing a flag in the process. It is for this act of gallantry that he was presented with the Medal of Honor. During the war Boon was seriously injured, a bullet piercing through his neck in close proximity to his spinal cord, an injury which troubled him throughout the rest of his life.<ref name=\"Obit\"/>\n\nAfter the war Boon returned to the grocery business for a while but soon left to go into farming, a trade in which his family was involved while growing up. In October 1866 he married Hannah J. Cook, with whom he had one child. He was later a clerk in the A. B. Caldwell Co store. He died on 14 January 1908, after a period of illness.<ref name=\"Obit\"/>\n\n==Medal of Honor citation==\n{{quotation|Capture of flag.<ref name=\"History\"/><ref name=\"CMOHS\"/>}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n*[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: A\u2013F]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boon, Hugh P.}}\n[[Category:1831 births]]\n[[Category:1908 deaths]]\n[[Category:People of Pennsylvania in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Union Army officers]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name          = Hugh P. Boon\n|image         = \n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1831|07|28}}\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1908|01|14|1831|07|28}}\n|birth_place   = \n|death_place   = \n|placeofburial = \n|allegiance    ={{flag|United States of America|1861}}\n|branch        ={{army|USA}}\n|serviceyears  = August 1861 to 8 July 1865\n|rank          = Captain\n|unit          ={{Flagicon|Pennsylvania}} Company B, 1st West Virginia Cavalry.\n|battles       = [[Battle of Sayler's Creek]]\n|awards        ={{Flagicon image|Medal of Honor ribbon.svg}} [[Medal of Honor]]\n}}\n\nCaptain '''Hugh P. Boon''' (July 28, 1831 \u2013 January 14, 1908) was an American soldier who fought in the [[American Civil War]]. Boon received the country's highest award for bravery during combat, the [[Medal of Honor]], for his action during the [[Battle of Sayler's Creek]] in [[Virginia]] on 6 April 1865. He was honored with the award on 3 May 1865.<ref name=\"History\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.history.army.mil/html/moh/civwaral.html |title=Civil War (A-L) Medal of Honor Recipients |accessdate=14 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"CMOHS\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cmohs.org/recipient-detail/126/boon-hugh-p.php |title=Moon, Hugh P. |accessdate=25 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:Hugh P Boon marker.JPG|thumb|325 px|Marker at Washington (PA) Cemetery showing Boon is buried there]]\nBoon was born on 28 July 1831 to James and Margaret Miller Boone in [[Washington, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"CMOHS\"/> Prior to the outbreak of the war, Boon was involved in the grocery business. He first joined the war efforts as a volunteer in the three-month service and later enlisted into the [[1st West Virginia Volunteer Cavalry Regiment|1st West Virginia Volunteer Cavalry]] in August 1861,<ref name=\"History\"/> where he was eventually promoted to captain.<ref name=\"Obit\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.lindapages.com/wvcw/1wvc/1wvc-hpboon.htm |title=OBITUARIES: WAS BRAVE SOLDIER AND AN EXCELLENT CITIZEN: After Weeks of Illness, Captain Hugh P. Boone Answers the Last Summons |publisher=The Washington Pennsylvania Daily Reporter |date=January 15, 1908}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April 1865 Boon mounted his horse and entered the enemy's camp during the [[Battle of Sayler's Creek]], capturing a flag in the process. It is for this act of gallantry that he was presented with the Medal of Honor. During the war Boon was seriously injured, a bullet piercing through his neck in close proximity to his spinal cord, an injury which troubled him throughout the rest of his life.<ref name=\"Obit\"/>\n\nAfter the war Boon returned to the grocery business for a while but soon left to go into farming, a trade in which his family was involved while growing up. In October 1866 he married Hannah J. Cook, with whom he had one child. He was later a clerk in the A. B. Caldwell Co store. He died on 14 January 1908, after a period of illness.<ref name=\"Obit\"/>\n\n==Medal of Honor citation==\n{{quotation|Capture of flag.<ref name=\"History\"/><ref name=\"CMOHS\"/>}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n*[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: A\u2013F]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boon, Hugh P.}}\n[[Category:1831 births]]\n[[Category:1908 deaths]]\n[[Category:People of Pennsylvania in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Union Army officers]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n", "name_user": "Hhfjbaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hugh_P._Boon"}
{"title_page": "Mohmand Valley raid", "text_new": "{{short description|Joint US/Afgan special operations raid targeting an ISIL-KP compound in Nangarhar Province}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Mohmand Valley raid\n| width       =\n| partof      = the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n| date        = 26 \u2013 27 April 2017\n| place       = [[Mohmand Valley]], [[Achin District]], [[Nangarhar Province]], [[Afghanistan]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|34|04|24.01|N|70|37|52.37|E|}}\n| map_type    = Afghanistan\n| map_relief  = 1\n| map_size   = 300\n| map_marksize = \n| map_caption = Location of Achin District, where the raid took place \n| map_label   = Achin District\n| territory   =\n| result      = US/Afghan victory\n* [[Emir]] of ISIL-KP, killed<ref>https://www.cnn.com/2017/05/07/middleeast/isis-leader-killed-in-afghanistan/index.html</ref><ref>https://www.reuters.com/article/us-afghanistan-islamic-state/head-of-islamic-state-in-afghanistan-confirmed-killed-idUSKBN1830TR</ref><ref>https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-military-confirms-death-of-isis-afghanistan-leader-4645466/</ref><ref>https://abcnews.go.com/International/leader-isis-afghanistan-killed-april-raid-pentagon/story?id=47261842</ref><ref>https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/top-isis-commander-afghanistan-was-killed-raid-where-rangers-died-n756066</ref>\n| status      =\n| combatants_header =\n| combatant1  = {{flag|United States|1960}}<br>{{flag|Afghanistan}}\n| combatant2  = {{flagicon|Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant}} [[ISIL-KP]]\n| commander1  =\n| commander2  = {{flagicon|Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant}} [[Abdul Haseeb Logari]]{{KIA}}\n| units1 = {{flagicon|United States|1960}} '''[[United States Armed Forces]]'''\n*[[File:75th Ranger Regiment Distinctive Unit Insignia.svg|18px]] '''[[75th Ranger Regiment]]'''\n**[[File:3 Ranger Battalion Shoulder Sleeve Insignia.svg|24px]] [[3rd Ranger Battalion (United States)|3rd Ranger Battalion]]\n*{{flagicon image|Flag of the United States Air Force.svg}} [[United States Air Force|US Air Force]]\n{{flagicon|Afghanistan}} '''[[Afghan Armed Forces]]''' \n* [[Afghan Special Security Forces]] (Kteh Khas)<ref>http://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/10114/this-shadowy-afghan-unit-fights-alongside-americas-most-elite-forces</ref>\n| units2      = '''[[Military of ISIL]]'''\n* Khorasan Province\n| strength1   = {{flagicon|United States|1960}} 50 [[United States Army Rangers|Army Rangers]]<br>[[Lockheed AC-130|AC-130 gunships]]<br>[[General Dynamics F-16 Fighting Falcon|F-16 fighter jets]]<br>[[Boeing AH-64 Apache|AH-64 Apache attack helicopters]]<br>[[Unmanned combat aerial vehicle|Drones]]<br>{{flagicon|Afghanistan}} 40 commandos\n| strength2   = Unknown\n| strength3   =\n| casualties1 = {{flagicon|United States|1960}} 2 killed (possibly friendly fire)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.military.com/daily-news/2017/04/28/two-army-rangers-possibly-killed-friendly-fire-afghanistan.html|title=Two Army Rangers Possibly Killed by Friendly Fire in Afghanistan|first=Richard|last=Sisk|website=Military.com|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref><br>1 wounded\n| casualties2 = 36+ killed including several leaders {{small|(per U.S.)}}<ref>https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2017/may/8/abdul-hasib-head-isis-afghanistan-killed-us-afghan/</ref><ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/isis-commander-afghanistan-abdul-hasib-killed-special-forces-a7723376.html</ref>\n| casualties3 =\n| notes       =\n| campaignbox ={{Campaignbox US war in Afghanistan}}\n}}\nThe '''Mohmand Valley raid''' was a joint US/Afghan operation targeting an [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant - Khorasan Province]] (ISIL-KP) compound in the [[Achin District]] of [[Nangarhar Province]], that lasted from the night of 26 April to the early morning hours of the 27th, 2017. The raid resulted in the deaths of two [[United States Army Rangers|US Army Rangers]] from C and D Companies of the [[3rd Ranger Battalion (United States)|3rd Battalion]], [[75th Ranger Regiment (United States)|75th Ranger Regiment]], and the death of [[Abdul Haseeb Logari]], the leader of ISIL-KP, alongside several leaders, and up to 35 other militants according to [[The Pentagon]].\n\n== Background ==\n{{main article|2017 Nangarhar airstrike}} \nOn January 11, 2015 [[Hafiz Saeed Khan]] a former member of [[Tehrik-i-Taliban]] and the [[Afghan Taliban]] alongside other former [[Taliban]] leaders pledged allegiance to [[Abu Bakr Al-Baghdadi]], forming the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant \u2013 Khorasan Province]] and becoming the group's [[emir]]. Seven months later the [[Islamic Movement of Uzbekistan]] pledged allegiance to ISIL and claimed membership in the Khorasan group. Immediately after its formation the [[United States]] and [[Afghanistan]] targeted the group in airstrikes and raids. The group also suffered major setbacks while fighting the [[Taliban]]. \n\nIn July 2016, Hafiz was killed in a US drone strike, around eight months later the Afghan and US military began its offensive against the militant group in [[Nangarhar Province]] in March 2017.<ref>https://www.thebureauinvestigates.com/stories/2017-07-28/islamic-state-in-afghanistan-us-military</ref>\n\nLess than two weeks before the raid on April 13, 2017 and less than a mile away from the location of the raid, the US military [[2017 Nangarhar airstrike|dropped]] the largest non-nuclear bomb, a [[GBU-43/B MOAB]] on an ISIL-KP tunnel network once used by the [[Mujahideen]] during the [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War]] in the 80s and [[Osama Bin Laden]] during the [[United States invasion of Afghanistan|invasion of Afghanistan]] in 2001. The strike killed 96 militants according to an Afghan official.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/isis-fighters-killed-in-mother-of-all-bombs-moab-blast-2017-4|title=The 'Mother of All Bombs' blast site is still off-limits, but here's who it may have killed|first=Christopher|last=Woody|website=[[Business Insider]]|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt the time of the raid the group had been reduced to an estimated 700 fighters, down from 3,000 fighters at the group's peak, according to US officials.<ref>https://www.theatlantic.com/news/archive/2017/05/isis-afghanistan-abdul-hasib/525807/</ref>\n\n== Target ==\nThe target of the operation was a compound in the [[Mohmand Valley]] located less than a mile away from where the US dropped the [[GBU-43/B Massive Ordnance Air Blast|MOAB]] bomb. The compound was believed to have housed [[Abdul Haseeb Logari|Abdul Hasib]], a former [[Taliban]] commander before switching alliances to the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant - Khorasan Province|Islamic State - Khorasan Province]], he would eventually become the group's leader after his predecessor [[Hafiz Saeed Khan]] was killed in a US airstrike. Abdul had overseen several attacks against the Afghan Government including the [[March 2017 Kabul attack]] on a military hospital that killed nearly 100 people. Commanders decided to conduct a joint US/Afghan special forces raid over an airstrike because woman and children were believed to have been in the compound.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/07/world/asia/abdul-hasib-isis-leader-killed.html</ref><ref>https://heavy.com/news/2017/05/sheikh-abdul-hasib-dead-death-killed-isis-afghanistan-leader-raid-cameron-thomas-joshua-rodgers/</ref>\n\n== Raid ==\nAt around 10:30 on the night of 26 April, 50 U.S. Army Rangers from [[3rd Ranger Battalion (United States)|3rd Battalion]], [[75th Ranger Regiment]], alongside 40 Afghan commandos from the [[Special Security Forces]] (Kteh Khas), were inserted near the target site by helicopter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/10114/this-shadowy-afghan-unit-fights-alongside-americas-most-elite-forces|title=This Shadowy Afghan Unit Fights Alongside America's Most Elite Forces|first=Joseph|last=Trevithick|website=The Drive|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref> Almost immediately after landing the force came under heavy fire from multiple directions by entrenched enemy positions with the firefight being described as \"close quarters with enemy fire coming at 360 degrees\". As the joint American/Afghan force pushed through the difficult terrain under fire, they called in airstrikes from [[Lockheed AC-130|AC-130 gunships]], [[General Dynamics F-16 Fighting Falcon|F-16 fighter jets]], [[Boeing AH-64 Apache|AH-64 Apache attack helicopters]] and [[Unmanned combat aerial vehicle|drones]]. Early in the firefight two Army Rangers were critically wounded, possibly as a result of friendly fire, team members later denied the assertion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://taskandpurpose.com/rangers-reject-pentagon-friendly-fire-afghanistan|title=Rangers Reject DoD Claim Of \u2018Friendly Fire\u2019 In Afghanistan Deaths|date=28 April 2017|website=Task & Purpose|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.army.mil/article/187021/mattis_honors_army_rangers_killed_in_afghanistan|title=Mattis honors Army Rangers killed in Afghanistan|website=Army.mil|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref> The two wounded were medevaced by helicopter where they would later die from their injuries. Another Ranger was grazed by a bullet but left the battle on his own choosing.<ref>https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/least-2-u-s-service-members-killed-anti-isis-raid-n751826</ref> The raid lasted for more than three hours up to about 3:30&nbsp;a.m. and resulted in the death of the attended target with [[the Pentagon]] calling it as a success in degrading the group's ability to fight.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2017/04/28/526117060/the-pentagon-investigates-possible-friendly-fire-deaths-in-afghanistan|title=The Pentagon Investigates Possible Friendly Fire Deaths In Afghanistan|website=NPR.org|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/ct-2-army-rangers-killed-in-afghanistan-dover-photos-20170428-photogallery.html|title=2 Army Rangers killed in Afghanistan|website=Chicago Tribune|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/washington/la-na-essential-washington-updates-two-u-s-army-rangers-killed-in-eastern-1493413125-htmlstory.html|title=Pentagon says two Army Rangers may have been killed by friendly fire in Afghanistan|first=W. J.|last=Hennigan|website=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.army/%20times.com/news/your-army/2017/04/28/army-rangers-killed-in-afghanistan-were-possible-victims-of-friendly-fire/|title=Army Rangers killed in Afghanistan were possible victims of friendly fire|first=Meghann Myers, Andrew|last=deGrandpre|date=7 August 2017|website=Army Times|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/world/friendly-fire-may-killed-2-army-rangers-afghanistan|title=Friendly fire may have killed 2 Army Rangers in Afghanistan|date=28 April 2017|website=PBS NewsHour|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/pentagon-identifies-2-soldiers-killed-in-afghanistan-during-raid-on-isis/|title=Friendly fire may have killed Army Rangers during ISIS raid in Afghanistan|publisher=CBS News|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/friendly-fire-may-have-killed-the-two-us-soldiers-fighting-isis-in-afghanistan-a7708861.html|title=Pentagon says friendly fire may have killed two US soldiers in Afghanistan, not Isis|date=28 April 2017|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/least-2-u-s-service-members-killed-anti-isis-raid-n751826|title=Two U.S. Army Rangers killed in anti-ISIS raid in Afghanistan|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/27/us/politics/two-us-service-members-killed-in-afghanistan-pentagon-says.html|title=2 U.S. Service Members Killed in Afghanistan, Pentagon Says|first=Helene|last=Cooper|date=27 April 2017|accessdate=11 January 2019|website=New York Times}}</ref>\n\n=== Casualties ===\nAmong the dead were two Army Rangers identified as 22 year old Sgt. Joshua Rodgers of [[Bloomington, Illinois|Bloomington]], [[Illinois]] and 23 year old Sgt. Cameron Thomas of [[Kettering, Ohio|Kettering]], [[Ohio]]. Both of them enlisted in the [[United States Army|Army]] out of high school and were on their third deployments. Their rewards and decorations include the [[Army Good Conduct Medal]], [[Army Achievement Medal]], [[Army Service Ribbon]], [[Global War on Terrorism Service Medal]], [[Afghanistan Campaign Medal|Afghanistan Campaign Star]], and the [[NATO Medal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/news/local-military/for-kettering-army-ranger-service-was-all-lived-and-breathed/BHXEapzRnzfTAxChrsZoUN/|title=For Kettering Army Ranger, service was \u2018all he lived and breathed\u2019|author=Barrie Barber|website=Dayton Daily News|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pantagraph.com/herald-review/news/local/military/bloomington-soldier-killed-in-afghanistan-praised/article_c3cd3088-1d13-5d9b-9f12-960c477cdc80.html|title=Bloomington soldier killed in Afghanistan praised|author=LENORE SOBOTA |website=Pantagraph.com|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/11/world/asia/afghanistan-military-american-soldiers-deaths.html|title=All 6 U.S. Combat Deaths in Afghanistan in 2017 Were in Fight Against ISIS|first=Rod|last=Nordland|date=11 June 2017|accessdate=11 January 2019|website=New York Times}}</ref> Abdul Hasib, several more of the group's leaders, and about 35 other militants were killed in the raid [[The Pentagon]] stated.<ref>https://www.theatlantic.com/news/archive/2017/05/isis-afghanistan-abdul-hasib/525807/</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\nOn April 28, Afghan forces conducted an operation in the Mohmand Valley, reportedly killing 20 ISIL-KP militants the MoD said.<ref>https://www.tolonews.com/afghanistan/20-daesh-militants-killed-nangarhar</ref> Abdul Hassib would be replaced by [[Pakistani]] militant [[Abdul Rahman Ghaleb|Abu Saeed]], who would be killed by a US drone strike in [[Kunar Province]] on July 11, making him the third ISIL-KP [[emir]] killed since July 2016.<ref>https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-afghanistan-islamic-state/head-of-islamic-state-in-afghanistan-killed-pentagon-idUSKBN19Z26G</ref> On May 7, the US Military confirmed Hassib\u2019s death in a press release.\n\nArmy Ranger, [[Staff Sgt.]] Michael Young, a squad leader in C Company, [[3rd Ranger Battalion]], was credited for saving the lives of 22 Rangers during the raid. He was subsequently award the [[Silver Star]] in April 2018 for his actions.<ref>https://www.armytimes.com/news/your-army/2018/04/13/rangers-heroic-actions-saved-dozens-led-to-silver-star-medal/</ref><ref>https://www.stripes.com/news/army-ranger-awarded-silver-star-for-actions-in-deadly-terrifyingly-chaotic-fight-in-afghanistan-1.521975</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2017 in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Battles of the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Battle of Mohmand Valley]]\n[[Category:April 2017 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:Military operations involving the United States]]\n[[Category:Military operations involving Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Military operations involving the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Joint US/Afgan special operations raid targeting an ISIL-KP compound in Nangarhar Province}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Mohmand Valley raid\n| width       =\n| partof      = the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n| date        = 26 \u2013 27 April 2017\n| place       = [[Mohmand Valley]], [[Achin District]], [[Nangarhar Province]], [[Afghanistan]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|34|04|24.01|N|70|37|52.37|E|}}\n| map_type    = Afghanistan\n| map_relief  = 1\n| map_size   = 300\n| map_marksize = \n| map_caption = Location of Achin District, where the raid took place \n| map_label   = Achin District\n| territory   =\n| result      = US/Afghan victory\n* [[Emir]] of ISIL-KP, killed<ref>https://www.cnn.com/2017/05/07/middleeast/isis-leader-killed-in-afghanistan/index.html</ref><ref>https://www.reuters.com/article/us-afghanistan-islamic-state/head-of-islamic-state-in-afghanistan-confirmed-killed-idUSKBN1830TR</ref><ref>https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-military-confirms-death-of-isis-afghanistan-leader-4645466/</ref><ref>https://abcnews.go.com/International/leader-isis-afghanistan-killed-april-raid-pentagon/story?id=47261842</ref><ref>https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/top-isis-commander-afghanistan-was-killed-raid-where-rangers-died-n756066</ref>\n| status      =\n| combatants_header =\n| combatant1  = {{flag|United States|1960}}<br>{{flag|Afghanistan}}\n| combatant2  = {{flagicon|Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant}} [[ISIL-KP]]\n| commander1  =\n| commander2  = {{flagicon|Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant}} [[Abdul Haseeb Logari]]{{KIA}}\n| units1 = {{flagicon|United States|1960}} '''[[United States Armed Forces]]'''\n*[[File:75th Ranger Regiment Distinctive Unit Insignia.svg|18px]] '''[[75th Ranger Regiment]]'''\n**[[File:3 Ranger Battalion Shoulder Sleeve Insignia.svg|24px]] [[3rd Ranger Battalion (United States)|3rd Ranger Battalion]]\n*{{flagicon image|Flag of the United States Air Force.svg}} [[United States Air Force|US Air Force]]\n{{flagicon|Afghanistan}} '''[[Afghan Armed Forces]]''' \n* [[Afghan Special Security Forces]] (Kteh Khas)<ref>http://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/10114/this-shadowy-afghan-unit-fights-alongside-americas-most-elite-forces</ref>\n| units2      = '''[[Military of ISIL]]'''\n* Khorasan Province\n| strength1   = {{flagicon|United States|1960}} 50 [[United States Army Rangers|Army Rangers]]<br>[[Lockheed AC-130|AC-130 gunships]]<br>[[General Dynamics F-16 Fighting Falcon|F-16 fighter jets]]<br>[[Boeing AH-64 Apache|AH-64 Apache attack helicopters]]<br>[[Unmanned combat aerial vehicle|Drones]]<br>{{flagicon|Afghanistan}} 40 commandos\n| strength2   = Unknown\n| strength3   =\n| casualties1 = {{flagicon|United States|1960}} 2 killed (possibly friendly fire)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.military.com/daily-news/2017/04/28/two-army-rangers-possibly-killed-friendly-fire-afghanistan.html|title=Two Army Rangers Possibly Killed by Friendly Fire in Afghanistan|first=Richard|last=Sisk|website=Military.com|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref><br>1 wounded\n| casualties2 = 36+ killed including several leaders {{small|(per U.S.)}}<ref>https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2017/may/8/abdul-hasib-head-isis-afghanistan-killed-us-afghan/</ref><ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/isis-commander-afghanistan-abdul-hasib-killed-special-forces-a7723376.html</ref>\n| casualties3 =\n| notes       =\n| campaignbox ={{Campaignbox US war in Afghanistan}}\n}}\nThe '''Mohmand Valley raid''' was a joint US/Afghan operation targeting an [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant - Khorasan Province]] (ISIL-KP) compound in the [[Achin District]] of [[Nangarhar Province]], that lasted from the night of 26 April to the early morning hours of the 27th, 2017. The raid resulted in the deaths of two [[United States Army Rangers|US Army Rangers]] from C and D Companies of the [[3rd Ranger Battalion (United States)|3rd Battalion]], [[75th Ranger Regiment (United States)|75th Ranger Regiment]], and the death of [[Abdul Haseeb Logari]], the leader of ISIL-KP, alongside several leaders, and up to 35 other militants according to the [[The Pentagon]].\n\n== Background ==\n{{main article|2017 Nangarhar airstrike}} \nOn January 11, 2015 [[Hafiz Saeed Khan]] a former member of [[Tehrik-i-Taliban]] and the [[Afghan Taliban]] alongside other former [[Taliban]] leaders pledged allegiance to [[Abu Bakr Al-Baghdadi]], forming the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant \u2013 Khorasan Province]] and becoming the group's [[emir]]. Seven months later the [[Islamic Movement of Uzbekistan]] pledged allegiance to ISIL and claimed membership in the Khorasan group. Immediately after its formation the [[United States]] and [[Afghanistan]] targeted the group in airstrikes and raids. The group also suffered major setbacks while fighting the [[Taliban]]. \n\nIn July 2016, Hafiz was killed in a US drone strike, around eight months later the Afghan and US military began its offensive against the militant group in [[Nangarhar Province]] in March 2017.<ref>https://www.thebureauinvestigates.com/stories/2017-07-28/islamic-state-in-afghanistan-us-military</ref>\n\nLess than two weeks before the raid on April 13, 2017 and less than a mile away from the location of the raid, the US military [[2017 Nangarhar airstrike|dropped]] the largest non-nuclear bomb, a [[GBU-43/B MOAB]] on an ISIL-KP tunnel network once used by the [[Mujahideen]] during the [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War]] in the 80s and [[Osama Bin Laden]] during the [[United States invasion of Afghanistan|invasion of Afghanistan]] in 2001. The strike killed 96 militants according to an Afghan official.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/isis-fighters-killed-in-mother-of-all-bombs-moab-blast-2017-4|title=The 'Mother of All Bombs' blast site is still off-limits, but here's who it may have killed|first=Christopher|last=Woody|website=[[Business Insider]]|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt the time of the raid the group had been reduced to an estimated 700 fighters, down from 3,000 fighters at the group's peak, according to US officials.<ref>https://www.theatlantic.com/news/archive/2017/05/isis-afghanistan-abdul-hasib/525807/</ref>\n\n== Target ==\nThe target of the operation was a compound in the [[Mohmand Valley]] located less than a mile away from where the US dropped the [[GBU-43/B Massive Ordnance Air Blast|MOAB]] bomb. The compound was believed to have housed [[Abdul Haseeb Logari|Abdul Hasib]], a former [[Taliban]] commander before switching alliances to the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant - Khorasan Province|Islamic State - Khorasan Province]], he would eventually become the group's leader after his predecessor [[Hafiz Saeed Khan]] was killed in a US airstrike. Abdul had overseen several attacks against the Afghan Government including the [[March 2017 Kabul attack]] on a military hospital that killed nearly 100 people. Commanders decided to conduct a joint US/Afghan special forces raid over an airstrike because woman and children were believed to have been in the compound.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/07/world/asia/abdul-hasib-isis-leader-killed.html</ref><ref>https://heavy.com/news/2017/05/sheikh-abdul-hasib-dead-death-killed-isis-afghanistan-leader-raid-cameron-thomas-joshua-rodgers/</ref>\n\n== Raid ==\nAt around 10:30 on the night of 26 April, 50 U.S. Army Rangers from [[3rd Ranger Battalion (United States)|3rd Battalion]], [[75th Ranger Regiment]], alongside 40 Afghan commandos from the [[Special Security Forces]] (Kteh Khas), were inserted near the target site by helicopter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/10114/this-shadowy-afghan-unit-fights-alongside-americas-most-elite-forces|title=This Shadowy Afghan Unit Fights Alongside America's Most Elite Forces|first=Joseph|last=Trevithick|website=The Drive|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref> Almost immediately after landing the force came under heavy fire from multiple directions by entrenched enemy positions with the firefight being described as \"close quarters with enemy fire coming at 360 degrees\". As the joint American/Afghan force pushed through the difficult terrain under fire, they called in airstrikes from [[Lockheed AC-130|AC-130 gunships]], [[General Dynamics F-16 Fighting Falcon|F-16 fighter jets]], [[Boeing AH-64 Apache|AH-64 Apache attack helicopters]] and [[Unmanned combat aerial vehicle|drones]]. Early in the firefight two Army Rangers were critically wounded, possibly as a result of friendly fire, team members later denied the assertion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://taskandpurpose.com/rangers-reject-pentagon-friendly-fire-afghanistan|title=Rangers Reject DoD Claim Of \u2018Friendly Fire\u2019 In Afghanistan Deaths|date=28 April 2017|website=Task & Purpose|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.army.mil/article/187021/mattis_honors_army_rangers_killed_in_afghanistan|title=Mattis honors Army Rangers killed in Afghanistan|website=Army.mil|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref> The two wounded were medevaced by helicopter where they would later die from their injuries. Another Ranger was grazed by a bullet but left the battle on his own choosing.<ref>https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/least-2-u-s-service-members-killed-anti-isis-raid-n751826</ref> The raid lasted for more than three hours up to about 3:30&nbsp;a.m. and resulted in the death of the attended target with [[the Pentagon]] calling it as a success in degrading the group's ability to fight.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2017/04/28/526117060/the-pentagon-investigates-possible-friendly-fire-deaths-in-afghanistan|title=The Pentagon Investigates Possible Friendly Fire Deaths In Afghanistan|website=NPR.org|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/ct-2-army-rangers-killed-in-afghanistan-dover-photos-20170428-photogallery.html|title=2 Army Rangers killed in Afghanistan|website=Chicago Tribune|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/washington/la-na-essential-washington-updates-two-u-s-army-rangers-killed-in-eastern-1493413125-htmlstory.html|title=Pentagon says two Army Rangers may have been killed by friendly fire in Afghanistan|first=W. J.|last=Hennigan|website=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.army/%20times.com/news/your-army/2017/04/28/army-rangers-killed-in-afghanistan-were-possible-victims-of-friendly-fire/|title=Army Rangers killed in Afghanistan were possible victims of friendly fire|first=Meghann Myers, Andrew|last=deGrandpre|date=7 August 2017|website=Army Times|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/world/friendly-fire-may-killed-2-army-rangers-afghanistan|title=Friendly fire may have killed 2 Army Rangers in Afghanistan|date=28 April 2017|website=PBS NewsHour|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/pentagon-identifies-2-soldiers-killed-in-afghanistan-during-raid-on-isis/|title=Friendly fire may have killed Army Rangers during ISIS raid in Afghanistan|publisher=CBS News|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/friendly-fire-may-have-killed-the-two-us-soldiers-fighting-isis-in-afghanistan-a7708861.html|title=Pentagon says friendly fire may have killed two US soldiers in Afghanistan, not Isis|date=28 April 2017|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/least-2-u-s-service-members-killed-anti-isis-raid-n751826|title=Two U.S. Army Rangers killed in anti-ISIS raid in Afghanistan|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/27/us/politics/two-us-service-members-killed-in-afghanistan-pentagon-says.html|title=2 U.S. Service Members Killed in Afghanistan, Pentagon Says|first=Helene|last=Cooper|date=27 April 2017|accessdate=11 January 2019|website=New York Times}}</ref>\n\n=== Casualties ===\nAmong the dead were two Army Rangers identified as 22 year old Sgt. Joshua Rodgers of [[Bloomington, Illinois|Bloomington]], [[Illinois]] and 23 year old Sgt. Cameron Thomas of [[Kettering, Ohio|Kettering]], [[Ohio]]. Both of them enlisted in the [[United States Army|Army]] out of high school and were on their third deployments. Their rewards and decorations include the [[Army Good Conduct Medal]], [[Army Achievement Medal]], [[Army Service Ribbon]], [[Global War on Terrorism Service Medal]], [[Afghanistan Campaign Medal|Afghanistan Campaign Star]], and the [[NATO Medal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/news/local-military/for-kettering-army-ranger-service-was-all-lived-and-breathed/BHXEapzRnzfTAxChrsZoUN/|title=For Kettering Army Ranger, service was \u2018all he lived and breathed\u2019|author=Barrie Barber|website=Dayton Daily News|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pantagraph.com/herald-review/news/local/military/bloomington-soldier-killed-in-afghanistan-praised/article_c3cd3088-1d13-5d9b-9f12-960c477cdc80.html|title=Bloomington soldier killed in Afghanistan praised|author=LENORE SOBOTA |website=Pantagraph.com|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/11/world/asia/afghanistan-military-american-soldiers-deaths.html|title=All 6 U.S. Combat Deaths in Afghanistan in 2017 Were in Fight Against ISIS|first=Rod|last=Nordland|date=11 June 2017|accessdate=11 January 2019|website=New York Times}}</ref> Abdul Hasib, several more of the group's leaders, and about 35 other militants were killed in the raid [[The Pentagon]] stated.<ref>https://www.theatlantic.com/news/archive/2017/05/isis-afghanistan-abdul-hasib/525807/</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\nOn April 28, Afghan forces conducted an operation in the Mohmand Valley, reportedly killing 20 ISIL-KP militants the MoD said.<ref>https://www.tolonews.com/afghanistan/20-daesh-militants-killed-nangarhar</ref> Abdul Hassib would be replaced by [[Pakistani]] militant [[Abdul Rahman Ghaleb|Abu Saeed]], who would be killed by a US drone strike in [[Kunar Province]] on July 11, making him the third ISIL-KP [[emir]] killed since July 2016.<ref>https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-afghanistan-islamic-state/head-of-islamic-state-in-afghanistan-killed-pentagon-idUSKBN19Z26G</ref> On May 7, the US Military confirmed Hassib\u2019s death in a press release.\n\nArmy Ranger, [[Staff Sgt.]] Michael Young, a squad leader in C Company, [[3rd Ranger Battalion]], was credited for saving the lives of 22 Rangers during the raid. He was subsequently award the [[Silver Star]] in April 2018 for his actions.<ref>https://www.armytimes.com/news/your-army/2018/04/13/rangers-heroic-actions-saved-dozens-led-to-silver-star-medal/</ref><ref>https://www.stripes.com/news/army-ranger-awarded-silver-star-for-actions-in-deadly-terrifyingly-chaotic-fight-in-afghanistan-1.521975</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2017 in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Battles of the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Battle of Mohmand Valley]]\n[[Category:April 2017 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:Military operations involving the United States]]\n[[Category:Military operations involving Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Military operations involving the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]]\n", "name_user": "Ira Leviton", "label": "safe", "comment": "Deleted a duplicate \"the\".", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mohmand_Valley_raid"}
{"title_page": "DJ Stretch Armstrong", "text_new": "{{About|the DJ|the band|Stretch Arm Strong|the toy|Stretch Armstrong}}\n{{short description|New York-based DJ and music producer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = \n| image           = Stretch Armstrong and Bobbito Garcia in 2011.jpg\n| caption         = Armstrong (left) in 2011\n| birth_name      = Adrian Bartos\n| birth_date      = \n| birth_place     = \n| other_names     = \n| occupation      = \n| years_active    = \n| known_for       = ''[[The Stretch Armstrong and Bobbito Show]]''\n}}\n\n'''Adrian Bartos''' known professionally as '''DJ Stretch Armstrong''' is a New York-based [[Disc jockey|DJ]] and music producer, known as a former co-host of [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] radio show ''[[The Stretch Armstrong and Bobbito Show]]'', alongside [[Bobbito Garcia]]. \n\nFrom 1990\u201398, Bartos co-hosted ''[[The Stretch Armstrong and Bobbito Show]]'' on [[Columbia University]]'s [[WKCR]]. It featured exclusive demo tapes and in-studio freestyles from many then-unsigned hip hop artists such as [[Nas]],  [[Big Pun]], [[Jay-Z]], [[Busta Rhymes]], [[Fat Joe]], [[Cam'ron]], [[DMX (rapper)|DMX]], [[Wu-Tang Clan]], [[Fugees]], [[Talib Kweli]], [[Big L]] and [[The Notorious B.I.G.]] who later found great success on major record labels.<ref>Bobbito Garcia in ''[[ego trip (magazine)|ego trip]]'s Book of Rap Lists''. Sacha Jenkins, Elliott Wilson, Chairman Mao, Gabriel Alvarez & Brent Rollins. New York: St. Martin's Press, 1999 (pp. 110\u201311); {{ISBN|978-0-312-24298-5}}</ref> In 2020 the pair produced an album called ''No Requests'' with a group of musicians called the M19, named for a bus in Manhattan connecting the Upper East Side to the Upper West Side.<ref name=\"Cornish Lonsdorf 2020\">{{cite web | last=Cornish | first=Audie | last2=Lonsdorf | first2=Kat | title=On Their Debut Album, Stretch And Bobbito Are Taking 'No Requests' | website=WFAE | date=2020-01-17 | url=https://www.wfae.org/post/their-debut-album-stretch-and-bobbito-are-taking-no-requests | access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> The album is a reimagining of hip-hop's foundational songs with some updated lyrics and no sampling. <ref name=\"CBC 2020\">{{cite web | title=Hip-hop radio DJs Stretch and Bobbito on their debut album No Requests - CBC Radio | website=CBC | date=2020-01-27 | url=https://www.cbc.ca/radio/q/tuesday-jan-28-2020-stretch-and-bobbito-whoop-szo-and-more-1.5442122/hip-hop-radio-djs-stretch-and-bobbito-on-their-debut-album-no-requests-1.5442156 | access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nBartos co-hosted [[NPR|NPR's]] podcast ''What's Good with Stretch and Bobbito'' which began in 2017.<ref name=\"NPR\">{{cite web | title=Adrian \"Stretch\" Bartos | website=NPR.org | date=2017-07-18 | url=https://www.npr.org/people/537945398/adrian-stretch-bartos | access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref name=\"Nieman Lab 2017\">{{cite web | title=NPR is bringing back \u201990s hip-hop DJs Stretch and Bobbito | website=Nieman Lab | date=2017-04-19 | url=https://www.niemanlab.org/2017/04/npr-is-bringing-back-90s-hip-hop-djs-stretch-and-bobbito/ | access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref name=\"WAMU 2017\">{{cite web | title=Stretch & Bobbito On Race, Hip-Hop, And Belonging | website=WAMU | date=2017-07-26 | url=https://wamu.org/story/17/07/26/stretch-bobbito-on-race-hip-hop-and-belonging/ | access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> The show which was about art, politics, and sports, as well as music, interviewed people such as [[Dave Chappelle]] and [[Stevie Wonder]].<ref name=\"Blistein Blistein 2017\">{{cite web | last=Blistein | first=Jon | last2=Blistein | first2=Jon | title=Pioneering Rap DJs Stretch and Bobbito Detail New NPR Show | website=Rolling Stone | date=2017-04-19 | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/pioneering-rap-djs-stretch-and-bobbito-detail-new-npr-show-128762/ | access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nHis musical career, along with Garcia, was made into a movie [[Stretch and Bobbito: Radio That Changed Lives]], which was picked up by Netflix in 2015 on the 25th anniversary of the pair's radio show.<ref name=\"Vibe 2016\">{{cite web | title=DJ Stretch Armstrong Discusses 'Stretch & Bobbito' Documentary | website=Vibe | date=2016-11-03 | url=https://www.vibe.com/2016/11/dj-stretch-armstrong-no-sleep-book-documentary | access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref name=\" officialdon 2015\">{{cite web | author= officialdon | title=Stretch & Bobbito Film Highlights NYC Legends Who Put Lyricists On The Map | website=The Source | date=2015-10-09 | url=https://thesource.com/2015/10/09/stretch-bobbito-film-highlights-nyc-legends-who-put-lyricists-on-the-map/ | access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref name=\"Vibe 2020\">{{cite web | title=Stretch And Bobbito On Debut Album \"No Requests,\" Radio Legacy | website=Vibe | date=2020-02-05 | url=https://www.vibe.com/2020/02/stretch-and-bobbito-no-requests-feature | access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> [[The Source|The Source Magazine]] called their show \"The Best Hip Hop Radio Show of All Time\" in 1998.<ref name=\"Hip-Hop Radio Archive 1992\">{{cite web | title=The Stretch Armstrong and Bobbito Show | website=Hip-Hop Radio Archive | date=1992-11-19 | url=https://hiphopradioarchive.org/browse/shows/The+Stretch+Armstrong+and+Bobbito+Show/ | access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nBartos' first book, with archivist Evan Auerbach, ''No Sleep: NYC Nightlife Flyers 1988-1999 '', was released through Powerhouse Books.<ref name=\"powerHouse\">{{cite web | title=No Sleep.: NYC Nightlife Flyers 1988-1999 | website=powerHouse Books | url=https://www.powerhousebooks.com/books/no-sleep-nyc-nightlife-flyers-1988-1999/ | access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref name=\"bee\">{{cite news |last1=Caramanica |first1=Jon |title=Inside the Secret NYC Club Culture |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/644994773/ |accessdate=20 April 2020 |work=Sacramento Bee |date=December 25, 2016}}</ref> He explains that it's \"a book that chronicles basically the history of New York City nightclubs from \u201888 to \u201899 as told through club flyer art.\"<ref name=\"Vibe 2016\" />\n\n==Early life==\nBartos grew up in the Upper East Side of New York City.<ref name=\"Owerko\">{{cite book | last=Owerko | first=L. | last2=Lee | first2=S. | title=The Boombox Project: The Machines, the Music, and the Urban Underground | publisher=ABRAMS | year=2014 | isbn=978-1-61312-810-7 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZtWdBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT39 | access-date=2020-04-20 | page=39}}</ref> He was obsessed with [[boombox]]es as a child and had an older sister who was into early disco music in the seventies, bringing records home to listen to.<ref name=\"NPR.org 2020\">{{cite web | title=On Their Debut Album, Stretch And Bobbito Are Taking 'No Requests' | website=NPR.org | date=2020-01-17 | url=https://www.npr.org/2020/01/17/797299976/on-their-debut-album-stretch-and-bobbito-are-taking-no-requests | access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> He started DJing in downtown New York City, making his own concert flyers out of cardboard, scissors, and glue.<ref name=\"Owerko\" /><ref name=\"powerHouse\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://stretchandbobbito.com/ Stretch and Bobbito film website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bartos, Adrian}}\n[[Category:American hip hop DJs]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American hip hop record producers]]\n[[Category:East Coast hip hop musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the DJ|the band|Stretch Arm Strong|the toy|Stretch Armstrong}}\n{{short description|New York-based DJ and music producer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = \n| image           = Stretch Armstrong and Bobbito Garcia in 2011.jpg\n| caption         = Armstrong (left) in 2011\n| birth_name      = Adrian Bartos\n| birth_date      = \n| birth_place     = \n| other_names     = \n| occupation      = \n| years_active    = \n| known_for       = ''[[The Stretch Armstrong and Bobbito Show]]''\n}}\n\n'''Adrian Bartos''' known professionally as '''DJ Stretch Armstrong''' is a New York-based [[Disc jockey|DJ]] and music producer, known as a former co-host of [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] radio show ''[[The Stretch Armstrong and Bobbito Show]]'', alongside [[Bobbito Garcia]]. \n\nFrom 1990\u201398, Bartos co-hosted ''[[The Stretch Armstrong and Bobbito Show]]'' on [[Columbia University]]'s [[WKCR]]. It featured exclusive demo tapes and in-studio freestyles from many then-unsigned hip hop artists such as [[Nas]],  [[Big Pun]], [[Jay-Z]], [[Busta Rhymes]], [[Fat Joe]], [[Cam'ron]], [[DMX (rapper)|DMX]], [[Wu-Tang Clan]], [[Fugees]], [[Talib Kweli]], [[Big L]] and [[The Notorious B.I.G.]] who later found great success on major record labels.<ref>Bobbito Garcia in ''[[ego trip (magazine)|ego trip]]'s Book of Rap Lists''. Sacha Jenkins, Elliott Wilson, Chairman Mao, Gabriel Alvarez & Brent Rollins. New York: St. Martin's Press, 1999 (pp. 110\u201311); {{ISBN|978-0-312-24298-5}}</ref> In 2020 the pair produced an album called ''No Requests'' with a group of musicians called the M19, named for a bus in Manhattan connecting the Upper East Side to the Upper West Side.<ref name=\"Cornish Lonsdorf 2020\">{{cite web | last=Cornish | first=Audie | last2=Lonsdorf | first2=Kat | title=On Their Debut Album, Stretch And Bobbito Are Taking 'No Requests' | website=WFAE | date=2020-01-17 | url=https://www.wfae.org/post/their-debut-album-stretch-and-bobbito-are-taking-no-requests | access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> The album is a reimagining of hip-hop's foundational songs with some updated lyrics and no sampling. <ref name=\"CBC 2020\">{{cite web | title=Hip-hop radio DJs Stretch and Bobbito on their debut album No Requests - CBC Radio | website=CBC | date=2020-01-27 | url=https://www.cbc.ca/radio/q/tuesday-jan-28-2020-stretch-and-bobbito-whoop-szo-and-more-1.5442122/hip-hop-radio-djs-stretch-and-bobbito-on-their-debut-album-no-requests-1.5442156 | access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nBartos co-hosted [[NPR|NPR's]] podcast ''What's Good with Stretch and Bobbito'' which began in 2017.<ref name=\"NPR\">{{cite web | title=Adrian \"Stretch\" Bartos | website=NPR.org | date=2017-07-18 | url=https://www.npr.org/people/537945398/adrian-stretch-bartos | access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref name=\"Nieman Lab 2017\">{{cite web | title=NPR is bringing back \u201990s hip-hop DJs Stretch and Bobbito | website=Nieman Lab | date=2017-04-19 | url=https://www.niemanlab.org/2017/04/npr-is-bringing-back-90s-hip-hop-djs-stretch-and-bobbito/ | access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref name=\"WAMU 2017\">{{cite web | title=Stretch & Bobbito On Race, Hip-Hop, And Belonging | website=WAMU | date=2017-07-26 | url=https://wamu.org/story/17/07/26/stretch-bobbito-on-race-hip-hop-and-belonging/ | access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> The show which was about art, politics, and sports, as well as music, interviewed people such as [[Dave Chapelle]] and [[Stevie Wonder]].<ref name=\"Blistein Blistein 2017\">{{cite web | last=Blistein | first=Jon | last2=Blistein | first2=Jon | title=Pioneering Rap DJs Stretch and Bobbito Detail New NPR Show | website=Rolling Stone | date=2017-04-19 | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/pioneering-rap-djs-stretch-and-bobbito-detail-new-npr-show-128762/ | access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nHis musical career, along with Garcia, was made into a movie [[Stretch and Bobbito: Radio That Changed Lives]], which was picked up by Netflix in 2015 on the 25th anniversary of the pair's radio show.<ref name=\"Vibe 2016\">{{cite web | title=DJ Stretch Armstrong Discusses 'Stretch & Bobbito' Documentary | website=Vibe | date=2016-11-03 | url=https://www.vibe.com/2016/11/dj-stretch-armstrong-no-sleep-book-documentary | access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref name=\" officialdon 2015\">{{cite web | author= officialdon | title=Stretch & Bobbito Film Highlights NYC Legends Who Put Lyricists On The Map | website=The Source | date=2015-10-09 | url=https://thesource.com/2015/10/09/stretch-bobbito-film-highlights-nyc-legends-who-put-lyricists-on-the-map/ | access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref name=\"Vibe 2020\">{{cite web | title=Stretch And Bobbito On Debut Album \"No Requests,\" Radio Legacy | website=Vibe | date=2020-02-05 | url=https://www.vibe.com/2020/02/stretch-and-bobbito-no-requests-feature | access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> [[The Source|The Source Magazine]] called their show \"The Best Hip Hop Radio Show of All Time\" in 1998.<ref name=\"Hip-Hop Radio Archive 1992\">{{cite web | title=The Stretch Armstrong and Bobbito Show | website=Hip-Hop Radio Archive | date=1992-11-19 | url=https://hiphopradioarchive.org/browse/shows/The+Stretch+Armstrong+and+Bobbito+Show/ | access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nBartos' first book, with archivist Evan Auerbach, ''No Sleep: NYC Nightlife Flyers 1988-1999 '', was released through Powerhouse Books.<ref name=\"powerHouse\">{{cite web | title=No Sleep.: NYC Nightlife Flyers 1988-1999 | website=powerHouse Books | url=https://www.powerhousebooks.com/books/no-sleep-nyc-nightlife-flyers-1988-1999/ | access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref name=\"bee\">{{cite news |last1=Caramanica |first1=Jon |title=Inside the Secret NYC Club Culture |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/644994773/ |accessdate=20 April 2020 |work=Sacramento Bee |date=December 25, 2016}}</ref> He explains that it's \"a book that chronicles basically the history of New York City nightclubs from \u201888 to \u201899 as told through club flyer art.\"<ref name=\"Vibe 2016\" />\n\n==Early life==\nBartos grew up in the Upper East Side of New York City.<ref name=\"Owerko\">{{cite book | last=Owerko | first=L. | last2=Lee | first2=S. | title=The Boombox Project: The Machines, the Music, and the Urban Underground | publisher=ABRAMS | year=2014 | isbn=978-1-61312-810-7 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZtWdBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT39 | access-date=2020-04-20 | page=39}}</ref> He was obsessed with [[boombox]]es as a child and had an older sister who was into early disco music in the seventies, bringing records home to listen to.<ref name=\"NPR.org 2020\">{{cite web | title=On Their Debut Album, Stretch And Bobbito Are Taking 'No Requests' | website=NPR.org | date=2020-01-17 | url=https://www.npr.org/2020/01/17/797299976/on-their-debut-album-stretch-and-bobbito-are-taking-no-requests | access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> He started DJing in downtown New York City, making his own concert flyers out of cardboard, scissors, and glue.<ref name=\"Owerko\" /><ref name=\"powerHouse\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://stretchandbobbito.com/ Stretch and Bobbito film website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bartos, Adrian}}\n[[Category:American hip hop DJs]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American hip hop record producers]]\n[[Category:East Coast hip hop musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Mandarax", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DJ_Stretch_Armstrong"}
{"title_page": "Spies in Disguise", "text_new": "{{short description|2019 film directed by Nick Bruno & Troy Quane}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Spies in Disguise\n| image          = Spies_in_Disguise_Final_Poster.jpeg\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = {{Plainlist|\n* Troy Quane\n* Nick Bruno\n}}\n| producer       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Peter Chernin]]\n* [[Jenno Topping]]\n* Michael J. Travers<ref name=\"DENALI PUBLISHING\">{{cite press release|url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/pressreleases/353913/DENALI_PUBLISHING_ANNOUNCES_SPIES_IN_DISGUISE_AGENTS_ON_THE_RUN.php|title=Denali Publishing Announces Spies in Disguise: Agents on the Run|date=November 13, 2019|accessdate=November 13, 2019|via=''[[Gamasutra]]''}}</ref>\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{plainlist|\n* [[Brad Copeland]]\n* Lloyd Taylor<ref name=\"DENALI PUBLISHING\"/>\n}}\n| story          = Cindy Davis<ref name=\"DENALI PUBLISHING\"/>\n| based on       = {{based on|''Pigeon: Impossible''|Lucas Martell}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Will Smith]]\n* [[Tom Holland (actor)|Tom Holland]]\n* [[Rashida Jones]]\n* [[Ben Mendelsohn]]\n* [[Reba McEntire]]\n* [[Rachel Brosnahan]]\n* [[Karen Gillan]]\n* [[DJ Khaled]]\n* [[Masi Oka]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Theodore Shapiro]]<ref name=\"ShapiroSpiesInDisguise\">{{cite news |title=Theodore Shapiro to Score Blue Sky Studios\u2019 \u2018Spies in Disguise\u2019 & Karyn Kusama\u2019s \u2018Destroyer\u2019 |url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2018/06/12/theodore-shapiro-to-score-blue-sky-studios-spies-in-disguise-karyn-kusamas-destroyer/ |accessdate=October 28, 2018 |work=Film Music Reporter |date=June 12, 2018}}</ref>\n| editing        = {{plainlist|\n* Randy Trager\n* Christopher Campbell<ref name=\"filmreviews\">{{cite web |title=Spies in Disguise reviews |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/spies-disguise-review-1262755 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=December 16, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Blue Sky Studios]]<ref name=\"varietyinsight\">{{cite web |title=Film releases |url=https://www.varietyinsight.com/print_featurefilm_releases.php?sort=&from_date= |website=[[Variety Insight]] |accessdate=August 28, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[20th Century Fox Animation]]<ref name=\"varietyinsight\" />\n* [[Chernin Entertainment]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vary |first1=Adam B. |title=Disney and Chernin Entertainment Parting Ways |url=https://variety.com/2020/biz/news/disney-chernin-entertainment-deal-ending-1203470944/ |accessdate=January 21, 2020 |work=Variety |date=January 17, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n}}\n| distributor    = [[20th Century Fox]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2019|12|4|[[El Capitan Theatre]]|2019|12|25|United States}}\n| runtime        = 102 minutes<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/spies-disguise-2019 |title=Spies in Disguise |publisher=British Board of Film Classification |accessdate=2020-01-11}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $100 million<ref name=\"IndieWireBO\"/>\n| gross          = $171.6 million<ref name=BOM>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl1333691905/?ref_=bo_hm_rs|title=Spies in Disguise (2019)|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Spies in Disguise''''' is a 2019 American [[Computer animation|computer-animated]] [[Spy film|spy]] [[comedy film]] produced by [[Blue Sky Studios]] and distributed by [[20th Century Fox]]. Loosely based on the 2009 animated short ''Pigeon: Impossible'' by Lucas Martell, the film is directed by Troy Quane and Nick Bruno (in their feature directorial debuts) from a screenplay by [[Brad Copeland]] and Lloyd Taylor, and a story by Cindy Davis. It stars the voices of [[Will Smith]] and [[Tom Holland (actor)|Tom Holland]], alongside [[Rashida Jones]], [[Ben Mendelsohn]], [[Reba McEntire]], [[Rachel Brosnahan]], [[Karen Gillan]], [[DJ Khaled]], and [[Masi Oka]] in supporting roles. The plot follows a secret agent (Smith) who is accidentally transformed into a pigeon by an intelligent young scientist (Holland); the two must then work together to stop a revenge-seeking cybernetic terrorist, and return the agent to his human form.\n\nThe film premiered at the [[El Capitan Theatre]] on December 4, 2019, and was theatrically released in the United States on December 25, 2019. It has grossed $171 million worldwide and it received generally positive reviews from critics, with praise for the animation, music, humor, and vocal performances (particularly Smith and Holland).\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Please see WP:FILMPLOT before editing. Per key guideline, the plot summary should be within the desired length of 400-700 words. -->\nLance Sterling, a cocky secret agent of H.T.U.V. (Honor, Trust, Unity and Valor), is sent to recover an attack [[Drone strike|drone]] from Japanese arms dealer Katsu Kimura in Japan. As soon as the buyer, cybernetically enhanced terrorist Killian, arrives, Sterling breaks in against the orders of H.T.U.V. director Joy Jenkins, defeats Kimura and his gang, and manages to escape with the briefcase containing the drone. Sterling returns to H.T.U.V. headquarters to confront Walter Beckett, a socially inept [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]] graduate and outcast young scientist, for equipping nonlethal weapons into his suit. Walter tries to convince Sterling that there is a more peaceful way to save the world, but Sterling fires him before he can explain his latest invention: \"biodynamic concealment\".\n\nSterling discovers the briefcase to be empty and is confronted by Marcy Kappel, a security forces agent, who reveals footage of Sterling (actually Killian in a holographic disguise) leaving with the drone, labeling him as a traitor. Sterling escapes the H.T.U.V. and decides to track down Walter to help him disappear. Meanwhile, Killian breaks into the H.T.U.V. weapons facility.\n\nWhile searching Walter's home for his invention, Sterling unknowingly ingests the concoction and transforms into a pigeon. Before Walter can start making an antidote to change him back, Marcy and other H.T.U.V. agents chase the duo through the city, but they escape in Sterling's spy car. The two track down Kimura to a resort in [[Playa del Carmen]], Mexico. There, they learn of Killian's whereabouts in [[Venice, Italy]] before Marcy and the H.T.U.V. can capture them again. On their way to Venice, Walter attempts to make the antidote, but fails.\n\nArriving in Venice, Walter is confronted by the H.T.U.V., who are unaware of Sterling's condition. Revealing that she knows about Wendy, Walter's mother who was a police officer who died on duty, Marcy tries to convince him to help turn Sterling in, but Walter refuses. Suddenly, a drone distracts the H.T.U.V. and allows Walter and Sterling to escape. The two discover the drone carrying the H.T.U.V. agent database, and Walter manages to retrieve it. However, Killian shows up, takes the database, and prepares to kill Walter. With help from hundreds of pigeons in the surrounding area, they distract Killian and flee. Disguised as Sterling once more, Killian escapes the H.T.U.V., shaking Marcy's suspicions of Sterling upon her seeing him with a robot hand.\n\nWhilst underwater in a submarine, Walter reveals he planted a tracking device on Killian and locates him at the weapons facility. Walter manages to perfect the antidote and successfully turns Sterling human again. Reaching Killian's hideout, Sterling is concerned about Walter's safety and sends him away in the submarine. Once inside, Sterling confronts Killian, but is defeated and captured as Killian reveals he has mass produced hundreds of drones to target everyone at the agency using the database as revenge for killing his crew in a past mission led by Sterling. Noticing Walter returning in the submarine, Killian destroys it; unbeknownst to them, Walter survives with the help of one of his inventions, the inflatable hug.\n\nOnce Walter frees Sterling, the two escape and contact Marcy for support as the drones approach H.T.U.V. headquarters in Washington D.C. Walter attempts to hack into Killian's bionic arm but when Killian realizes this, he tries to flee via air with a drone, but Walter catches up.  Walter risks his life by trapping Killian in the inflatable hug and deactivates the villain's arm as Walter himself falls, but Sterling, who has turned himself back into a pigeon, successfully flies for the first time and carries him to safety with help from other pigeons, while Killian is found and arrested.\n\nDespite saving the world, Sterling, back in his human form, and Walter are fired for disobedience. However, they are quickly rehired by the H.T.U.V. as the agency could learn from Walter's more peaceful ways of handling villainy.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Will Smith]] as Lance Sterling, \"the world's most awesome spy,\" who is accidentally turned into a pigeon.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Evangelista|first=Chris|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/will-smith-and-tom-holland-are-spies-in-disguise/|title=Spies in Disguise Teams Will Smith and Tom Holland|date=October 10, 2017|work=Slashfilm|access-date=October 11, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Tom Holland (actor)|Tom Holland]] as Walter Beckett, a socially inept scientific genius who graduated from [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]] at age 15 and designs gadgets. He inadvertently turns Sterling into a pigeon with a new invention of his and must now help Sterling change back to his human form.\n** Jarrett Bruno as Young Walter Beckett.\n* [[Rashida Jones]] as Marcy Kappel, a security forces agent of internal affairs who is in pursuit of Lance Sterling.\n* [[Ben Mendelsohn]] as Killian, a powerful technology-based terrorist mastermind with a left bionic arm which controls an array of weaponized drones that threatens the world. Killian is Sterling's arch-enemy and his main mission objective.\n* [[Reba McEntire]] as Joy Jenkins, the director of H.T.U.V. (short for Honor, Trust, Unity and Valor) and Sterling's superior.<ref name=\"Heat Vision\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/reba-mcentire-rachel-brosnahan-join-spies-disguise-1226447|title=Reba McEntire, Rachel Brosnahan Join Will Smith in 'Spies in Disguise' (Exclusive)|work=The Hollywood Reporter|last=Galuppo|first=Mia|date=July 23, 2019|accessdate=July 23, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Rachel Brosnahan]] as Wendy Beckett, a police officer and Walter's late mother.<ref name=\"Heat Vision\"/>\n* [[Karen Gillan]] as Eyes, an H.T.U.V. specialist in spectral analysis and quantum optical thermography who is paired with Ears.<ref name=\"SIDEWCast\">{{cite news|url=https://ew.com/movies/2018/11/01/spies-in-disguise-trailer-will-smith-tom-holland/|title=Will Smith, Tom Holland are a secret agent team in 'Spies in Disguise' trailer|last1=Romano|first1=Nick|date=November 1, 2018|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=November 1, 2018|publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]}}</ref>\n* [[DJ Khaled]] as Ears, an H.T.U.V. specialist in communications and ultrasonics who is paired with Eyes.<ref name=\"SIDEWCast\" />\n* [[Masi Oka]] as Katsu Kimura, a Japanese arms dealer and an associate to Killian.\n* [[Carla Jimenez]] as Geraldine<ref name=\"THR\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/rep-sheet-roundup-caa-china-signs-matt-william-knowles-1237770|title=Rep Sheet Roundup: CAA China Signs Matt William Knowles|work=The Hollywood Reporter|last=Sun|first=Rebecca|date=September 9, 2019|accessdate=September 9, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Olly Murs]] as Junior Agent #1 (Uncredited)<ref>{{cite web|last=Chilton |first=Louis |url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/film/2019-12-16/olly-murs-joins-will-smith-and-tom-holland-in-cast-of-spies-in-disguise/ |title=Olly Murs joins Will Smith and Tom Holland in Spies In Disguise |work=Radio Times |date=2019-12-16 |accessdate=2020-01-11}}</ref>\n* Bex Marsh as Italian Tourist\n* Stefania Spampinato as Italian Woman\n* Eddie Mujica as Agency Accountant and Male Tourist\n* Emily Altman as Lead Agency Lab Tech, Scooter Girl\n* Claire Crosby as Unity\n* Randy Trager as Terrance\n* [[Mark Ronson]] as Agency Control Room Technician\n* Matthew J. Munn as Weapons Lab Soldier\n* [[Kimberly Brooks]] as Lance Sterling's Car ([[Audi RSQ e-tron]])\n* Krizia Bajos as Receptionist\n* Reggie De Leon as Weapons Lab Tech\n* Casey Roberts as Launch Control Voice\n\nSouth Korean voice actors {{Interlanguage link|So Youn|ko|\uc18c\uc5f0 (\uc131\uc6b0)}} and [[Jang Min-hyeok|Jang Min-hyuck]]  provided the voices of Soo-min and Joon respectively, the protagonists in a [[South Korean television drama]] Walter is a fan of in the film. Jang also voiced Lance Sterling in the Korean version. {{citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\n==Production==\nOn October 9, 2017, it was announced that development was underway on a film based on the animated short ''Pigeon: Impossible'' (2009), with [[Will Smith]] and [[Tom Holland (actor)|Tom Holland]] set to voice the lead characters.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/will-smith-tom-holland-1202584327/|title=Will Smith, Tom Holland to Star in Animated Movie \u2018Spies in Disguise\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Lang|first=Brent|date=October 9, 2017|work=Variety|access-date=October 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, new additions to the voice cast included [[Ben Mendelsohn]], [[Karen Gillan]], [[Rashida Jones]], [[DJ Khaled]] and [[Masi Oka]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/karen-gillan-rashida-jones-dj-khaled-masi-oka-ben-mendelsohn-spies-in-disguise-will-smith-tom-holland-fox-1202491121/|title=Ben Mendelsohn, Karen Gillan, Rashida Jones, DJ Khaled and Masi Oka Join Voice Cast Of Fox Animation \u2018Spies In Disguise\u2019|last=Wiseman|first=Andreas|date=October 29, 2018|work=Deadline Hollywood|access-date=November 22, 2019}}</ref> In July 2019, [[Reba McEntire]] and [[Rachel Brosnahan]] joined the cast,<ref name=\"Heat Vision\" /> and in September 2019, [[Carla Jimenez]] was added as well.<ref name=\"THR\" />\n\n==Music==\n===Score===\nOn June 12, 2018, it was reported that [[Theodore Shapiro]] was set to compose the film's score.<ref name=\"ShapiroSpiesInDisguise\"/> The film's score album was released by [[Hollywood Records]] and [[Fox Music]] on December 27, 2019.\n\n===EP soundtrack===\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Whale City: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n| type         = EP\n| longtype     = and [[soundtrack album]]\n| artist       = various artists\n| cover        = \n| alt          = \n| released     = {{Start date|2018|6|15}}\n| recorded     = 2018\n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Pop]], [[R&B]], [[Pop rock]]\n| length       = \n| label        = [[Virgin Records]]\n| producer     = Various Artists\n| prev_title   = \n| prev_year    = \n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n| misc         = {{Singles\n| name = Whale City: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n| type = EP\n| single1 = Discover \n| single1date = May 18, 2018\n| single2 = City of Love \n| single2date = June 6, 2018\n}}\n}}\n \n<br />{{Track listing\n| collapsed = no\n| extra_column = Artist(s)\n| title1 = Discover\n| extra1 = [[Labrinth]] and [[Dua Lipa]]\n| length1 = 3:27\n| title2 = City of Love\n| extra2 = [[Charlie Puth]]\n| length2 = 2:32\n| title3 = [[Coming Home]]\n| extra3 = [[Sheppard]]\n| length3 = 2:43\n| title4 = Raindrops\n| extra4 = [[Charlotte Lawrence]]\n| length4 = 3:18\n| title5 = Underworld\n| note5 = \n| extra5 = [[Kevin Abstract]]\n| length5 = 3:14\n| title6 = Above and Beyond\n| extra6 = Lipa\n| length6 = 5:00\n| total_length = 20:14\n| all_writing = \n| title7 = \n| length7 = \n| title8 = \n| length8 = \n| title9 = \n| length9 = \n| title10 = \n| length10 = \n}}\n\n==Release==\nThe film was originally scheduled for release on January 18, 2019 by [[20th Century Fox]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The film was delayed to April 19, 2019, and then to September 13, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/06/20th-century-fox-sets-dates-for-untitled-james-mangold-ferrari-project-kenneth-branaghs-death-on-the-nile-1202416198/|title=20th Century Fox Sets Dates For Untitled James Mangold Ferrari Project, Kenneth Branagh\u2019s \u2018Death On The Nile\u2019|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=June 22, 2018|last=Haring|first=Bruce|access-date=July 10, 2018}}</ref> On May 10, the film was delayed once more, to December 25, 2019.<ref name=\"DisneyFox Release Date\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/star-wars-movies-new-mutants-disney-fox-release-schedule-1202608933/|title=Disney-Fox Updates Release Schedule: Sets Three Untitled \u2018Star Wars\u2019 Movies, \u2018Avatar\u2019 Franchise To Kick Off In 2021 & More|date=May 7, 2019 |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |work=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=May 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n''Spies in Disguise'' is the first release by Blue Sky Studios as a unit of [[The Walt Disney Company]], following [[Acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney|their acquisition of Fox]]. This allows ticket purchases to be eligible for Disney Movie Insiders points in the United States.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=Disney_Insiders|number= 1184923813961580544|title=This Christmas they\u2019re saving the world on the fly. And guess what Insiders? #SpiesInDisguise will be eligible for Disney Movie Insiders points! http://di.sn/60081GsWY|first=Disney Movie Insiders|date=October 17, 2019|accessdate=October 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe film had its world premiere at the [[El Capitan Theatre]] in Hollywood, on December 4, 2019.<ref name=\"SIDPremiereVariety\">{{cite news |last1=Jackson |first1=Angelique |title=Tom Holland on Spider-Man, James Bond and Meeting \u2018Spies in Disguise\u2019 Co-Star Will Smith in an Escape Room |url=https://variety.com/2019/scene/news/tom-holland-spider-man-james-bond-will-smith-1203425653/ |accessdate=December 5, 2019 |work=Variety |date=December 5, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\nThe first trailer and teaser poster were released on November 1, 2018.<ref name=\"first_trailer\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LSSGHvzMY60|title=Spies in Disguise, Official Trailer|work=20th Century FOX|date=November 1, 2018}}</ref> The second trailer was released on July 1, 2019 and the final trailer was released on September 27, 2019, though a \"super secret\" trailer was released on November 18.\n\n===Home media===\n''Spies in Disguise'' was released in [[Blu-ray]], [[Ultra HD Blu-ray]], and [[DVD]] by [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]] on March 10, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Prange |first1=Stephanie |title=Animated \u2018Spies in Disguise\u2019 to Be Unveiled on Digital and Disc \u2014 Including 4K \u2014 March 10|url=https://www.mediaplaynews.com/animated-spies-in-disguise-to-be-unveiled-on-digital-and-disc-including-4k-march-10/ |accessdate=February 13, 2020 |work=[[Media Play News]]|publisher=JCH Media|date=February 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Milligan |first1=Mercedes |title=\u2018Spies in Disguise\u2019 Tackles Digital & Disc Mission March 10 |url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/home-entertainment/spies-in-disguise-tackles-digital-disc-mission-march-10/ |accessdate=February 13, 2020 |work=[[Animation Magazine]] |date=February 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n{{As of|2020|3|16|df=US}}, ''Spies in Disguise'' has grossed $66.8 million in the United States and Canada, and $104.9 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $171.6 million.<ref name=\"BOM\" />\n\nIn the United States and Canada, the film was released on Wednesday, December 25, alongside ''[[Little Women (2019 film)|Little Women]]'' and the wide expansion of ''[[Uncut Gems]]'', and was projected to gross $19\u201323 million from 3,502 theatres over its five-day opening weekend.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://deadline.com/2019/12/star-wars-rise-of-skywalker-christmas-box-office-little-women-spies-in-disguise-1202816735/|title=\u2018Rise Of Skywalker\u2019 Eyes $35M Merry Christmas With 2nd Best Ever For Holiday; \u2018Little Women\u2019 $7M; \u2018Spies In Disguise\u2019 $5M |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=December 25, 2019 |accessdate=December 26, 2019}}</ref> The film made $4.8 million on Christmas Day and $4.1 million on its second day.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/rise-skywalker-unwraps-huge-35m-christmas-little-women-opens-1264949|title=Box Office: 'Star Wars: Rise of Skywalker' Unwraps Huge $32M on Christmas Day|last=McClintock|first=Pamela|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=December 25, 2019 |accessdate=December 26, 2019}}</ref> It went on to make $13.2 million during its opening weekend, for a total of $22.1 million over the five-day Christmas frame, finishing fifth.<ref name=opening>{{cite web |url= https://deadline.com/2019/12/star-wars-rise-of-skywalker-little-women-uncut-gems-spies-in-disguise-post-christmas-box-office-1202817539/ |title=\u2018Star Wars: Rise Of Skywalker\u2019 Counts $362M Through 10 Days, -2% Behind \u2018Last Jedi\u2019; \u2018Little Women\u2019 All Grown Up With $29M 5-Day |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=December 29, 2019 |accessdate=December 29, 2019}}</ref><ref name=IndieWireBO>{{cite web |url= https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/little-women-box-office-star-wars-the-rise-of-skywalker-1202199513/ |title=\u2018Little Women\u2019 Is the Top Box Office Newcomer; \u2018Skywalker\u2019 May Fall $100 Million Short of \u2018Jedi\u2019 |last= Brueggemann |first=Tom|work=[[IndieWire]] |date=December 29, 2019 |accessdate=December 31, 2019}}</ref> In its second weekend the film made $10.1 million, finishing sixth.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://deadline.com/2020/01/star-wars-rise-of-skywalker-the-grudge-uncut-gems-weekend-box-office-2020-1202820066/ |title= \u2018Star Wars: Rise Of Skywalker\u2019 Dips To $34M+ Third Weekend; \u2018Grudge\u2019 Doesn\u2019t Scream With $11M+ & \u2018F\u2019 CinemaScore |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=January 5, 2020|accessdate=January 5, 2020}}</ref> In its third weekend, it grossed $5.1 million, dropping 50.9% from the previous weekend and finishing at the 10th position.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/box-office-1917-star-wars-rise-of-skywalker-like-a-boss-1202826743/ |title= \u20191917\u2019 Strong With $36M+, But \u2018Like A Boss\u2019 & \u2018Just Mercy\u2019 Fighting Over 4th With $10M; Why Kristen Stewart\u2019s \u2018Underwater\u2019 Went Kerplunk With $7M |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=January 12, 2020|accessdate=January 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical response ===\nOn [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 75% based on 117 reviews and an [[Weighted arithmetic mean|average rating]] of 6.48/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"A cheerfully undemanding animated adventure that's elevated by its voice cast, ''Spies in Disguise'' is funny, fast-paced, and family-friendly enough to satisfy.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/spies_in_disguise|title=Spies in Disguise (2019)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=January 3, 2020}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] gave the film a weighted average score of 54 out of 100, based on 22 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/spies-in-disguise|title=Spies in Disguise Reviews|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=December 30, 2019}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\u2013\" on an A+ to F scale, while those at [[PostTrak]] gave it an average 3.5 out of 5 stars.<ref name=opening/>\n\n[[Peter Bradshaw]] of [[United Kingdom|British]] newspaper ''[[The Guardian]]'' gave the film three out of five stars, calling it an \"entertaining family adventure,\" and praising the vocal work of Smith and Holland.<ref name=\"theguardian1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/dec/16/spies-in-disguise-review-will-smith-tom-holland-family-animation|title = Movie Review: Spies in Disguise \u2013 Will Smith brings pecks appeal to animated caper |accessdate = December 16, 2019|work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nKwak Yeon-soo, a reporter at South Korean English language newspaper ''[[The Korea Times]]'', wrote that the film failed to convey its message because of its \"lackluster narrative\". Kwak also pointed out that the film tried to attract audiences there by putting references to the [[Culture of South Korea#Popular culture|South Korean popular culture]], and that it ended up exemplifying Walter Beckett's \"weird\" personality.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kwak |first1=Yeon-soo |title='Spies in Disguise' tries too hard to attract Korean moviegoers |url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/art/2020/01/689_281530.html |accessdate=3 February 2020 |work=[[The Korea Times]] |publisher=[[Hankook Ilbo]] |date=7 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width: 99%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Date of ceremony\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:30%;\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:33%;\"| Recipient(s) and nominee(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Motion Picture Sound Editors|Golden Reel Awards]]\n| scope=\"row\"| January 19, 2020\n| Outstanding Achievement in Sound Editing \u2013 Feature Animation\n| Leff Lefferts, Jeremy Bowker, [[Randy Thom]], Bjorn Ole Schroeder, Samson Neslund, David Farmer, [[Michael Silvers]], Larry Oatfield, Chris Manning, Shelley Roden, John Roesch\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/motion-pictures-sound-editors-67th-annual-golden-reel-nominations-1202809902/|