ese version===\nCD {{small|VJCP-12077}}\n#\"Bitter Sweet Symphony\" (original) \u2013 6:00\n#\"Lord I Guess I'll Never Know\" \u2013 4:51\n#\"Country Song\" \u2013 7:50\n#\"Bitter Sweet Symphony\" (radio edit) \u2013 4:35\n\n===Dutch version===\nCD {{small|8943752}}\n#\"Bitter Sweet Symphony\" (original) \u2013 6:00\n#\"Lord I Guess I'll Never Know\" \u2013 4:51\n#\"Country Song\" \u2013 7:50\n#\"Bitter Sweet Symphony\" (radio edit) \u2013 4:35\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Chart (1997\u20131998)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{single chart|Australia|11|artist=The Verve|song=Bitter Sweet Symphony|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 April 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|15|artist=The Verve|song=Bitter Sweet Symphony|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 April 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders|21|artist=The Verve|song=Bitter Sweet Symphony|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 April 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Wallonia|18|artist=The Verve|song=Bitter Sweet Symphony|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 April 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Canadatopsingles|5|chartid=3451|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 April 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Canadarock|1|chartid=3436|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 April 2018}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Europe ([[European Hot 100 Singles|Eurochart Hot 100]])<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/UK/Music-and-Media/90s/1997/MM-1997-07-05.pdf|title=Eurochart Hot 100 Singles|magazine=[[Music & Media]]|volume=14|issue=27|page=13|date=5 July 1997|access-date=5 February 2020}}</ref>\n|10\n|-\n{{single chart|Finland|6|artist=The Verve|song=Bitter Sweet Symphony|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 April 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|France|16|artist=The Verve|song=Bitter Sweet Symphony|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 April 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Germany2|37|artist=The Verve|song=Bitter Sweet Symphony|songid=3516|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 April 2018}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Iceland ([[\u00cdslenski listinn|\u00cdslenski Listinn Topp 40]])<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://timarit.is/files/12658655.pdf#navpanes=1&view=FitH|title=\u00cdslenski Listinn Topp 40 (NR. 233 Vikuna 7.8. '97 \u2013 14.8. '97)|publisher=Dagbla\u00f0i\u00f0 V\u00edsir|accessdate=12 July 2018|language=is}}</ref>\n|2\t\t\n|-\n{{single chart|Ireland2|3|song=Bitter Sweet Symphony|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 April 2018}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Italy (''[[Musica e dischi]]'')<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Music-and-Media/90s/1997/MM-1997-09-27.pdf|title=Top National Sellers|magazine=[[Music & Media]]|volume=14|issue=39|page=15|date=27 September 1997|access-date=27 November 2019}}</ref>\n|7\n|-\n{{single chart|Dutch40|11|year=1997|week=33|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 April 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Dutch100|14|artist=The Verve|song=Bitter Sweet Symphony|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 April 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|New Zealand|15|artist=The Verve|song=Bitter Sweet Symphony|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 April 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Norway|9|artist=The Verve|song=Bitter Sweet Symphony|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 April 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Scotland|1|date=19970628|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 April 2018}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Spain ([[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a|AFYVE]])<ref>{{cite book|last=Salaverri|first=Fernando|title=S\u00f3lo \u00e9xitos: a\u00f1o a a\u00f1o, 1959\u20132002|edition=1st|date=September 2005|publisher=Fundaci\u00f3n Autor-SGAE|location=Spain|isbn=84-8048-639-2}}</ref>\n|2\n|-\n{{single chart|Sweden|10|artist=The Verve|song=Bitter Sweet Symphony|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 April 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Switzerland|15|artist=The Verve|song=Bitter Sweet Symphony|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 April 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UK|2|date=19970628|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 April 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardhot100|12|artist=The Verve|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 April 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardadultalternativesongs|3|artist=The Verve|rowheader=true|accessdate=27 November 2019}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardadultpopsongs|8|artist=The Verve|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 April 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardalternativesongs|4|artist=The Verve|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 April 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardmainstreamrock|22|artist=The Verve|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 April 2018}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardpopsongs|23|artist=The Verve|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 April 2018}}\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Chart (2019)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardrocksongs|13|artist=The Verve|rowheader=true|accessdate=4 June 2019}}\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Chart (1997)\n!Position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Australia (ARIA)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-end-of-year-charts-top-100-singles-1997.htm|title=ARIA Charts - End Of Year Charts - Top 100 Singles 1997|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association|ARIA]]|accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref>\n|62\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Belgium (Ultratop 50 Flanders)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultratop.be/nl/annual.asp?year=1997|title=Jaaroverzichten 1997|publisher=[[Ultratop]]|language=Dutch|accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>\n|88\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Belgium (Ultratop 50 Wallonia)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultratop.be/fr/annual.asp?year=1997|title=Rapports annuels 1997|publisher=[[Ultratop]]|language=French|accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>\n|60\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Europe (Eurochart Hot 100)<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/UK/Music-and-Media/90s/1997/MM-1997-12-27.pdf|title=Year in Focus \u2013 Eurochart Hot 100 Singles 1997|magazine=[[Music & Media]]|volume=14|issue=52|page=7|date=27 December 1997|access-date=5 February 2020}}</ref>\n|50\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|France (SNEP)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.disqueenfrance.com/fr/page-259376.xml?year=1997|title=Classement Singles \u2013 ann\u00e9e 1997|language=French|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307032203/http://www.disqueenfrance.com/fr/page-259376.xml?year=1997|archivedate=7 March 2012|accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>\n|98\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Iceland (\u00cdslenski Listinn Topp 40)<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=https://timarit.is/page/2963913?iabr=on#page/n15/mode/2up/|title=\u00c1rslistinn 1997 \u2013 \u00cdslenski Listinn \u2013 100 Vins\u00e6lustu L\u00f6gin|newspaper=[[DV (newspaper)|Dagbla\u00f0i\u00f0 V\u00edsir]]|language=is|page=25|date=2 January 1998|access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n|8\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Netherlands (Dutch Top 40)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.top40.nl/bijzondere-lijsten/top-100-jaaroverzichten/1997|title=Top 100-Jaaroverzicht van 1997|publisher=Dutch Top 40|accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref>\n|92\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Netherlands (Single Top 100)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dutchcharts.nl/jaaroverzichten.asp?year=1997&cat=s|title=Jaaroverzichten \u2013 Single 1997|publisher=[[MegaCharts]]|language=Dutch|accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>\n|56\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Sweden (Sverigetopplistan)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitlistan.se/netdata/ghl002.mbr/lista?liid=43&dfom=19970001&newi=0&height=420&platform=Win32&browser=MSIE&navi=no&subframe=Mainframe|title=\u00c5rslista Singlar \u2013 \u00c5r 1997|publisher=[[Sverigetopplistan|Hitlistan]]|language=Swedish|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208230504/http://www.hitlistan.se/netdata/ghl002.mbr/lista?liid=43&dfom=19970001&newi=0&height=420&platform=Win32&browser=MSIE&navi=no&subframe=Mainframe|archivedate=8 February 2015|accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>\n|60\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Switzerland (Schweizer Hitparade)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.swisscharts.com/charts/jahreshitparade/1997|title=Schweizer Jahreshitparade 1997|language=German|accessdate=22 June 2019}}</ref>\n|44\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|UK Singles (Official Charts Company)<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Top 100 Singles 1997|magazine=[[Music Week]]|page=27|date=17 January 1998}}</ref>\n|43\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Chart (1998)\n!Position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Canada Top Singles (''RPM'')<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://rpmimages.3345.ca/pdfs/Volume+68-No.+12-December+14%2C+1998.pdf|title=RPM's Top 100 Hit Tracks of '98|magazine=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|volume=63|issue=12|page=20|date=14 December 1998|accessdate=23 March 2019}}</ref>\n|34\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Canada Rock/Alternative (''RPM'')<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.6985&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.6985.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.6985|title=RPM's Top 50 Alternative Tracks of '98|magazine=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|publisher=[[Library and Archives Canada]]|accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref>\n|27\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://longboredsurfer.com/charts.php?year=1998|title=Billboard Top 100 - 1998|accessdate=28 August 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090309202636/http://longboredsurfer.com/charts.php?year=1998|archivedate=9 March 2009}}</ref>\n|79\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Australia|award=Gold|relyear=1997|certyear=1997|accessdate=9 January 2015|type=single}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=France|award=Silver|relyear=1997|certyear=1998|artist=The Verve|title=Bitter Sweet Symphony|accessdate=9 January 2015|type=single}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Germany|award=Gold|relyear=1997|certyear=2018|artist=The Verve|title=Bitter Sweet Symphony|accessdate=15 May 2018|type=single}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Italy|award=Platinum|relyear=1997|certyear=2017|artist=The Verve|title=Bitter Sweet Symphony|accessdate=6 November 2017|type=single}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|award=Platinum|number=2|relyear=1997|certyear=2018|salesamount=1,276,209|salesref=<ref name=\"Dispute over\"/>|artist=The Verve|title=Bitter Sweet Symphony|accessdate=2 January 2019|type=single}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|award=Gold|relyear=1998|certyear=2005|artist=The Verve|title=Bitter Sweet Symphony|accessdate=2 January 2019|type=single}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|streaming=true}}\n\n{{Portal bar|London|Rock music}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|the-verve|bitter-sweet-symphony}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{The Verve}}\n\n[[Category:The Verve songs]]\n[[Category:1997 songs]]\n[[Category:Sampling controversies]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Jagger/Richards]]\n[[Category:Virgin Records singles]]\n[[Category:1997 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Richard Ashcroft]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Chris Potter (record producer)]]\n[[Category:Hut Records singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Baroque pop songs]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Walter Stern]]\n[[Category:Songs involved in royalties controversies]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the album by Jade Valerie|Bittersweet Symphony (album)}}\n{{short description|1997 single by The Verve}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Bitter Sweet Symphony\n| cover      = The Verve - Bitter Sweet Symphony CD1.jpg\n| alt        = A man looking through a lens\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Verve]]\n| album      = [[Urban Hymns]]\n| B-side     = {{hlist|\"Lord I Guess I'll Never Know\"|\"Country Song\"}}\n| released   = {{Start date|1997|6|16|df=yes}}\n| format     = {{hlist|[[CD single|CD]]|[[Twelve-inch single|12-inch]]}}\n| recorded   = January\u2013March 1997\n| studio     = [[Olympic Studios]], London<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thevervelive.com/2005/05/bitter-sweet-symphony-controversy-and.html|title=Bitter Sweet Symphony|last=|first=|date=|website=The Verve Live|access-date=2018-12-23}}</ref>\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Britpop]]|[[alternative rock]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/7640665/1997-alternative-rock-songs-turning-20-2017|title=20 Alternative Rock Hits Turning 20 in 2017|last=Richin|first=Leslie|date=12 January 2017|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=29 November 2018}}</ref>}}\n| length     = {{ubl|5:58 {{small|(album version)}}|4:33 {{small|(radio edit and video version)}}}}\n| label      = [[Hut Recordings|Hut]]\n| writer     = [[Richard Ashcroft]]<ref name=\"Dispute over\"/>\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Youth (musician)|Martin \"Youth\" Glover]]|The Verve}}\n| prev_title = [[History (The Verve song)|History]]\n| prev_year  = 1995\n| next_title = [[The Drugs Don't Work]]\n| next_year  = 1997\n| misc       = \n{{External music video|{{YouTube|1lyu1KKwC74|\"Bitter Sweet Symphony\"}}}}\n{{Audio sample\n | type        = single\n | file        = The Verve - Bitter Sweet Symphony.ogg\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Bitter Sweet Symphony'''\" is a song by English [[alternative rock]] band [[the Verve]]. It is the lead track on their third studio album, ''[[Urban Hymns]]'' (1997). It is based on a sample it uses from the [[Andrew Loog Oldham]] orchestral cover of [[the Rolling Stones]]' song \"[[The Last Time (The Rolling Stones song)|The Last Time]]\", and involved some legal controversy surrounding a [[plagiarism]] charge. As a result, [[Mick Jagger]] and [[Keith Richards]] were added to the songwriting credits, and all royalties from the song went to former Rolling Stones manager [[Allen Klein]]. In April 2019, Jagger and Richards signed over all their publishing for the song to The Verve.<ref name=\"Dispute over\"/> The song was released in June 1997 by [[Hut Recordings]] as the first [[Single (music)|single]] from the album, reaching number two on the [[UK Singles Chart]] and remaining in the chart for three months.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/330634.stm \"The Verve's bitter sweet career\"]. BBC News. Retrieved 8 March 2015</ref>\n\nAcclaimed in music publications, it was named ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' and [[NME Single of the Year|''NME'' Single of the Year]] for 1997, and is considered one of the defining songs of the [[Britpop]] era. The accompanying music video features lead vocalist [[Richard Ashcroft]] walking down a busy [[London]] pavement \u2013 in Hoxton Street, [[Hoxton]] \u2013 oblivious to what is going on around and refusing to change his stride or direction throughout.<ref name=\"RollingStone\">[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/verve-single-tops-charts-but-success-is-bittersweet-19971011 Verve Single Tops Charts But Success Is Bittersweet] ''Rolling Stone''. Retrieved February 12, 2012</ref><ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandjazzmusic/3649299/Still-crazy.html|title=Still crazy|last=McLean|first=Craig|date=14 January 2006|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=11 February 2012}}</ref> At the [[1998 Brit Awards]], \"Bitter Sweet Symphony\" was nominated for [[1998 BRIT Awards#The awards|Best British Single]]. The song was released in the US as a single in March 1998 by [[Virgin Records America]], reaching No. 12 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]],<ref>[http://bestsongsever.com/the-verve/bitter-sweet-symphony Billboard Hot 100 (line 17)]. TheBestSongsEver.com</ref> and the music video was nominated for [[MTV Video Music Award for Video of the Year|Video of the Year]], [[Best Group Video]], and [[Best Alternative Video]] at the [[1998 MTV Video Music Awards]].<ref>[http://www.brits.co.uk/artist/the-verve The Brit Awards: The Verve] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120202085636/http://www.brits.co.uk/artist/the-verve |date=2012-02-02 }} Brits.co.uk. Retrieved 11 February 2012</ref><ref name=\"MTVAwards\">[http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/1998/mtvvmas.htm 1998 MTV Video Music Awards] Rock on the Net. Retrieved 11 February 2012</ref> In 1999, the song was nominated for the [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Song]].<ref>[http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/1999/grammys.htm 41st Grammy Awards - 1999] Rock on the Net. Retrieved 12 February 2012</ref>\n\n==Production==\nProducer [[Youth (musician)|Youth]] said: \"This was certainly the most successful track I've done. I think Richard had actually cut a version with [[John Leckie]] but, by the time I came on board, he didn't want to do the song. I persuaded him to have a go at cutting a version but at first he wasn't really into it. It was only once we'd put strings on it that he started getting excited. Then, towards the end, Richard wanted to chuck all the album away and start again. What was my reaction? Horror. Sheer horror. All I could say was, I really think you should reconsider.\"<ref>''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' January 2001</ref>\n\n==Credits dispute==\n{{See|List of songs that have been the subject of plagiarism disputes}}\nThe opening strings are [[Sampling (music)|sampled]] from the 1965 [[The Andrew Oldham Orchestra|Andrew Oldham Orchestra]] recording of [[the Rolling Stones]]' song \"[[The Last Time (The Rolling Stones song)|The Last Time]]\", arranged and written by [[David Whitaker (composer)|David Whitaker]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/jan01/articles/david.asp|title=Archived copy|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140319090334/http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/jan01/articles/david.asp|archivedate=2014-03-19|url-status=dead|accessdate=2014-04-05}} Sound On Sound. Retrieved 19 March 2014</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/feb/16/david-whitaker \u201cDavid Whitaker obituary\u201d]. The Guardian. Retrieved 19 March 2014</ref> The Rolling Stones' song was itself strongly inspired by \"This May Be the Last Time\" from the Staple Singers.<ref name=songfacts>{{cite web|url=http://www.songfacts.com/detail.php?id=478 |title=The Last Time by The Rolling Stones Songfacts |publisher=Songfacts.com |date= |accessdate=2016-12-04}}</ref> The Verve negotiated rights to use a six-note [[Sampling (music)|sample]] from the recording from the recording's copyright holder Decca Records; however, they did not obtain permission from former Rolling Stones manager [[Allen Klein]], who owned the copyrights to the band's pre-1970 songs, including \"The Last Time\".<ref name=\"Klein\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thevervelive.com/2005/05/bitter-sweet-symphony-controversy-and.html|title=Bitter Sweet Symphony: the controversy|website=www.thevervelive.com |accessdate=25 May 2019}}</ref><ref>[http://www.superswell.com/samplelaw/horror.html Superswell.com: \"Horror Stories of Sampling\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090605224422/http://www.superswell.com/samplelaw/horror.html |date=5 June 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"People\">{{cite web |url=https://people.com/music/rolling-stones-return-bitter-sweet-symphony-credit-the-verve-richard-ashcroft/ |first=Matt |last=McNulty |title=Rolling Stones Return 'Bitter Sweet Symphony' Songwriting Credit to the Verve's Richard Ashcroft |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=24 May 2019 |accessdate=25 May 2019}}</ref> Although \"Bitter Sweet Symphony\" had already been released, Klein refused to grant a licence for the sample.<ref name=\"Klein\" /> This led to a lawsuit with [[ABKCO Records]], Klein's holding company, which was settled out of court. The Verve relinquished all [[royalties]] to Klein, and the songwriting credits were changed to [[Jagger/Richards]], with Ashcroft receiving $1,000 for completely relinquishing rights.<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web|title=The Verve: Bitter Sweet Symphony|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/bittersweet-symphony-mt0001301257|work=allmusic|publisher=Rovi Corp|accessdate=14 February 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Klein\" />\n\nVerve bassist [[Simon Jones (musician)|Simon Jones]] said, \"We were told it was going to be a 50/50 split, and then they saw how well the record was doing. They rung up and said we want 100 percent or take it out of the shops, you don't have much choice.\"<ref name=\"powell\">Powell, Betsy. [http://www.musicsaves.org/verve/interviews/30.shtml MusicSaves.org: \"Bitter, Sweet Success\"]</ref> Ashcroft sarcastically said, \"This is the best song Jagger and Richards have written in 20 years\",<ref>[https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/6596227/bitter_sweet_symphony \u201cBitter Sweet Symphony\u201d]. Rolling Stone. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123044440/http://rollingstone.com/news/story/6596227/bitter_sweet_symphony |date=23 January 2009}}</ref> noting it was their biggest UK hit since \"[[Brown Sugar (song)|Brown Sugar]]\".<ref name=\"powell\" />\n\nIn a 1999 interview with [[Q (magazine)|''Q'']], asked whether he believed the result was fair, Rolling Stones guitarist [[Keith Richards]] said: \"I'm out of whack here, this is serious lawyer shit. If the Verve can write a better song, they can keep the money.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Lawyers sue, men plunder - Music - Entertainment - smh.com.au|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/entertainment/music/lawyers-sue-men-plunder/2009/11/01/1257010103921.html?page=fullpage|website=www.smh.com.au|accessdate=6 May 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Snyder|first1=Jeffrey|title=Song authorship controversies, from George Harrison to Oasis|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-copyright-controversy-rolling-stones-verve-oasis-george-harrison-20150126-story.html|website=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=6 May 2017|language=en|date=27 January 2015}}</ref> In 1999, [[Andrew Oldham]] sued for royalties after failing to receive the [[Royalty payment#Mechanical royalties|mechanical royalties]] he claimed he was owed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/511079/the-verve-sued-again-over-bitter-sweet-symphony/ |title=The Verve Sued Again Over 'Bitter Sweet Symphony'|author= Christopher O'Connor |date=January 11, 1999 |work=MTV }}</ref> After receiving his royalties, Oldham joked that he bought \"a pretty presentable watch strap\" compared to the watch Jagger and Richards would get with the money. In an interview with ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]'', he said: \"As for Richard Ashcroft, well, I don't know how an artist can be severely damaged by that experience. Songwriters have learned to call songs their children, and he thinks he wrote something. He didn't. I hope he's got over it. It takes a while.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-verve/40284 |title=Rolling Stones' manager derides The Verve |date=7 October 2008 |work=NME |accessdate=1 February 2015 |author=Adam Bychawski}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Ashcroft received the [[Ivor Novello Award]] for Outstanding Contribution to British Music from the [[British Academy of Songwriters, Composers, and Authors]]. Ashcroft announced that the dispute was over following negotiations with Klein's son, Jody, and the Rolling Stones' manager Joyce Smith.<ref name=\"Dispute over\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-48380600|title=The Bittersweet Symphony dispute is over|date=23 May 2019|agency=BBC News|accessdate=23 May 2019}}</ref> Ashcroft thanked Jagger and Richards \"for acknowledging me as the writer of a fucking masterpiece!\"<ref>[http://www.musicweek.com/publishing/read/five-amazing-moments-from-the-ivor-novellos-2019/076288 \u201cFive amazing moments from the Ivor Novellos 2019\u201d]. ''Music Week''. Retrieved 23 May 2019</ref> He added:\n\n{{quote|As of last month, Mick Jagger and Keith Richards signed over all their publishing for Bittersweet Symphony, which was a truly kind and magnanimous thing for them to do. I never had a personal beef with the Stones. They've always been the greatest rock and roll band in the world. It's been a fantastic development. It's life-affirming in a way.<ref name=\"Dispute over\"/>|sign=|source=}}\n\n==Music video==\n[[File:Bitter Sweet Symphony Screenshot.jpg|thumb|200px|right|A screenshot at the beginning of the music video showing vocalist Richard Ashcroft standing on a pavement in [[Hoxton]], east London]]\nThe [[music video]] (directed by [[Walter Stern (director)|Walter A. Stern]]) is a homage to the [[One shot (music video)|single continuous shot]] [[docufiction|docu-fiction]] music video for [[Massive Attack]]'s \"[[Unfinished Sympathy]]\". It focuses on Ashcroft singing while walking down a busy London [[sidewalk|pavement]], without changing his stride or direction throughout, except for one instance where he is forced to stop for a moving car and a reflection is seen of him standing stationary in the car's tinted window.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> He narrowly avoids being hit by a car as he starts his walk, repeatedly bumping into passers-by (causing one young woman to lose balance and fall), and he also jumps on top of the [[Hood (vehicle)|bonnet]] of another vehicle stopped in his path (the driver gets out of her car and proceeds to confront him, while he continues unflinchingly). At the end of the video, the rest of the Verve join Ashcroft, and the final shot sees them walking down the street into the distance. This then leads into the beginning of the video for \"[[The Drugs Don't Work]]\".<ref name=\"Music Video\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Zx3m4e45bTo|title=The Verve - Bittersweet Symphony|date=23 July 2008|accessdate=25 April 2009|publisher=[[Parlophone]]}}</ref> The music video received heavy rotation on music channels and it was nominated for a number of awards, including three [[MTV Awards]] at the [[1998 MTV Video Music Awards]].<ref name=\"MTVAwards\"/>\n\n[[File:Hoxton Street 2002.jpg|thumb|left|[https://maps.google.com/maps?q=Hoxton+Street+and+Falkirk+Street,+London,+UK&layer=c&sll=51.530816,-0.080185&cbp=12,132.57,,0,3.63&cbll=51.530904,-0.080186&hl=en&ie=UTF8&hq&hnear=Hoxton+St,+London,+United+Kingdom&ll=51.530987,-0.080187&spn=0.003531,0.009613&t=m&z=17&vpsrc=0&panoid=PIfjU2v71G-KM1NP00FmaQ&output=classic&dg=brw Hoxton Street and Falkirk Street, London N1, UK; 2002]]]\nAshcroft starts walking from the southeast corner of the intersection of Hoxton and Falkirk Streets in [[Hoxton]] in the [[East End of London]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicpilgrimages.com/video/index.php?alias=video_bittersweet_symphony.html|title=musicpilgrimages.com: \"Music video - Bittersweet Symphony\"|publisher=}}</ref> subsequently proceeding north along the east side of Hoxton Street until he reaches Hoxton Gardens. He then crosses to the corner of Purcell Street and walks back the way he came, before being joined by the rest of the band at the corner of Crondall Street, opposite where he started.  The British comedy band [[Fat Les]] would later release a direct parody for their 1998 song \"[[Vindaloo (song)|Vindaloo]]\", an alternative anthem for England at the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]], where [[Paul Kaye]] takes the role of an Ashcroft look-alike who is mocked by a growing group of passers by as the video progresses.<ref>Irene Morra (2013). \"Britishness, Popular Music, and National Identity: The Making of Modern Britain\". p. 138. Routledge,</ref> In 2016, ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' named Hoxton Street in their list of the 54 locations that defined the Britpop era.<ref>{{cite news|title=54 locations that defined Britpop|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/europe/united-kingdom/articles/Britpop-On-the-trail-of-Blur-and-Oasis/|agency=The Telegraph|date=25 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Live 8==\nOn 2 July 2005, at the [[Live 8]] concert in [[Hyde Park, London|Hyde Park]], London, [[Coldplay]] invited Ashcroft to perform the song with them in their set. They played it after only one rehearsal in Crystal Palace. Ashcroft was introduced by [[Chris Martin]] as \"the best singer in the world\" and he described the song as \"the best song ever written\".<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.gigwise.com/news/14747/richard-ashcroft-married-to-chris-martin | title= Richard Ashcroft 'Married' To Chris Martin | work=Gigwise | date=19 March 2006 | accessdate=2 October 2019}}</ref> On 25 December 2005, a documentary entitled ''Live 8: A Bitter Sweet Symphony'' was aired reliving moments of the day featuring a portion of Ashcroft's performance as the music for the show's opening soundtrack.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0496339/ Live 8: A Bittersweet Symphony (TV 2005)] IMDb. Retrieved 10 March 2012</ref>\n\n==Accolades and legacy==\n{{Quote box|width=30%|align=right|quote=\u201cBitter Sweet Symphony\" is built on a slow-rolling fat beat, a pomp and circumstance violin loop and singer \"Mad\" Richard Ashcroft's elliptical, snake-swallowing-its-tail lyrics. It is an infectious, glorious piece of pop music.|source=\u2014Gil Kaufman writing for [[MTV]], September 1997<ref>{{cite news |title=The Verve Back With Bitter Sweet Hit |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1264/the-verve-back-with-bitter-sweet-hit/ |accessdate=25 May 2019 |agency=MTV}}</ref>}}\nRegarded as the band's signature song and one of the defining tracks and music videos of the [[Britpop]] era, \"Bitter Sweet Symphony\" has been featured in a number of best ever song lists and polls. It was named ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' and [[NME Single of the Year|''NME'' Single of the Year]] for 1997. In 1998, [[BBC Radio 1]] listeners voted it the third Best Track Ever.<ref>[http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/uk_radio.htm Radio 1 - Best Tracks Ever] Rock List.net. Retrieved 10 February 2012</ref> The same year, it was named the third-best single of 1997 by New York City weekly ''[[The Village Voice]]''{{'}}s [[Pazz & Jop]] annual critics' poll. In a 2005 [[Channel 4]] poll, the music video was ranked eighth on their list of the [[100 Greatest (TV series)|100 Greatest Pop Videos]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itnsource.com/en/shotlist/ITVProgs/2005/02/06/Y09420007/ |title=100 Greatest ... (The 100 Greatest Pop Videos) |publisher=[[ITN Source]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150221233131/http://www.itnsource.com/en/shotlist/ITVProgs/2005/02/06/Y09420007/ |archivedate=21 February 2015 |url-status=dead |accessdate=31 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, ''[[NME]]'' magazine placed the song at number 18 in its list of the \"50 Greatest Indie Anthems Ever\".<ref>[http://www.nme.com/news/nme/28059 The Greatest Indie Anthems Ever - Numbers 30-11], NME.com. Accessed on 23 June 2007.</ref> In September 2007, a poll of 50 songwriters in ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' magazine placed it in a list of the \"Top 10 Greatest Tracks\".<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6972837.stm Songwriters reveal top 10 tracks] BBC News. Retrieved 31 August 2007</ref> In the Australian [[Triple J Hottest 100 of All Time, 2009]], the track was voted the 14th best song of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/triplej/hottest100_alltime/countdown/cd_14.htm |title=Countdown &#124; Hottest 100 - Of All Time &#124; triple j |publisher=Abc.net.au |date= |accessdate=11 February 2012}}</ref> [[Pitchfork Media]] included the song at number 29 on their \"Top 200 Tracks of the 90s\" list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/7852-the-top-200-tracks-of-the-1990s-50-21/3/|title=The Top 200 Tracks of the 1990s: 50-21 - Page 3 - Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com}}</ref> The publication also included it in its collection of ''[[The Pitchfork 500]]''.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Plagenhoef |editor1-first=Scott |editor2-last=Schreiber |editor2-first=Ryan |date=November 2008 |title=[[The Pitchfork 500]] |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |pages=143\u2013144 |isbn=978-1-4165-6202-3 }}</ref> In 2011, ''NME'' placed it at number 9 on its list \"150 Best Tracks of the Past 15 Years\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/list/150-best-tracks-of-the-past-15-years/248648/page/15 |title=150 Best Tracks Of The Past 15 Years |publisher=Nme.Com |date=30 April 1997 |accessdate=4 January 2012}}</ref> Despite the band having half a dozen hits, the song featured at number one in ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]'' magazine's poll of its 25 \"awesome one-hit wonders of the 1990s\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/lists/2011/09/25-awesome-one-hit-wonders-of-the-1990s.html?p=3|title=25 Awesome One-Hit Wonders of the 1990s|magazine=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|last=Barrett|first=John|date=28 September 2011|accessdate=29 May 2013}}</ref> In 2015, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' readers voted it the third greatest Britpop song in a poll (after \"[[Common People]]\" by [[Pulp (band)|Pulp]] and \"[[Don't Look Back in Anger]]\" by [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]]).<ref>{{cite news|title=Readers' Poll: The 10 Best Brit-Pop Songs|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/readers-poll-the-10-best-britpop-songs-20150513/oasis-dont-look-back-in-anger-20150513|agency=Rolling Stone|date=25 March 2018}}</ref> In 2004, it was ranked at number 392 on ''Rolling Stone''\u2019s list of \"[[The 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]]\".<ref name=\"500songs\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/the-500-greatest-songs-of-all-time-20110407/the-verve-bitter-sweet-symphony-19691231|title=500 Greatest Songs of All Time|magazine=Rolling Stone|accessdate=22 August 2011}}</ref> According to [[Acclaimed Music]], it is the 63rd most celebrated song in popular music history.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/song/S1.htm |title=Bitter Sweet Symphony ranked 63rd most celebrated song|work=Acclaimed Music|access-date=15 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Cover versions==\n[[File:Beyonce If I Were a Boy 2013.jpg|thumb|Beyonc\u00e9 performing a mash-up of \"If I Were a Boy\" and \"Bitter Sweet Symphony\" during The Mrs. Carter Show World Tour, 2013]]\n* American recording artist [[Beyonc\u00e9]] [[Mashup (music)|mashed]] the song with her own \"[[If I Were a Boy]]\" during the [[set list]] of her [[The Mrs. Carter Show World Tour]] (2013). The string motif of \"Bitter Sweet Symphony\" was used during the performances.<ref name=\"nmelist\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/beyonce/70022|title=Beyonc\u00e9 makes nod to The Verve at London's O2 Arena|work=[[NME]]|publisher=[[IPC Media]]|date=30 April 2013|accessdate=9 July 2013|archiveurl=http://www.freezepage.com/1373081154GBKXJTDAND?url=http://www.nme.com/news/beyonce/70022|archivedate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Nu metal]] band [[Limp Bizkit]] also mashed this with their cover of \"[[Home Sweet Home (M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce song)|Home Sweet Home]]\" by [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]], with \"[[Home Sweet Home/Bittersweet Symphony]]\".\n* A version recorded at the BBC by [[London Grammar]] appears on the deluxe version of the album ''[[Truth Is a Beautiful Thing]]'' (2017).\n\n==In popular culture==\n* The song played on ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode \"[[That '90s Show]]\".<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OAYH0ldYrtI The Simpsons - \"That 90's Show\" (Season 19, and episode 11)] Fox. Retrieved 25 March 2018</ref>\n* The song was used at the end of the film ''[[Cruel Intentions]]'' and was included on the [[Cruel Intentions (soundtrack)|soundtrack]]''.<ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/album/cruel-intentions-r398838 Cruel Intentions OST] All Music. Retrieved 25 March 2018</ref>\n*Since 2008, the song has been used by [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] as the background music to the opening sequence for [[England national football team|England]]'s international football matches; including the qualifiers for the [[FIFA World Cup]].<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/richard-ashcroft---from-urban-hymns-to-united-nations-2050935.html \"Richard Ashcroft - From urban hymns to united nations\"]. ''The Independent''. Retrieved 25 March 2018</ref> In 2019, following the settling of the songwriting dispute with the Stones, Ashcroft stated, \u201cI can sit back and watch England... and finally just enjoy the moment.\"<ref name=\"Dispute over\"/>\n*The song was covered by [[Ashleigh Murray]] & [[Camila Mendes]] for the ''[[Riverdale (2017 TV series)|Riverdale]]'' season 2 episode \"Chapter Twenty-Five: The Wicked and the Divine\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cwtv.com/shows/riverdale/|title=Riverdale|last=|first=|date=|website=The CW|accessdate=28 April 2018}}</ref>\n*The song was used during the final scene and outro credits of ''[[My Dinner with Herv\u00e9]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hbo.com/movies/my-dinner-with-herve|title=My Dinner with Herv\u00e9|website=HBO|language=en|access-date=2018-10-22}}</ref>\n*\"Bitter Sweet Symphony\" serves as the title theme for the [[Investigation Discovery]] series ''The 1990s: The Deadliest Decade''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.investigationdiscovery.com/tv-shows/1990s-the-deadliest-decade/|title=1990s: The Deadliest Decade {{!}} Watch Full Episodes & More!|website=Investigation Discovery|language=en-us|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref>\n* The song was used at the end of the film ''[[The Death and Life of John F. Donovan]]'' by Canadian filmmaker [[Xavier Dolan]].<ref>[http://collider.com/the-death-and-life-of-john-f-donovan-review/ \"'The Death and Life of John F. Donovan' Review: A Hot Mess | TIFF 2018\"]. ''Collider''. Retrieved 7 February 2019</ref>\n\n==Track listings==\nCD 1 {{small|HUTDG 82}}\n#\"Bitter Sweet Symphony\" (original) \u2013 6:00\n#\"Lord I Guess I'll Never Know\" \u2013 4:51\n#\"Country Song\" \u2013 7:50\n#\"Bitter Sweet Symphony\" (radio edit) \u2013 4:35\n\nCD 2 {{small|HUTDX 82}}\n#\"Bitter Sweet Symphony\" (extended version) \u2013 7:52\n#\"So Sister\" \u2013 4:11\n#\"Echo Bass\" \u2013 6:39\n\nCassette {{small|HUTC 82}}\n#\"Bitter Sweet Symphony\" (radio edit) \u2013 4:35\n#\"Lord I Guess I'll Never Know\" \u2013 4:51\n\n7\" {{small|HUTLH 82}}\n#\"Bitter Sweet Symphony\" (radio edit) \u2013 4:35\n#\"Lord I Guess I'll Never Know\" \u2013 4:51\n\n12\" {{small|HUTT 82}}\n#\"Bitter Sweet Symphony (original) \u2013 6:00\n#\"Lord I Guess I'll Never Know\" \u2013 4:51\n#\"Bitter Sweet Symphony\" (James Lavelle Remix)\n#\"Country Song\" \u2013 7:50\